[White "Introduction and Background of this Repertoire"]
[Black "Introduction and The Philosophy of the Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ Welcome to this repertoire!     Let me tell you a bit about it, about how it was created, was goals I have set to accomplish while writing and the philosophy behind it.    This is my fifth Chessable repertoire overall and my first full White opening repertoire.    During six or so last years, I have been extensively coaching, primarily focusing on teaching club players, which is why I have written two 1.e4-oriented repertoires, namely The Dynamic Italian and The Accelerated Rossolimo.    However, my main expertise as a player has always been closed positions: in particular, 1.Nf3.  This, alongside with the fact my full Black repertoire The Accelerated Queen's Indian got some absolutely overwhelmingly positive feedback for its flexibility, simplicity in use and in learning, led me to the desire to create a full White repertoire based on 1.Nf3, almost at all times followed by 2.b3.    The repertoire in question aims to copy the setups I have used with Black in the Accelerated Queen's Indian, massively benefiting from the fact we are a full tempo up.   Of course, things are not that simple, because Black in the Queen's Indian is often happy to reach safe equality, while with White we certainly want a lot more.   That's why in some of the lines, especially in the Slav, we choose to go for some very new, creative, fresh and ambitious continuations, which don't look like the Queen's Indian at all.    However, in most cases, such as while playing against 1...d5 followed by 2...c5, against the King's Indian, against the English with 1...c5 or 1...Nf6 and 2...c5, against the Queen's Indian, and in many other situations, we aim to repeat what Black does in my AQID repertoire, looking to benefit from an extra move, which is an approach that tends to work rather well, in my understanding.   This happens to be a very positional repertoire; in most cases, based on pawn structures, ideas and plans.  Why did I construct it that way? Well, having spent so many years and thousands of hours teaching club players, I know that no one below a very high level needs tons of specific details and lengthy 20+ move-long sequences. The amateurs neither can memorize them, nor do they have the need to do so, as most of their mistakes are made in the middlegame and endgame and are based on a lack of understanding of positional plans, pawn structures, and so on.  That is why this repertoire has more than 30 model games which are analyzed in great detail, and equally importantly, a chapter on the typical pawn structures you will be arriving at, such as positions with an isolated queen's pawn, with and against hanging pawns, with a symmetrical center with d and c-pawns gone, and so on.     I wholeheartedly believe that studying the pawn structures and plans will be of MUCH better benefit for everyone below 2300 or so FIDE, as that will improve your understanding of the game overall while making it a lot easier for you to understand and remember specific sequences as well, as you will have a much better comprehension of what we and the opponent are playing for.    On another note, I need to say my chess style and taste has been greatly affected and shaped by positional and strategic players such as Ulf Andersson, Anatoly Karpov, Tigran Petrosian and other players of this kind. That is why in many cases we will have balanced endgames, instead of crazy complications.   Sometimes, that means we might not get an advantage, and sometimes it might mean with perfect play Black will be able to reach a draw.   However, if we understand that chess is a balanced game, instead of something where we're guaranteed to win no matter what, we should be okay with such an approach.    Finally, I have also consulted several leading opening books, courses and repertoires to understand how to challenge the recommendations of other leading authors, and for more details on that, please take a look at the chapter Repertoire Clashes.    The result of this extensive research is this repertoire, which has 60 000 words of instruction, with a major amount of this volume created by the annotated games and analysis of typical pawn structures, and less than 300 trainable variations.   A very easy repertoire to pick as White without spending centuries on memorization, but ambitious enough for titled players like myself to pose problems to Black in serious games - or, at least, I have been able to do so rather often for most of my personal chess career. }
*

