1. Nf3
{ While I have stated several times that the main goal of this course was to give you a coherent easy-to-learn repertoire, similar to the one on the Accelerated Queen's Indian for Black, but with colors reversed, so that you would be able to play chess without drowning in theory, while enjoying the familiar positions and learning the classical pawn structures, it does not mean that we are throwing our opening ambitions and aspirations to get an advantage away.   That's why, of course, it was crucial for me to check the work of other authors who wrote Black repertoires on all kinds of openings: Slav, King's Indian, Queen's Gambit, Dutch and whatnot, and see if it's possible to find improvements, new ideas, or any other kinds of challenges.   Here are the works I've consulted and here is how this repertoire compares to them:     1@@EndBracket@@ Sam Shankland: Black vs the English, Reti and sidelines.  Shankland has published a lot of Chessable courses recently and proved himself as a strong analyst and a capable talented author. It is certainly not unreasonable to assume a lot of people would use his course to prepare with Black and try to neutralize our opening. So, what's going on there? He transposes to our repertoire from a sequence @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.b3  (hi, #b3cowboys!)  1...d5  2.Bb2  Bf5  3.e3  e6  4.Nf3  Nf6  . Here, I suggest the rare move  5.Nh4  , which he does mention, but he goes on to dismiss it, claiming that after  5...Bg4  White needs to go back  6.Nf3  , so the setup doesn't make sense.   The database finds 66 games that saw 5.Nh4, and of course, White never wanted a draw: he went 6.Nf3 in one game only. Instead, our repertoire suggestion 6.Be2 was tried by Nakamura in five games, by Nihal Sarin, by Eric Hansen, and by a number of other strong players.   I certainly believe Black is able to equalize in that line, but I also believe White has great chances of developing initiative and getting a very easy game, unless Black really knows what he's doing and is comfortable in a variety of structures, such as the Reversed Benoni, Reversed Dutch/Queen's Indian, typical Slav, etc. We also analyze some model games from that position to make sure we get a good knowledge of plans. So, with that repertoire, I think we succeed and the ball is in Black's court.   2@@EndBracket@@ Mikhalevski: Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings.  3@@EndBracket@@ Kornev: Practical Black Repertoire with d5, c6.   I have placed these two books next to each other, as they both recommend an identical move order and sequence, and that is @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.e3  Nf6  3.b3  Bg4  .   However, after  4.h3  Bh5  5.Bb2  e6  their recommendations fall short, as we opt for the plan with an immediate aggressive g-pawn push: g2-g4 and g4-g5. Unfortunately, Mikhalevski fails to consider the inclusion of h2-h3 as something relevant, and, as a result, does not analyze our plan.  Instead, Kornev does mention the g2-g4 push but fails to analyze the immediate g4-g5, which is understandable, as that move has only been tried in four games so far, and they were played after the books were published.  That is excellent news for us, as it means no one expects our setup, which is by no means harmless: it was primarily used by Artemiev, and the novelty I came up with, which offers an exchange sacrifice, is one of the most exciting ideas I have come up with while preparing this course. So, it looks like another success for us.  4@@EndBracket@@ Kamil Plichta: Kings Indian: Too Hot To Handle.  Plichta is one of the most popular Chessable authors, known for his aggressive suggestions and dynamic repertoires.  He wrote the course on KID with a lot of passion and effort, but he did not consider our plan and move order with b2-b3 and e2-e3.  5@@EndBracket@@ Kotronias: Five Volumes on King's Indian.  This is another example of a very strong, famous and diligent author focusing on the 1.d4 move orders, and as a result, he ignores our move order and plan.  6@@EndBracket@@ Nikola Sedlak: Playing the Stonewall.   The author goes in great depth about nuances of handling the proper Stonewall, but starts with the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  e6  and doesn't analyze the sidelines, such as  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Bg5  , or  1.d4  f5  2.Nc3  .  The move order  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  f5  2.d4  is also not considered, which means we get another easy pass.   7@@EndBracket@@ Yuriy Krykun: The Accelerated Queen's Indian.  Oh boy, this one is tough! It was by no means easy to write a repertoire on the Evans Gambit for White after writing a repertoire on 1.e4 e5 for Black.  In my opening of choice for Black, Queen's Indian, the very symmetrical positions tend to arise.  I believe that they are equal, however, we went into great detail discussing the plans, ideas, traps, typical pawn structures: in fact, we even spent a while analyzing various arising positions in the chapter on pawn structures. Furthermore, the chapter on model games should be of even more help. These are the positions that better players win for either side, and I don't see a reason to be disappointed, as players who don't know as many ideas and plans are guaranteed to get outplayed.  All in all, while in many, if not most, principled theoretical mainlines Black is able to equalize, I am very satisfied with the result of the research done for this repertoire, because a lot of fresh ideas have been found, novelties between moves 5-10. Most importantly, I believe we have an idea-based repertoire which is easy to play and enjoy, and of course, Black still often has to navigate complex theoretical jungles to get out of the opening safe. Hopefully, we've challenged the existing research of many leading theoreticians, who don't seem to have caught on to some of the latest trends. }
