{ In the last example, I've told you White is looking to trade the minor pieces and then blockade the isolated pawn and attack it with his major pieces. Now, a fair question arises: once we did that, then what? Here, we have a very strong idea, please find it. }
1. e4 { White wins a pawn, because the d5-pawn is pinned. } 1... g6
{ Instead, if Black just plays some move, we pick up the pawn.   1...dxe4??  2.Rxd7+-  And we win a rook and the game. }
2. Rxd5 Rxd5 3. Rxd5 Rxd5 4. exd5
{ With a nearly winning endgame. It might still take work to convert, but we are just a healthy pawn up, which is a pretty great outcome, if you ask me.   4.Qxd5?  Would be a mistake, however, because the Black king is too close to the pawn.  4...Qxd5  5.exd5  Kf8  6.Kf1  Ke7  7.Ke2  Kd6  8.Kd3  Kxd5=  And we wasted all the advantage. }
