[SetUp "1"]

{ The next most common structure after the IQP positions is the position with hanging pawns.   Unlike the IQP, which we mostly play against, positions with hanging pawns are something we both get and play against in this course.    Of course, it is worth mentioning the IQP position can easily transpose into a position with hanging pawns, for example, if Black has an isolated d5-pawn and then we take his knight on c6, to which he responds with ...bxc6.    What are the pros and cons?    The advantages look the following way:   1@@EndBracket@@ Just like an IQP, hanging pawns control a lot of space, and in fact, they control a lot more squares: for example, in the position in front of us, they control the squares on b4, c4, d4 and e4.   2@@EndBracket@@ Unlike the IQP, the hanging pawns cannot be blockaded nearly as easily: for example, the d4-square is no longer an outpost.   3@@EndBracket@@ Since they cannot be blockaded, at an appropriate moment they can advance, which could be rather beneficial. For instance, imagine a black bishop on b7 and queen on c6, blocked by the d5-pawn. Once that pawn goes to d4, especially if that happens with a tempo, Black might end up checkmating White on the long diagonal.    However, there are also downsides.    Just like an IQP, it is easy to attack the hanging pawns on the c and d-file with Rac1 and Rfd1, for example.    While Black can try to time the advance of one of the pawns, which will unleash the pieces behind them, a poorly timed or forced pawn advance could also be very beneficial to White, as it would weaken some squares.   For example, if the c-pawn moved to c4, the d4-square would become weak.   That is why one of the most common plans for White involves preparing b3-b4 or e3-e4, forcing the advance of one of the pawns.    But overall, if the pawns are positioned properly on c5 and d5, it is correct to say that in 99% of the cases it is better for the side with the hanging pawns to have them rather than the IQP. However, that is not true if the pawns are placed poorly, such as on d5 and c6, because White might be able to blockade the pawns and install his pieces on the gorgeous outposts on d4 and c5.     Also, overall it is fair to say the side who has the hanging pawns wants to keep the pieces on the board, because they are a dynamic advantage and a static weakness. }
1. Kf1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "Hanging Pawns, Example 1 -  when hanging pawn are bad"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/pbn1bppp/5n2/2pp2B1/Q7/P1N2NP1/1P2PPBP/R2R2K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here we see an example of a position with hanging pawns that did not go great for Black. Why is that? The good part is that he has pawns on c5 and d5, which is much better than a scenario when his c-pawn is on c6 and the White piece, typically the knight, landed on c5, blockading the pawns, because it looks like his pawns could advance.   However, the truth is that the Black pieces are very far from what we call active, and the pawns are now rather vulnerable. }
1. Ne5
{ This move opens up the g2-bishop, which means the d5-pawn is under even more pressure. Furthermore, at some point White could go Nc6, taking the bishop pair. }
1... Qd6
{ 1...h6  2.Bxf6  Bxf6  3.Nd7!  would be very strong, forking the f8-rook, the f6-bishop and the c5-pawn.  3...Re8  4.Nxc5+-  With a technically winning position where we are just a pawn up. }
2. Nc4
{ The knight is coming to a5 to put pressure on one of Black's key defenders, the b7-bishop. This is even more tempting because it comes with a tempo on the Black queen. }
2... Qa6 3. Na5 Rad8
{ Black managed to defend the pawn for now, but his position remains terrible in the long run.   3...h6  If Black were to ignore our threats, we would win very easily.  4.Bxf6!  Bxf6  5.Nxb7  Qxb7  6.Nxd5  Nxd5  7.Bxd5  And White picks the pawn and the exchange. }
4. Nxb7
{ 4.Bf4!?  Ne6  5.Nxb7  Qxb7  6.Be5±  Is also very strong, looking to eliminate the f6-knight and win the d5-pawn. }
4... Qxb7 5. Rd2
{ White doubles on the d-file while also defending the b2-pawn. } 5... Qb6 6.
Qc2
{ Now, the threat is to distract the e7-bishop with Bxf6 and play Na4!, winning the c5-pawn.   6.Bxf6  Would have also been very strong, obtaining a dominant position after the forced sequence  6...Bxf6  7.Nxd5  Nxd5  8.Bxd5  Bxb2  9.Rb1  The only problem that prevents White from winning a piece is that Black has  9...Qf6!!  10.Rbxb2  Rxd5!  And the b2-rook ends up hanging. However, the simple  11.Qxa7±  Gives White an extra pawn and a nearly winning position. But, instead of pulling the trigger, he chose to wait. }
6... d4
{ Black feels it's necessary to push the pawn to avoid losing it, but as we can see, this advance weakens the c5-pawn and the c4-square.   6...Rfe8  7.Bxf6!  Bxf6  8.Na4±  Wins the c5-pawn. }
7. Na4 Qa5 8. Bxf6
{ Black is forced to take with the g-pawn, which terribly weakens his king. }
8... gxf6 9. Rad1 Ne6 10. Qc4
{ White blockaded the pawns and is about to either attack the Black king after Be4!-Bb1-Qd3!, or play e2-e3 at an appropriate moment, undermining the pawns. Later on, he went on to win a brilliant positional game. Dorfman-Romanishin, USSR 1981. }
