[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "Hanging Pawns, Example  2 - what NOT to do with hanging pawns"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
{ I am making these moves up to show how a position with hanging pawns can be misplayed. }
4. e3 O-O 5. Nf3 c5 6. Bd3 d5 7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. Bxc4
{ This is common Nimzo-Indian theory. } 9... b6
{ However, here let's suppose White doesn't know what to do, provokes a position with hanging pawns and then starts playing poorly. }
10. a3 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Ba6
{ Black benefits from trading pieces, as it decreases the dynamic potential of White's position. }
12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Re1
{ It would have been better to pin the knight with Bg5, but our assumption is that White plays passive moves. }
13... h6 { Black prevents Bg5 for good. } 14. h3
{ White keeps playing passively. } 14... Rc8 { Time to target the pawns. } 15.
Bb2 Nb8 { The knight is getting re-routed to c4 via c6-a5. } 16. Rc1 Nc6
{ Now, c3-c4! would be necessary, even though the pawns would still be weak. But let's suppose White keeps waiting. }
17. Qd2 Na5 18. Qd3 Nc4 19. Rc2 Qd5
{ This is a perfect example of what the side that has hanging pawns should NEVER do. As we can see, the pawns got blockaded, now the b2-bishop is terrible and the outposts on c4 and d5 are being put to very good use. Later, Black will improve the position with ... Rfd8, maybe ...b7-b5, etc.  At some point, he might take the b2-bishop, if that would enable him to win the c3-pawn. White is certainly not having fun! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "Hanging Pawns, Example 3 - what to do when you have them (Nimzowitsch vs. Tarrasch, 1914)"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r1rk1/p3qp1p/2bb2p1/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/PBQn1PPP/2R2RK1 w - - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

18. Nxd2
{ This example is rather famous, but it won't hurt to look at it again to reinforce our understanding of the dynamic component of positions with hanging pawns. As we can see, both Black bishops are aimed at the kingside, which has no defenders. However, the c6-bishop isn't particularly useful right now. So... }
18... d4 { Time to put that bishop to work! } 19. exd4 Bxh2+
{ The now famous double bishop sacrifice. } 20. Kxh2 Qh4+
{ The Black queen comes closer. } 21. Kg1 Bxg2
{ The king shelter is meant to be destroyed! } 22. f3
{ White tries to create an escape square and run away via f2 in the event of ...Qh1+.   22.Kxg2?  Qg4+  23.Kh2  Rd5  Will either result in White getting mated on the next turn, or after  24.Qxc5□  Rxc5  25.dxc5  Qf4+  Black would also win the knight on d2, keeping the attack going and achieving a decisive material advantage. }
22... Rfe8 { Black takes the e-file away from White. } 23. Ne4 Qh1+ 24. Kf2
Bxf1 { The point is that White cannot recapture. } 25. d5
{ 25.Rxf1?  Qh2+  and Black picks the free queen on the next move.   25.Nf6+  Kg7  26.Nxe8+  Rxe8  27.dxc5+  Kg8-+  and White no longer has checks, whereas ... Qg2+ cannot be stopped. }
25... f5 { Making room for the king. } 26. Qc3
{ White has threats of his own as well, but Black is much faster. } 26... Qg2+
27. Ke3 Rxe4+ 28. fxe4 f4+ { Time to send that king on a walk. } 29. Kxf4 Rf8+
30. Ke5 Qh2+ 31. Ke6 Re8+ 32. Kd7 Bb5#
{ Black wins by checkmate. This is definitely not just a very beautiful game and a game that teaches us a famous attacking pattern - the double bishop sacrifice - but also a game that shows how the dynamic potential of the hanging pawns can be easily revealed. }
