[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "Symmetrical Structure: no c and d pawns "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/p4ppp/1p2p3/8/8/1P2P3/P4PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here is another structure that we are going to see A LOT in this repertoire, primarily in the positions arising from the Queen's Indian, Queen's Gambit, the Grunfeld and the Double Fianchetto.    The pawns can be placed slightly differently: for example, the White pawns could instead be on b4 and a3, or b5 and a4, or instead the Black queenside pawns could be more advanced.    It is very likely the b-pawns won't be on their initial positions: after all, we are nearly always playing 2.b3!  What general ideas can we learn and use in these structures?   There are quite a few:   1@@EndBracket@@ When the b2-b3 or ... b7-b6 moves are played, the c3 and c6 squares become really weak. That means playing b4-b5 and installing the knight on c6 can be extremely strong.   2@@EndBracket@@ Since Black weakened the c6-square, it is usually very useful to play Be2-f3 to trade off his light-squared bishop, which will facilitate the idea of installing some piece, such as a knight or a rook, on c6. Of course, the opposite holds true for Black as well.   3@@EndBracket@@ It is often really good to place the queen on a1, or for Black, on a8. That is because the long diagonal is a good place for a queen and bishop battery to be, as the g7 and g2-pawns could end up under a lot of pressure, and because it's crucial to control even better the aforementioned squares on c3 and c6.   4@@EndBracket@@ Often, the move b3-b4 is rather tempting, as it takes away the c5-square from the Black knight or rook, and often it wins a tempo. While often a good idea, you need to keep in mind that placing the pawn on a dark square means your dark-squared bishop becomes inferior, which is fine, but then trading it off is a more attractive idea than before.   5@@EndBracket@@ In the event you are fighting for the c-file, for instance when things get closer to the endgame, it's worth remembering the key maneuver that can enable us to win that battle: Ba6!, taking the c8-square under control. Of course, the opposite holds true, and Black can often go ...Ba3! as well.   6@@EndBracket@@ On the way to this position, when there could still be pawns on c4 and d4 for White and on c5 and d5 for Black, usually it's better to keep the tension and have your opponent capture your pawns rather than take yourself. Why? Because when the opponent takes, it activates your pieces. Imagine your knights on d2 and f3; Black takes on c4, you take with the knight. Black takes on d4, you take with the knight. As these two moves got played, your knights are a lot more active!   7@@EndBracket@@ If someone has a bishop on the long diagonal, for example Black has a bishop on b7, especially in the endgame, often f2-f3! and e3-e4! comes in very handy, restricting that piece.   These are the main ideas that come to mind, and while there are certainly more, I believe being aware of those should make your life a great deal easier. }
1. -- *

