[SetUp "1"]

{ The opening of this game saw me terribly misplay the Catalan with White. Black has the bishop pair and the much more active pieces, now his knight is on its way to c3 via d5. }
17. a5
{ This only helps the opponent.   17.e4∓  would have restricted the b6-knight and enabled me to hold on for a while, even though White is clearly worse, obviously. But I showed a lack of prophylactical thinking. }
17... Nd5 18. Ne4 Qe7 19. a6 Ba8 20. Nxc5
{ I was glad to deprive the opponent of the bishop pair, but as it turns out, he doesn't need it to win. }
20... Nc3 { A nice intermediate move. } 21. Qc2 Qxc5 22. Rfe1 Rfd8 23. e3
{ And here, Black made a wonderful positional move. } 23... Bxf3
{ That bishop on a8 looked really good, but the whole point is that the c3-knight is now never going to be challenged, while that White light-squared bishop is absolutely useless. }
24. Bxf3 Rd6
{ Black is preparing to double on the d-file with ...Rcd8 and invade on d2.  I, on the other hand, cannot ever contest the file with Rd1 due to that powerful c3-knight. }
25. Rac1 Rcd8
{ And I resigned here as ...Rd2 is unstoppable. Black is about to trap the white queen, or follow up with ...Qf5 at some point, harassing the bishop and the f2-pawn.   Maybe I should have played on, but at this point, Black is completely winning. This is certainly a good lesson on how NOT to play such positions, which I have hopefully learned, and a great game for my opponent, who was the strongest Ukrainian U-16 player at the time @@StartBracket@@this game was played in a Ukrainian Championship U-16@@EndBracket@@ and a few years later became a strong grandmaster. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "Miroslav Tosic  vs. Yuriy Krykun"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/pb1nbpp1/1p2p2p/3n4/1P6/P2BPN2/1B1N1PPP/RQ3RK1 w - - 0 14"]
[SetUp "1"]

14. Nc4
{ In a game I played versus the Serbian GM Tosic 5 years ago, the following position arose. Objectively, the situation is balanced, but both parties have some advantages and problems. For one, White has a bit more space, which is great. However, his queen is somewhat misplaced on b1, as the a1-rook is stuck. Not having enough space, Black needed to figure out what to do with his queen and f8-rook, which is something I failed to solve properly. }
14... Ba6
{ A positional mistake. I thought the bishop would put pressure on the c4-knight, but in fact, it ends up not doing anything useful there.  Not only that, but also the bishop is about to be rather vulnerable.   14...Rc7!  Would have been the right path, following the recommendation from one of the previous lines with guidelines on how to handle this structure: the queen belongs on a8, on the long White diagonal! }
15. Rc1 Bf6
{ I was looking to trade the dark-squared bishops, so as to use the c3-square. }
16. Nd4
{ 16.Bxf6  N7xf6  Was the idea, preparing to simply go ...Qe7 and ...Rfd8, for example. }
16... Rc7
{ Finally, I got on the right track, preparing ...Qb8 or ...Qa8.   16...Bb7?  17.Nb5!  Would be a problem, threatening both the a7-pawn and the invasion on d6.  17...a6  18.Nbd6±  With a large positional advantage.   16...Nb8?  Would prevent the invasion on c6, but now the knight is placed very passively.  17.b5  Bb7  18.Bh7+!  Before bringing the bishop on e4, it's useful to worsen Black king's position.  18...Kh8  19.Be4↑  Now, it's hard to say what the knight on b8 should do. If it ever moves, the c4-knight will invade on d6. While the position is by no means disastrous, it looks like White is clearly pressing. }
17. Bf1 Qa8
{ The second chance wasted: it was crucial to NOT give up the light-squared bishop.   17...Qb8!  Would have been a lot better, keeping the d6-square under control, which would have proven crucial in the following line.  18.b5  Bb7  19.a4   19.Nd6??  Rxc1!  And Black wins the d6-knight.  19...Rfc8  Black simply doubles up on the c-file.  20.a5  Ne7⩱  Now, ...Bd5! is about to be played, putting pressure on the c4-knight. Black is clearly somewhat more active and has no issues whatsoever. }
18. b5 Bb7 19. Nd6
{ White grabs the bishop pair and obtains a long-lasting edge. } 19... Nc5
{ Now that even the rooks don't get traded, Black's position is becoming even more difficult, as he has no space.   19...Rxc1!  Would have at least enabled me to somewhat simplify the position, making the defense easier.  20.Qxc1  Ne7  21.Nxb7  Qxb7  22.a4  Rc8⩲  White is slightly better due to bishops and the c6-square, but this is certainly by no means the end of the world. }
20. a4 { White keeps grabbing space. } 20... Qd8 21. Nxb7 Nxb7 22. Nc6
{ And White obtained full domination. Importantly, the move ...Qd7 that I had planned far in advance is not something Black can afford. }
22... Qa8
{ Now, unlike before, when the queen was active on the long diagonal, it's blocked by the c6-knight. Black's position is atrocious.   22...Qd7?  is bad due to  23.Bxf6  Nxf6  24.Rd1+-  And White wins the a7-pawn. }
23. Bxf6 Nxf6 24. g3
{ Now, the bishop is coming to g2. White is dominating, and it's only due to my opponent's careless play that I managed to save the game. I think this example definitely shows the value of the outpost on c6 and the long diagonals! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The KID Structure: c4 vs d6"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/ppp2p1p/3p2p1/8/2P5/1P2P3/P4PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here is another pawn structure you will be seeing a lot in the King's Indian, when your opponent will be rushing to play ...e7-e5 and White's d-pawn and Black's e-pawn will disappear.    I hold a very firm and strong opinion that this structure is EXTREMELY favorable for White, and that is for the following reasons: We can install the knight on d5. Black would have to either tolerate that knight for the rest of game, which does not sound appealing at all, or he'll need to go ...c7-c6.   If that happens, the d6-pawn will become substantially weak, allowing White to hunt it with simple moves like Rad1, etc. Once the knight is on d5, White can often proceed with e3-e4 and f2-f4, ideally looking to trade the dark-squared bishops, install the queen on the a1-h8 diagonal and threaten some nasty checks like Nf6+.  Potentially, White has c4-c5! ideas if Black is exposed on the d-file.   We will see a lot more examples that explain these points in the chapter on model games in the King's Indian. }
1. Kf1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "The Dutch Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/pp4pp/2p5/3p1p2/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Here is another pawn structure, this time a relatively infrequent one, typical of the Dutch positions in our course only.  As we can see, the primary difference between White and Black in this position is that the Black f-pawn had advanced, while White's one didn't.   This means the e5-square is weak, and White can use it as an outpost, while Black cannot say the same thing about the e4-square, because the piece on e4 can be kicked out with f2-f3! at any moment.   So, the question is which pieces should we trade and which ones should we keep? Clearly, Black's light-squared bishop is very restricted by his own pawns.   So, the main thing worth knowing is that we want to get a knight on e5 versus Black's light-squared bishop, that will likely be a winning endgame, or at least a significantly superior one. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Pawn Structures"]
[Black "2 vs 1 on the queenside"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "6k1/p4ppp/8/3pp3/8/1P2P3/P4PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This pawn structure is characterized by White having an extra queenside pawn on the b-file, while Black has an extra central pawn on the d-file.   Which pawn is better: the central one or the flank one? If such questions could be answered in an obvious non-debatable way, chess would be a boring game. So, it depends.   Luckily, there is a clear factor it depends on: the central pawns are a lot more useful in the middlegame, because they control a lot of central squares, grab space and restrict the opponent's pieces.   Besides, they can move at some point, letting the pieces behind them get new diagonals and squares: for example, moving the e5-pawn would open the h2-b8 diagonal and make the e5-square vacant for some pieces.   However, the queenside pawns are a lot more useful in the endgame, and that is because it's a lot harder for the opponent's pieces, especially the king, to deal with a remote b-pawn which is advancing than it is for White to deal with the d-pawn.   So, in this structure, the plan is very simple: trade all the major pieces down the c-file and go for the endgame, in which you are going to be better because of your outside passed pawn! A very simple plan, isn't it? I have a small admission to make: this is one of my favorite pawn structures of all times, as White's plan to trade pieces is extremely simple and understandable. 😊   This structure is super common in the actual Queen's Indian for Black, but is not as frequent in this White repertoire, however you can still see it every now and then, for example in the chapter on the Anti-English, where the positions resemble the Grunfeld Reversed, and in the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.e3  c5  3.b3  Nc6  4.Bb2  f6  . }
1. b4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Reversed Queen's Indian #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3, and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least committal move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 Nc6 5. Bb5
{ This is a reversed Nimzo. I believe the system isn't particularly dangerous even when played with White, a tempo up, so no wonder here Black is going to be under even more pressure. }
5... Bd7 6. O-O a6 7. Bxc6
{ Importantly, we don't mind giving up the bishop pair here. First of all, this is a temporarily concession, as our next move is going to be Ne5 and we will surely get the bishop pair back. But also, retreating would mean losing precious time, which is why we are so delighted to capture. }
7... Bxc6 8. Ne5 Rc8 9. d3
{ Now, Nd2 is about to be played. Later, we can follow up either with the classic f2-f4, Ndf3, Qe2, etc, or the more fresh c2-c4. }
9... e6 10. Nd2 Be7 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Nxc6 Rxc6 13. e4
{ Is another very interesting plan. The point, of course, is to challenge the strong d5-pawn and make Black define the situation in the center. }
13... d4
{ In my opinion, this is premature as it gives White a free hand on the kingside. }
14. a4
{ First, we grab some space, making sure . .. b7-b5 is made difficult, since playing ...b7-b5 will give White an open a-file. }
14... b5
{ Now, we have an opportunity to pursue some kingside activity with f2-f4, Nf3, etc, but there is another curious plan, which I like even better. }
15. Ra2
{ Later, we will follow up with Rfa1, making Black uncomfortable about the fact that the a-file can open up at any point. For example, after }
15... Qc7 16. Rfa1
{ Alternatively, if Black were to close the game on the queenside with ...b5-b4, White would be happy to switch to the kingside play with Rf1, Ra1-e1, Bc1, f2-f4, and so on. }
16... Rb8 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bc1
{ White is ready to improve his passive b2-bishop with g2-g3, Nf3, Bf4 or Bg5. He is also owning the only open file, which means Black always has to keep his guard up as Ra7 or Ra8 might hurt at some point. White is definitely very comfortable here! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Reversed Queen's Indian #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3, and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least committal move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 Bf5
{ With colours reversed, there is a system named after the great British player Anthony Miles that sees such moves as Bf4 and e2-e3. However, without a tempo, I don't have any trust in this system whatsoever, as the early bishop sortie weakens the queenside, which is highlighted distinctively by White's next move. }
5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. Be2
{ Please remember this unexpected cheeky novelty of mine! What's the point? There are quite a few of them. 1We want to grab the bishop pair with Nh4 without running into ... Bg4. 2We would like to strike with c2-c4, undermining Black's center when he's barely developed, without having to run into the ugly ...a7-a6, when the b5-bishop would be somewhat striped of retreat possibilities. }
6... e6 7. Nh4 { As promised, we go after the bishop pair. } 7... Bg6 8. c4
{ We are guaranteed to be able to grab the g6-bishop anytime we want, so first we hit Black in the center. There's no rush when it comes to taking! }
8... Be7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. O-O O-O 11. d4
{ Now, an isolated pawn position will inevitably arise. What do we have here? Well, we will grab the bishop pair, which is a nice thing both because bishops will be strong and because we are simplifying the position, which is the right thing to do while fighting the IQP. Black doesn't have any clear counterplay, so White is simply better. For example, after }
11... Rc8 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Nc3 cxd4 14. Qxd4
{ We will follow up with Rfd1, Bf3, etc. White is definitely extremely comfortable! }
