[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Reversed Queen's Indian #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3, and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least committal move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 Bf5
{ With colours reversed, there is a system named after the great British player Anthony Miles that sees such moves as Bf4 and e2-e3. However, without a tempo, I don't have any trust in this system whatsoever, as the early bishop sortie weakens the queenside, which is highlighted distinctively by White's next move. }
5. Bb5+ Nfd7
{ This idea might look very weird, but it's sometimes used with colours reversed. The point is to go ...a7-a6, force the bishop back and develop the other knight to c6. But, it cannot be any good to weaken the center this much. }
6. c4 a6 7. Bxd7+
{ This trade might seem unexpected, but White will now either win a pawn or multiple tempi. }
7... Qxd7 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. Nc3 Qd6 10. d4
{ While Black might seem to be doing fine due to his bishop pair, that's a huge misunderstanding. If you are in doubt, just count how many pieces are developed for each side and how soon each side can castle! Next up, unless Black takes on d4, we can advance in the center with d4-d5 and e3-e4. }
10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7
{ I think it's very reasonable to try and keep the bishop pair. } 12. O-O Nc6
{ Black is simply looking to develop. } 13. Nxc6 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Bxc6 15. Nd5
{ We are immediately creating threats such as Nc7 and Nb6. } 15... Bxd5 16.
Rxd5 e6 17. Rd3
{ While the position might seem nearly symmetrical, I bet you'll have a hard time explaining to me how Black is supposed to develop his f8-bishop, get the rooks in the game and deal with the threat of Rc1-c7. If that's the case, we couldn't be happier with White! This is a clear lovely advantage in a situation where our next moves are extremely simple: just get the last piece in the game and invade the 7th rank! }
