[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3
{ Let me explain a bit why I am recommending this move and what we are trying to accomplish. The variations starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/8/4PN2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  have become rather popular as of late, so, why not 3.c4?First of all, there is nothing wrong with 3.c4. In fact, I love this move and I am greatly interested in exploring it even more. However, I am afraid the potential zone for research is quite limited there, and a few recent sources, such as Alex Smith's e3-poison, Georgiev's The Modern English and Sielecki's/Hansen's 1.c4/1.Nf3 LTR all tackle that line. So, I am not sure how willing I am to follow the same line only to suggest a minor improvement on move 15. Instead, I am much more interested in investigating a fresh variation where I can suggest new ideas on move 5!Also, even more importantly, I believe the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/8/4PN2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.b3  fits extremely well in the philosophy of this course. We play b2-b3 everywhere, so why not do that here, too?  Now, Black can try to stick to the QGD or Slav setup, or take advantage of the fact the center isn't under pressure yet by means of  3...Bf5  or  3...Bg4  . Very importantly, the move  3...c5  transposes to what we discuss after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.e3  c5  .   Another pretty thing about 3.b3, as opposed to 3.c4, is that it doesn't allow for ...dxc4, so the QGA players might find it hard to navigate the arising positions! }
3... e6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3
{ We are developing in a style similar to the Queen's Indian, but with colours reversed. What is the goal? Likely, a few types of positions can arise from here, all based on the pawn structures.1@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ... c7-c5 and take on d4, we will recapture with the e-pawn and attack on the kingside with Ne5, f2-f4 and typical moves of that kind.2@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ... c7-c5 and keep the tension, we will eventually push c2-c4 and one side will end up with a pair of hanging pawns.3@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ...c7-c5 and keep the tension, we will eventually push c2-c4 and both sides' d and c-pawns will be eliminated, which will result in the open center. N2 and N3 can also happen if Black waits long enough, sees us push c2-c4 and meets it with ...c7-c5.4@@EndBracket@@ Black will do nothing, we'll push c2-c4 and will just enjoy the center. }
6... b6 { The most popular continuation. } 7. O-O Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. c4 c5
{ Here is the position of our interest. It is very symmetrical, which certainly means it's extremely important to know of precise ideas/plans/move orders to maintain any kind of initiative. However, I can assure you, this postiion is by no means dull or boring. Recently, my student rated about 2100 FIDE and I had a discussion about it. He was not entirely sure how to press, and drew a few games quickly. Well, the first thing I recommended him to do is to play it with Black against the best engine he can find and try to maintain equality for just ten moves. This task, of course, was successfully failed, which I perfectly expected, and that's totally fine. The idea was to have him see that any equal position stops being equal after an inaccuracy or two, and those are inevitable against opponents who know a lot more ideas than we do. Needless to say, he had wn a couple great games from this position after his experience with the engine, combined with us spending a fair amount of effort discussing it. But I digress. This little story aside, let's see how we can put Black under pressure. }
10. Rc1
{ We are asking Black, if he's interested in resolving the tension in the center, or if he'd rather keep it. }
10... Rc8 { Most people like to keep the tension. } 11. cxd5
{ White has many ways of handling this, but let's check the direct path. What if we take? }
11... Nxd5 12. a3
{ We are preparing to take on c5 and meet the recapture with a piece with b3-b4, grabbing space of course, if ...Nxc5, we need to make we don't hang our darling of a light-squared bishop!. }
12... cxd4
{ Black releases the tension, taking advantage of the fact the White bishop cannot ever take on d4, as the a3-pawn would hang. }
13. Nxd4
{ The White bishop is more active on b3 than the Black one is on e7. The dream here is to put pressure on the diagonals, potentially with Qa1 in the future, or with Nc6, using the weak c6-square. If it was our turn, b3-b4 would be rather promising, grabbing space. }
13... Rxc1 14. Qxc1
{ Let's see how the only top-level game that reached this position continued. }
14... Ne5 15. Be2 Ng6
{ Removing the knight from the danger of Nxe6 makes sense, but now it is rather misplaced. }
16. Qa1 Qa8 17. b4
{ Frankly, the position should be equal, but we are about to play Rc1, and then b4-b5!, making the c6-square an outpost. That is certainly something Black should be uncomfortable about; for more detail, take a look at the model games on this type of positions, which will show the potential problems very clearly. }
