1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 e5
{ This move was played by a number of strong grandmasters, but I consider it somewhat dubious due to the following idea. }
7. dxe5 Nfd7 8. h4
{ The new path. The point here is that White is always happy to play the structures after ...Nxe5, but positions after ...dxe5 are okay for Black from the structural perspective. Of course, Black would like to take with his d-pawn, if he knows what he's doing, so instead of expecting unforced mistakes, we try to immediately take advantage of the fact his knight left the kingside by setting our h-pawn on its mission to the open space. }
8... dxe5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. h5
{ White has a strong initiative and can continue with Qd2 and O-O-O, followed by opening the h-file. Black's development is very problematic, he seems to be in a very bad shape. }
