1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7
{ The most popular decision by far: Black is not showing his hand yet, choosing to wait and possibly follow up with ...e7-e5 shortly after, or with ...c7-c5, or with something slow like ...c7-c6, ...Qc7, etc. }
7. O-O e5
{ Usually, the Black players choose to immediately challenge us in the center. }
8. dxe5 Ng4 9. c4 Ndxe5
{ Results in a pawn structure identical to the one after 9...Nge5, and given there's no forcing lines or critical challenges, is an irrelevant move to us. }
10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qd2
{ Again, White has the space advantage, control over the d5-square and the easy development. Nc3, Rad1, f2-f4 and Bf3 are on the way. }
