1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares. Now, White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I would still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, the Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ... c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... c5 7. dxc5 Qa5+
{ This move was played more or less at all times, even by such strong players as Mamedyarov, but it's suspicious, as now we'll win a ton of time while attacking the Black queen. }
8. Nbd2
{ Here, Black can make a few choices, such as recapturing the c5-pawn, which is the most obvious continuation, or playing ... Rd8 to pin the knight, or even taking on c4 right away. }
8... Qxc5 9. a3
{ While the center is about to be liquidated, Black's problems are not even close to being solved, because his exposed queen will serve as a source of a couple free tempi for our pieces and pawns. }
9... Nc6 10. b4 Qd6 11. cxd5
{ In this position, Black tried recapturing in both ways, but neither gives him an easy life. }
11... Nxd5
{ Trades the bishops, which is beneficial if you believe trading pieces helps defend, but also exposes the Black queen to Nc4 or Ne4. }
12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Ne4
{ Again, the Black queen is a target and he has to lose time instead of developing, while we are activating the pieces for free. }
13... Qd8 14. Qd2
{ Moves like Bc4 or Rd1 are on the way, potentially Qb2+ might expose the d5-knight to new dangers, b4-b5 can push Black's pieces even further away and win more time. How is this position supposed to be fun for Black?! Let's take a look at the model game in the corresponding chapter to better understand how to pose problems in the arising middlegame. }
