[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Old Indian #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6
{ Black makes a claim he is about to play ...e7-e5, which is something we should not allow for, of course. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. e3
{ While ...Bxf3 was by no means a threat, there is no need to discuss some random pawn structure that doesn't arise anywhere else in our repertoire, so we play e2-e3. }
4... Nbd7 5. h3
{ I find it desirable to immediately clarify the situation with the bishop, making Black either concede the bishop pair, or retreat to h5, where the bishop would be somewhat endangered due to the ever-existing possibiltiies of g2-g4 at an appropriate moment. }
5... Bh5 6. Bb2
{ White just keeps developing in a natural way. Of course, our next moves are also rather easy and obvious: for example, we can follow up with Nbd2, Be2 and O-O. Alternatively, c2-c4 and Nc3 is a good setup as well, but keeping the knight on d2 allows the bishop on b2 to be active and to control the e5-square. Now, Black must be facing a bit of an existential crisis: playing ...e7-e5 is suspicious due to dynamic reasons we are about to see in a second, and ... g7-g6 is not possible either, as the h5-bishop will get trapped here we see the benefits of including h2-h3!. So, his only way of developing involves ... e7-e6, which, obviously, is a setup that has nothing to do with the Old Indian. }
6... e5
{ This was played in most of the few games that reached this position, but this move has a relatively straightforward issue attached to it. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Nbd2
{ Now, however, the e5-pawn is certainly a problem! As the variations below show, White sholud not hurry taking it, but Black always needs to keep that very possibility in mind. Interestingly, this natural move is a novelty. }
8... Be7 9. g4 Bg6 10. Bg2
{ Now, the pawn is indeed hanging, as White's development finally looks good and tactical issues from the previous variations where he attempted to capture the pawn, such as a move or two earlier, related to the ...Qd5 fork, have been addressed. }
10... e4
{ Is an attempt to shut down the g2-bishop and harass White somehow, but it's too ambitious and unjustified, because after }
11. Nh4 { Now, there is no way of holding on to the e4-pawn, because after }
11... Nc5 { This was the only move to defend the pawn, of course. } 12. Nxg6
hxg6 13. g5 { We kick out one of the defenders. } 13... Nd5 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15.
Bxe4
{ White simply picks up a free pawn and Black has nothing to show for it. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Old Indian #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6
{ Black makes a claim he is about to play ...e7-e5, which is something we should not allow for, of course. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. e3
{ While ...Bxf3 was by no means a threat, there is no need to discuss some random pawn structure that doesn't arise anywhere else in our repertoire, so we play e2-e3. }
4... Nbd7 5. h3
{ I find it desirable to immediately clarify the situation with the bishop, making Black either concede the bishop pair, or retreat to h5, where the bishop would be somewhat endangered due to the ever-existing possibiltiies of g2-g4 at an appropriate moment. }
5... Bxf3 6. Qxf3 c6
{ This was chosen by an experienced Irish GM and an author Baburin. However, while Black's setup is rather solid, it is certainly very passive. }
7. Bb2 g6 8. Nd2 d5
{ Is also possible, taking the game to the Slav-style positions, which are covered in the Slav and Grunfeld chapters. }
9. Bd3 Bg7 10. Qe2
{ White removes the queen in advance to both not run into some ...e7-e5 or something along those lines as well as create a possibility of Nf3 if it's ever needed to enhance our control over the e5-square. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Double Fianchetto #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 b6
{ Of course, this move, which is my very own recommendation for Black in the course on the Accelerated Queen's Indian, is to a large extent a critical test to this repertoire: what if Black simply keeps the symmetry? }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. e3 g6
{ Since positions after ...e6 are covered via QGD, as mentioned in the text, the only thing we need to analyze in this chapter is the Double Fianchetto, which is a rather ambitious opening for Black. This is typically the path Black would choose if he wants to make sure he avoids simplifications. Or, in other words, a 'must-win' line versus weaker opponents. }
5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White just quietly develops his pieces, not defining the situation in the center yet. At this point, Black can play in the Grunfeld-ish style with ...d7-d5, of flexiblty with ...e7-e6, ... c7-c5. Of course, the plan ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 will transpose to King's Indian. }
7... c5 8. O-O d5
{ Is what a lot of players did, but the list of White's proponents of the line is even more impressive: Nepo, Karjakin, Martirosyan and many others! }
9. Nxd5
{ This is a very safe path, which will result in an equal endgame where Black would need to be somewhat careful. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. d4 cxd4
{ Black releases the tension in the center, trading queens and simplifying the position even further. }
13. Qxd4+ Qxd4 14. Nxd4
{ Now, however, he is facing a serious problem: how to develop the queenside? Where should that queenside knight go? }
14... Nc6
{ This choice happens to be rather suspicious and does not solve all the problems, either. Why? Doesn't the position look entirely equal? Well, the move ...b7-b6 weakened the a6 square, and since both parties are interested in fighting for the open c-file, the move Ba6! is now available to White, which means Black would always fail while challenging the c-file. }
15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Rfc1 Rac8
{ It might seem tempting to try to avoid moving the bishop again, instead looking to get the rest of the pieces in the game fast, but this idea loses on the spot due to the awful weakness of the a6-square. }
17. Ba6 Rc7 18. Rc3
{ White is winning the bishop by force, as Rac1 and Bb5 cannot be stopped. The end! Look how quickly things fell apart. }
*

