[Black "Double Fianchetto #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 b6
{ Of course, this move, which is my very own recommendation for Black in the course on the Accelerated Queen's Indian, is to a large extent a critical test to this repertoire: what if Black simply keeps the symmetry? }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. e3 g6
{ Since positions after ...e6 are covered via QGD, as mentioned in the text, the only thing we need to analyze in this chapter is the Double Fianchetto, which is a rather ambitious opening for Black. This is typically the path Black would choose if he wants to make sure he avoids simplifications. Or, in other words, a 'must-win' line versus weaker opponents. }
5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White just quietly develops his pieces, not defining the situation in the center yet. At this point, Black can play in the Grunfeld-ish style with ...d7-d5, of flexiblty with ...e7-e6, ... c7-c5. Of course, the plan ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 will transpose to King's Indian. }
7... c5 8. O-O d5
{ Is what a lot of players did, but the list of White's proponents of the line is even more impressive: Nepo, Karjakin, Martirosyan and many others! }
9. Nxd5
{ This is a very safe path, which will result in an equal endgame where Black would need to be somewhat careful. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Nxe3
{ Is also possible, but White will get an extra pawn in the center } 11. fxe3
Kxg7 12. d4
{ Now, the positional threat is d4-d5! followed by e3-e4!, grabbing space and restricting the b7-bishop. }
12... e6 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Rad1
{ Having centralized the pieces, we are ready to continue with d4-d5! and e3-e4! A warning: do that with caution, because while d4-d5 will give us a very strong passed pawn, ...exd5 will expose the backward e3-pawn, which can certainly be a problem in the long run if we mishandle things. We are already in brand-new territory with no games, but we can certainly estimate a couple logical moves for both sides. }
14... Qe7 15. d5
{ Once we prepare e3-e4!, White will have a large advantage, and will be always able to meet ...exd5 with exd5!. }
15... exd5 16. cxd5 Rfe8 17. e4 { A key idea. Black cannot take the e4-pawn! }
17... Qxe4 18. Bb5
{ The threat is not only to take the knight, but also to exploit the f7-weakness with Ng5, attacking the f7-pawn and the queen on e4. }
18... Red8 19. Ng5 { And White wins on the spot. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5
{ Welcome to the chapter on the Anti-Dutch! I've spent a long time thinking what to recommend against this opening, and that is primarily not because it's hard for fight for advantage, but because we don't want to engage in highly theoretical opening discussions, and even more importantly, we do not want to be move-ordered into some variation that does not fit with the rest of this repertoire. Therefore, I hope you forgive me for not sticking to the pure b2-b3 plans which are typical of the rest of the course! However, I am really excited to show you the sideline that I find very promising, yet really easy to learn and relatively little-known. }
2. d4
{ Okay, we seem to be going for the main setups with d4! But, we won't enter the mainline theory, don't worry. Now, most people who play the Dutch would stay flexible with ... Nf6, but it's certainly also worth checking out such moves as 2...g6, 2...e6 and 2...d5. }
2... g6
{ This is a cheeky attempt to get to the Leningrad Dutch type of positions without allowing for our beloved Bg5 move. }
3. h4
{ Unfortunately, not developing the knight to f6 early on, combined with playing ...g7-g6, has been lately known for being very dangerous due to this typical h-pawn thrust. }
3... Nf6 4. h5
{ Many of you have likely seen this exchange sacrifice idea before in many various scenarios, it is very strong here as well. We are looking to take on g6, of course, or possibly go h5-h6!, forcing Black to take some action. }
4... Nxh5 5. Rxh5 gxh5 6. e4 Bg7 7. Nh4
{ By means of this move, we create a threat of Qxh5 while also attacking the f5-pawn. }
7... O-O 8. Nxf5
{ White doesn't need to urgently win anything back or hurry in any way. Instead, we are just looking to dominate the kingside, maybe exchange the g7-bishop, win the h5-pawn, bring the bishop in with Bg5 or Bh6, the other pieces with Bd3, Nc3, O-O-O, Rh1 and slowly but surely slaughter Black. }
8... e6 9. Nxg7 Kxg7 10. Qxh5
{ Black's king is really weak, Bh6 is a threat, and overall, White is enjoying fantastic compensation for the sacrificed exchange. Real trouble for the opponent! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Dutch #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5
{ Welcome to the chapter on the Anti-Dutch! I've spent a long time thinking what to recommend against this opening, and that is primarily not because it's hard for fight for advantage, but because we don't want to engage in highly theoretical opening discussions, and even more importantly, we do not want to be move-ordered into some variation that does not fit with the rest of this repertoire. Therefore, I hope you forgive me for not sticking to the pure b2-b3 plans which are typical of the rest of the course! However, I am really excited to show you the sideline that I find very promising, yet really easy to learn and relatively little-known. }
2. d4
{ Okay, we seem to be going for the main setups with d4! But, we won't enter the mainline theory, don't worry. Now, most people who play the Dutch would stay flexible with ... Nf6, but it's certainly also worth checking out such moves as 2...g6, 2...e6 and 2...d5. }
2... Nf6
{ The most flexible and common move which doesn't define yet what variation of the Dutch Black is going for. }
3. Bg5 e6
{ The most popular move by far, which you will be likely seeing in 65-70% of the games. }
4. Nbd2
{ White is about to take advantage of the pinned f6-knight by pushing e2-e4! }
4... Be7
{ Black unpins the knight, while also developing and getting ready to castle. }
5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4
{ Transposes to the famous variation 1.d4f52.c3f63.g5e64.e4fxe45.xe4e76.xf6xf67.f3. For one, I would highly recommend seeing the game Lasker-Thomas if you hadn't yet, that should give a couple ideas on how dangerous Black's position is. We won't go too deep in theory here, but we certainly will look at a couple of model variations to see what dangers Black is facing. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ Black has a few main issues here. For one, the fact his f6-knight and f-pawn are missing mean the kingside is weakened, and just like in the very famous game Lasker-Thomas, he could easily find himself checkmated after Ne5, Qh5, etc. However, it's also worth saying lack of the f-pawn makes it difficult for him to develop his queenside without weakening the pawn structure considerably, since moving the d-pawn would make the e6-pawn extremely weak. }
8... Nc6 { The most common move. } 9. c3 d5 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Qe2
{ We are taking the e5-square under control, preventing the opponent from carrying out the liberating ... e6-e5 break. }
11... Bd7 12. O-O Rae8 { Black is looking to carry out the ...e6-e5 break. }
13. Bb5
{ One of the key ideas in this position. We are looking to get rid of the c6-knight, which is a useful piece that is supporting the e5-break, and leave Black with that terrible passive light-squared bishop versus our drop-dead gorgeous knight on e5. Always keep in mind the following basic positional rule: while trading pieces, look not just at what you trade, but also at what remains on the board! }
13... a6
{ Let's see what happens if Black doesn't mind having us execute our idea. }
14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Rfe1
{ We go Ne5 next and then pursue Black on the kingside by means of such moves as Qd2, Re3, Rg3, possibly h4-h5, etc. He has no counterplay whatsoever. }
*

[Event "?"]
