[White "1.Nf3 d5 2.e3 c5: The Reversed Queen's Indian"]
[Black "An interesting line to explore on your own"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... f6
{ This line is the most aggressive @@StartBracket@@and the best!@@EndBracket@@ way of tackling the classic Accelerated Queen's Indian - for those of you who aren't sure what I mean, I'm referring to the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  b6  3.f3  . However, we now have an extra move e2-e3, which allows us to fight for the center with a pawn thrust, as we will soon see. }
4. Bb2 e5 5. Bb5+
{ This is also interesting, but doesn't give as much of an advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.Nf3 d5 2.e3 c5: The Reversed Queen's Indian"]
[Black "3...f6 - what NOT to do"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... f6
{ This line is the most aggressive @@StartBracket@@and the best!@@EndBracket@@ way of tackling the classic Accelerated Queen's Indian - for those of you who aren't sure what I mean, I'm referring to the position after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  Nf6  2.c4  b6  3.f3  . However, we now have an extra move e2-e3, which allows us to fight for the center with a pawn thrust, as we will soon see. }
4. d4 Nc6 5. dxc5
{ This novelty seems weird as the move is giving up the center. However, the fearless Lc0 claims White will just keep his extra pawn to eventually destroy Black's center! While 5.Bb2 isn't bad at all and was chosen by many GMs, I feel privileged to introduce to you an even better idea. }
5... e5
{ Of course, this is the most natural move, as Black is taking the whole center. }
6. Ba3
{ Among other things, it is vital to mention that the move ...f7-f6 makes it hard for Black to develop his kingside minor pieces. For example, if the bishop goes to e7, the g8-knight is stuck, and vice versa. So, it's fair to suggest he'll go ...Be7 and ...Nh6-f7. }
6... Be7 7. c4 Be6 8. cxd5 Bxd5 9. Nc3
{ This is dubious as White's pieces will be quite loose. } 9... Qa5
{ This is not something we want to allow, even though White is still better. }
*

