1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nc6
{ Will just transpose somewhere shortly in most cases, but there are variations where Black can abstain from playing ... Nf6. They are not very sound, but we certainly need to learn how to handle them. }
4. Bb2 f6
{ An attempt to grab space with ...e7-e5. This idea is somewhat dangerous with colours reversed against the Accelerated Queen's Indian, but without a tempo it's very suspicious, because now the f6-square is unavailable for the black knight, which means he might have a hard time castling quickly. }
5. d4 { Of course, we need to prevent ...e7-e5. } 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nxc6
bxc6 8. c4
{ This position was seen in two games only, so let's see how a grandmaster misplayed it with White and how we can improve on his play. }
8... Be6 { Black overprotects his center. } 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Bb5+
{ Black has to give up castling rights; however, this is not bad at all, because the king is safe on f7. }
10... Kf7 11. O-O
{ Now, White is ready to potentially undermine Black's centre with f2-f4!?, so that the White f1-rook can enjoy facing that f7-king. Alternatively, we can just keep developing. Those of you who play my Accelerated Queen's Indian already know the plan, but for those who don't, here it is: White has an extra pawn on the queenside, and queenside pawns are more beneficial in the endgame because it's harder for Black to deal with the passed b2-pawn than it is for White to stop the Black d-pawn. So, we just want to trade all the major pieces on the c-file and win the endgame. However, we can also try to bug the black king. }
11... Rc8 12. Ba6 Rc6 13. Bb5
{ The way White played showed he lost the thread, and eventually the game. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Jacobson,B @@StartBracket@@2504@@EndBracket@@-Burke,J @@StartBracket@@2538@@EndBracket@@ Sanit Louis 2021 }
