{ White is now ready to potentially undermine Black's center with f2-f4!?, so that the White f1-rook can enjoy facing that f7-king. Alternatively, we can just keep developing.   Those of you who play my Accelerated Queen's Indian already know the plan, but for those who don't, here it is: White has an extra pawn on the queenside, and queenside pawns are more beneficial in the endgame, because it's harder for Black to deal with the passed b2-pawn than it is for White to stop the Black d-pawn. So, we just want to trade all the major piece on the c-file and win the endgame. However, we can also try to bug the Black king. }
11... Rc8 12. Bd3
{ The threat is Qh5+, meeting ...g7-g6 with Bxg6, because the h8-rook would hang. }
12... Bd6 13. Qh5+
{ And Black will have even more problems with coordination. } 13... Kf8 14. Nc3
{ We are about to continue with Rc1 and then potentially Nb5, trying to kick the bishop away from the a3-f8 diagonal and follow up with Ba3+. }
*

