1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nc6
{ Will just transpose somewhere shortly in most cases, but there are variations where Black can abstain from playing ... Nf6. They are not very sound, but we certainly need to learn how to handle them. }
4. Bb2 Bg4 5. h3
{ We want to either provoke the capture on f3, which gives us the bishop pair, or make the bishop retreat to h5. The idea is that having the bishop there gives Black two problems:   It cannot retreat back to d7;   White can always break the pin with g2-g4 and potentially initiate some typical trouble with Bb5 and Ne5, which is very common with colours reversed in the Nimzo. }
5... Bh5 6. Bb5
{ Time to threaten g2-g4 and Ne5. Of course, Bxc6 is always on the agenda, as well. }
6... e6
{ After other moves, like 6..Qc7 or Nf6, we can, of course, follow the same plan.  Instead, 6...f6 makes the kingside development very difficult, which we can exploit by d2-d4!, preventing Black from taking the center with ...e7-e5 and asking him what is the pawn doing on f6 and how is he planning on getting the g8-knight out. }
7. g4 Bg6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Ne5
{ White acts in a manner identical to the Nimzo reversed. Black's pawn structure is cramped, now h3-h4-h5 is on the way. Alternatively, we can play d2-d3. f2-f4, Ndf3, Qe2 and keep Black in a very passive situation. The bishop on g6 is always in permanent danger of getting trapped after h3-h4-h5! }
