1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least commital move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 Nc6 5. Bb5
{ This is a reversed Nimzo. I believe the system isn't particularly dangerous even when played with White, a tempo up, so no wonder here Black is going to be under even more pressure. }
5... Bd7 6. O-O a6 7. Bxc6
{ Importantly, we don't mind giving up the bishop pair here. First of all, this is a temporarily concession, as our next move is going to be Ne5 and we will surely get the bishop pair back. But also, retreating would mean losing precious time, which is why we are so delighted to capture. }
7... Bxc6 8. Ne5 Rc8 9. d3
{ Now, Nd2 is about to be played. Later, we can follow up either with the classic f2-f4, Ndf3, Qe2, etc, or the more fresh c2-c4. }
9... e6 10. Nd2 Be7 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Nxc6 Rxc6 13. e4
{ Is another very interesting plan. The point, of course, is to challenge the strong d5-pawn and make Black define the situation in the center. }
13... b5
{ Let's say Black keeps the tension while also grabbing some space on the queenside. Seems reasonable, doesn't it. }
14. c4 { I want even more tension in the center! } 14... dxe4 15. dxe4 Qb8 16.
f4
{ With e4-e5 and Ne4-d6 coming at a moment of our choosing, Black is doing rather badly, as he is very short on space and his bishop is rather terrible. 1/2 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Horvath,J @@StartBracket@@2522@@EndBracket@@-Rieger,R @@StartBracket@@2275@@EndBracket@@ Aschach 2017 }
