[White "1.Nf3 d5 2.e3 c5: The Reversed Queen's Indian"]
[Black "4...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least commital move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 e6
{ The e2-e3 QID might be somewhat poisonous. But, without a tempo, it's no longer as attractive as we have two very promising setups. }
5. d4
{ While this move isn't as straightforward as c2-c4, as it doesn't define the pawn structure as fast, but I like it a ton because it's very much in the spirit of the QID @@StartBracket@@and of my course on it!@@EndBracket@@. Now, as I said in that course, we give Black two choices. He should either take on d4 right away, or we will take ourselves! }
5... Be7 6. dxc5
{ Once Black moved the bishop, I like the idea of taking right away. By the way, I also recommend this exact approach with colours reversed. }
6... Bxc5 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Bd3 Nc6
{ After the following natural developing moves, let's see what is happening and what we are playing for. It might seem as though after the inevitable c2-c4 and ... dxc4 the position would be simply equal due to the structural symmetry. However, symmetrical structure doesn't guarantee equality, as the piece activity might be rather different! This is exactly the factor we are betting on. Most importantly, the b2-bishop is very powerful, while the c8-bishop is not great at all. }
9. a3
{ I believe Black shouldn't allow us to grab more space with b3-b4 and c2-c4. }
9... a5
{ This hinders our queenside expansion, but we can play on both sides of the board as we will soon see. }
10. O-O b6 11. c4 Bb7 12. Qc2
{ We are creating some little nasty threats, such as cxd5, as ...Nxd5 would hang the h7-pawn while ...exd5 gets a pretty suspicious version of an IQP @@StartBracket@@while also hanging the pawn to Bxf6 and Bxh7@@EndBracket@@. }
12... h6 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Ne4 Be7 15. Rfd1
{ I have a hard time believing Black equalized, as White's activity is rather overwhelming and Black is struggling to find a good square for the queen, which is often the case in these symmetrical structures. As usual, we will greatly benefit from studying some  model games  (chaptr:17)  (with these symmetrical structures.) }
