[Black "4...e6  - DO NOT allow for this exchange sac!"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least commital move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 e6
{ The e2-e3 QID might be somewhat poisonous. But, without a tempo, it's no longer as attractive as we have two very promising setups. }
5. d4
{ While this move isn't as straightforward as c2-c4, as it doesn't define the pawn structure as fast, but I like it a ton because it's very much in the spirit of the QID @@StartBracket@@and of my course on it!@@EndBracket@@. Now, as I said in that course, we give Black two choices. He should either take on d4 right away, or we will take ourselves! }
5... cxd4 6. exd4
{ The plan is to follow up with Bd3, Nbd2, Qe2, O-O, Ne5 and f2-f4, fighting for the e4-square and then occupying e5 and setting up a kingside attack.   Again, I would highly recommend focusing on model games as opposed to theory here. Another hugely important thing I would like to mention is that we should keep the threat of ...Nb4 in mind, as it might cause us problems by harassing the d3-bishop. If that's ever in the air, you might as well simply insert a2-a3, stopping that idea for good. }
6... Nc6 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. a3 { We stop the ...Nb4 idea for good. } 8... O-O 9. O-O
b6
{ Of course, Black needs to try and develop his queenside. However, the c8-bishop is a serious issue, it's not easy to improve that piece all that much. }
10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. Qe2
{ This is a very typical setup of these reversed QID positions. Or, if you will, these positions also arise from Colle/ Zukertort all the time @@StartBracket@@this specific position can also easily arise from those systems@@EndBracket@@.  Later, Ne5 and f2-f4 is on cards. }
11... Rc8 12. Ne5 Ne7
{ It's rather important that the knight comes over to the kingside in order to negate White's upcoming mayhem over there.  Also, Black is potentially preparing some counterplay on the c-file. }
13. f4 Rc7
{ This is an interesting move which prepares ...Qc8, which might create an exchange sacrifice idea @@StartBracket@@...Rxc2@@EndBracket@@. I would like to show to you how to deal with that idea. }
14. Rae1 Qc8 15. g3
{ This move doesn't serve any purpose, I am just looking to show you what we should NOT allow. }
15... Rxc2 16. Bxc2 Qxc2
{ The queen is dangerously invading our position. For the sacrificed exchange, Black immediately gets a pawn and a lot of activity. Importnatly, he also takes the main 'tooth' or asset of our position - the powerful light-squared bishop. As you can see, the other bishop is rather passive at the moment. }
17. Rb1 Ne4
{ Black definitely has a ton of counterplay. In fact, I find his position easier to handle, so make sure to avoid this pesky ...Rxc2 idea! }
