[White "1.Nf3 d5 2.e3 c5: The Reversed Queen's Indian"]
[Black "Fianchetto Reversed #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least commital move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 g6
{ This is the reversed g2-g3 Queen's Indian. What is a very solid and ambitious setup with an extra tempo turns out a rather dicey idea with colours reversed a tempo down, since White immediately puts up some rather unpleasant pressure. }
5. c4 { The most ambitious continuation. } 5... Bg7
{ Seems less reliable than 5.dxc4, which we take a look at later. } 6. cxd5
{ Black is obligated to take with the queen, which is clearly undesirable. }
6... Qxd5 7. Nc3
{ Now, another tempo needs to be wasted. Let's not go too deep in detail here since Black can play ...Qd8, ...Qf5, etc, focusing on ideas. }
7... Qd8 8. Ne4
{ Moves like Rc1 and Be2 also deserve attention, but I think it's easiest to grab some long-term edge by spoiling Black's structure. }
8... b6 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Bxf6 exf6 11. d4
{ Let's try to understand what is the nature of White's advantage.  It's not that Black's kingside structure is terrible or the pawns are getting lost. His problem is very different here: after the inevitable trade of the d and c-pawns, White will be able to occupy the outpost on d4 with his knight, while Black doesn't have one on d5. That fact, for instance, grants White a long-term edge which could be rather annoying. Also, White is somewhat more better developed, which means Black still needs to solve a few more issues. Let's take a look at a couple more moves to see in practice what I mean! }
11... Nd7 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Ke2
{ Black's king is still somewhat vulnerable and such ideas as Nd4-c6 or Nd4-b5 are about to prove rather irritating. }
