[White "1.Nf3 d5 2.e3 c5: The Reversed Queen's Indian"]
[Black "Fianchetto Reversed #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5
{ This part of our repertoire is devoted to fighting 1...d5 - the solid Queen's Gambit Declined/Accepted as well as the Slav setups.   Now that we've played 2.e3, Black can react in various ways, but this one is especially ambitious and important: with his last move, Black is already pretending he's the one fighting for the opening advantage! }
3. b3
{ Now, Black has a whole plethora of approaches and setups. I perceive this position as a reversed Queen's Indian of sorts. What possibilities does White have in the QID? There are setups with g2-g3, e2-e3, Bf4 and e3, the classic Nc3-Nf3 and the Petrosian system.   So, let's base our play on setups as opposed to very concrete theory and look what happens if Black tries to reach one of these setups with colours reversed. }
3... Nf6
{ The least commital move - the other knight may later go to c6, d7 or not move at all. But, Black definitely needs to castle at some point, so ...Nf6 is very reasonable and flexible. }
4. Bb2 g6
{ This is the reversed g2-g3 Queen's Indian. What is a very solid and ambitious setup with an extra tempo turns out a rather dicey idea with colours reversed a tempo down, since White immediately puts up some rather unpleasant pressure. }
5. c4 { The most ambitious continuation. } 5... dxc4 6. Bxc4 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8.
d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4
{ It doesn't look to me as though Black solved all the opening problems. It's not very easy to develop his queenside, while we are about to play Nd2, Rc1, Qe2, Rfd1 and ask Black a bunch of awkward questions. }
9... Bd7
{ This is the most common continuation, the point being to prepare ...Nc6 in order to develop the queenside without spoiling the pawn structure. }
10. Nd2 Nc6 11. N4f3
{ I like this new idea that was seen twice only in Nepo's games. White....well, I would like to say he has more space, but I am not sure if that's the right definition. Let's say our b2-bishop is very active and our pieces have greater potential, we also want to prevent Black from trading on d4 and playing ...Bc6, setting his bishop to sit nicely on that long diagonal. So, we don't trade!   Later, the plan is Qe2, Rfd1, Rac1, etc. We are looking at a bunch of model games that teach us how to handle this symmetrical structure, so let's not bother learning too many theoretical lines - the position isn't too sharp, plans and ideas matter much more! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Jianchao Zhou vs.  Alexander Moiseenko, Shanghai-Chengdu, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6
{ This is an attempt to fianchetto the bishop. Of course, with colours reversed this would have been the g2-g3 variation against the Queen's Indian, one of the most solid lines out there. However, with colours reversed, it does not work nearly as well, because White gets to immediately challenge the center. }
5. c4 dxc4 6. bxc4
{ In the theoreticalchapter, I recommend the move  6.Bxc4  in this line, or alternatively, to play @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pp1p/5np1/2pp4/8/1P2PN2/PBPP1PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bb5+  rather than  5.c4  .  However, I thought it would be beneficial for us to look at the arising hanging pawns structure. }
6... Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 9. Ne5
{ One of the key Queen's Indian moves: White takes the e5-square under control, looking to exchange the knights and weaken the h1-a8 diagonal and possibly prepare Bf3 and Rb1, putting pressure on the b7-pawn. At the same time, we prevent the ...e7-e5 move altogether. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5 Bd7 11. Qc2
{ 11.a4!?  Bc6  12.a5  Seems a very interesting plan as well, the idea being to restrict the b7-pawn, and then prepare Nc3, Qb3, etc with pressure on the b7-pawn.   11.Bf3  Would be a nice move to make, as the b7-pawn would be awkward to defend, but Black has one sufficient defense.  11...Qc8  Black is about to play Bc6, and I'm afraid we did not accomplish much.   11...Bc6  12.Bxc6  bxc6  White is slightly better, but things don't look entirely clear here, either. }
11... Bc6 12. d3
{ White is in no rush to play d2-d4. Instead, he takes the e4-square under control, preparing Qb2, maybe Nc3 or Nd2, and maybe eventually a4-a5, Rb1, etc. }
12... Ne8 13. Bc3 Qd7 14. a4 { Time to grabs space on the queenside. } 14...
Nc7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qb2+ f6
{ 16...Kg8  17.d4!  Is also unpleasant, but it's not that bad, as the ...f7-f6 move is weakening Black's position considerably. }
17. d4
{ The ...f7-f6 move is rather weakening, now d4-d5 and e3-e4 is about to build the strong center. }
17... cxd4 18. exd4 e6 { Black prevents ...d7-d5. } 19. a5
{ White is squeezing Black even more on the queenside. } 19... Qd6 20. Rd1
{ This move gets a piece in the game and prepares Nc3 and d4-d5! } 20... Rad8
21. Nc3 Rf7 22. Rd3 { White prepares Rad1 and d4-d5! } 22... Na6 23. Rad1
{ The last rook gets in the game. The central pawn break is on the way! } 23...
Qb4 24. Qa1
{ Of course, having the better king and activity, White has no interest in trading queens. }
24... Qd6 25. Re3
{ 25.h4!?  Would have been a very interesting idea, intending h4-h5, Qc1 and Rh3! }
25... Nc7 26. h4 { A move later, White finds the right path. } 26... Rfd7 27.
h5 Qf4 28. Qa3
{ The queen is taking the e7-square under control, the point being to prepare d4-d5 and Re7! }
28... Rxd4 { Black could not afford this pawn. } 29. Qe7+ Kg8 30. Rxd4
{ 30.Nd5!  Would have won on the spot, creating a threat of Nxf6. Now, Black could accept the sacrifice, but that would ruin his position.  30...Rxd1+  31.Bxd1  exd5  32.Qxd8+  And then loses a rook, and then the knight! }
30... Rxd4 31. g3
{ Unfortunately, here White goes wrong.   31.Nd5!  Would have still won on the spot, but for different reasons.  31...exd5  32.g3  Qf5  33.Qd8+  Kg7  34.Re7+  And White would have mated on the spot. Not an easy sequence to find, necessarily! }
31... Qd6 32. Qxf6 Ne8 33. Qg5
{ However, despite the missed forced win, White is still much better. } 33...
Kf7 34. Bf3 Rxc4 35. Ne4 Qd4 36. Qh6
{ The pieces keep coming at our opponent's king. } 36... Qg7 37. Qf4+ Ke7 38.
Qg5+ Nf6 39. Nc5 { There's no way to stop the capture on e6. } 39... Bxf3 40.
Rxf3 Kd6 41. h6 Qe7 42. Nxb7+ Qxb7 43. Qxf6 Qd5 44. Qd8+
{ And White ended up winning by force. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Bogdan Daniel Deac vs. Neil Berry, Heraklion, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
{ 1.Nf3  d5  2.e3  c5  3.b3  Nf6  4.Bb2  e6  5.c4  Nc6  6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bb5  Bd6  8.O-O  O-O  9.d4  cxd4  10.Nxd4  is where this game comes together with our repertoire, of course. }
1... e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. b3 c5 5. Bb2
{ While the opening moves were slightly different, soon the game arrived at the same position as the one we're looking at. }
5... Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4
{ Here is the position we're looking at after 4...e6 in the chapter on the Reversed QID. This is a typical isolated queen's pawn situation, and there are hundreds of articles, chapters and books written on this topic, so I would highly recommend you investigate some of those, if you'd like to learn more. For example, the 'Chess Structures' book by Rioz has material on the topic. White is looking to trade all the minor pieces and win the endgame where Black would have a weak pawn. }
10... Bd7 11. Be2 Re8 12. Nd2
{ The knight is coming to f3, of course.   12.Nc3?!  Wouldn't be such a great move, because Black can get rid of his IQP.  12...Nxd4!  13.Qxd4  Be5!  With the next move likely being ...d5-d4, Black has no issues whasoever. }
12... Rc8 13. N2f3 Bb8 14. Rc1
{ 14.Nxc6!?  Would have been very interesting. Now, if Black takes with a piece, White should be happy, because the pieces get traded off. At the same time, after  14...bxc6  15.Ba6!  Is a very important move.  15...Rc7  16.Be5±  And the c7-rook is in trouble. }
14... Qe7 15. Nxc6 Bxc6
{ 15...bxc6  16.Qd4!  Would be a very nice square for the queen. Now, the a7-pawn is hanging and White is ready to play Qh4, which will threaten Bxf6, spoiling the pawn structure, while also preparing Nd4 with additional pressure on c6. }
16. Qd4
{ There is no activity that compensates for the weak pawn, White is comfortably better. }
16... Qe4 17. Qd2
{ 17.Bd3!  Would have been better, either forcing a queen trade@@StartBracket@@ remember, that's what White wants!@@EndBracket@@, or pushing Black back.  17...Qe7  18.Qh4±  Threatening Bxf6 and Nd4-f5. }
17... Qe7 18. Rc2 Ne4 19. Qd4 f6 { Slow maneuvering continues. } 20. a4 Qd6 21.
Rd1 Ng5 22. g3 { ...Nxf3 and ...Qxh2 was threatened. } 22... Re4 23. Qd3
{ Now Nxg5 is about to destroy Black's pawn structure. } 23... Nf7
{ 23...Nxf3+  24.Bxf3  The d5-pawn would fall shortly.  24...Ree8  25.Bxd5+  Bxd5  26.Rxc8  Rxc8  27.Qxd5+  Qxd5  28.Rxd5+-  White is not just a pawn up, he is also about to invade on d7, and his bishop would be placed really well on d4.  The game is over. }
24. Qxd5 { What a cool idea! } 24... Bxd5 25. Rxc8+ Nd8 26. Bc4
{ Black is pinned all over the place and is losing by force. } 26... Rxc4 27.
bxc4 Bc7 28. Rxd5 { The game is ending right away. } 28... Qe7 29. Nd4 g6 30.
Nb5 Ba5 31. Bc3
{ White is distracting the bishop on a5 from defending the knight. } 31... Bb6
32. a5 Qe6 33. Ra8
{ Black resigned as he's losing even more pieces. A nice demonstration of how to restrict the opponent's activity while fighting against the isolated pawn! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Grigoriy Oparin vs. Pavel Eljanov, Extremadura, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c5 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. Bb5 Bd7 6. c4
{ In the repertoire, the suggested move is 6.O-O, but the arising positions are idea-based and highly transpositional, so we should certainly look at this game. }
6... a6 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5
{ White is looking to spoil the opponent's pawn structure after taking on c6. }
8... Rc8 9. O-O e6 10. Nxc6 Rxc6 11. Bxf6
{ A very interesting idea, which takes advantage of the vulnerability of Black's center. }
11... gxf6
{ 11...Qxf6  12.cxd5!  exd5  13.Nc3!  The center is about to collapse. } 12.
cxd5 Qxd5
{ 12...exd5  Of course, now the pawn structure looks atrocious.  13.Nc3  Bg7  14.Qf3  Rd6  15.Ne2±  There is no telling how Black should continue, as castling would expose him to the attack after Ng3-f5 and Qg4. Additionally, of course, the idea of d2-d4 is always on the agenda, creating an isolated pawn, which would be very weak, as most minor pieces have already been traded. }
13. Nc3 Qd3
{ Black is looking to block the d-pawn from advancing.   13...Qd8  14.Rc1⩲  White would go Qf3 and Rfd1 next, preparing d2-d4. }
14. Rc1 Be7 15. Ne2
{ The knight is coming to f4, potentially looking to arrive at h5 to attack the Black king, or to simply lure the queen away and prepare d2-d4. }
15... Rg8 16. g3 Kf8 17. Nf4 Qf5 18. d4
{ As the game opens up, it clearly turns out Black's coordination is terrible, there is no safe spot for his king, and all the pieces are very uncoordinated overall. }
18... e5
{ 18...cxd4  19.Rxc6  bxc6  20.Qxd4  Results in a terrible pawn structure for Black, we are about to play Rc1, Qc4 and win the queenside pawns.  20...e5  21.Qd3±  And White avoids losing a piece and gets a significantly superior endgame. }
19. Ng2 { 19.d5!  Would have been even better, getting a passed pawn. } 19...
Qh3 20. Qf3
{ Pressure on the center keeps increasing. Black's coordination is absolutely terrible, and White is ready to capture on c5 and open the game even more. }
20... Rg6 21. Rfd1 Rh6 22. Kf1
{ There is no need to fear the capture on h2, as taking significantly misplaces the Black queen. }
22... Qxh2 23. d5 Rb6 24. e4
{ 24.Nh4  Would have been even better, cutting the Black queen away and prepare Nf5 and d5-d6. }
24... f5 25. exf5 Rb4 26. Rc4
{ White trades the only active piece of his opponent and converts comfortably. }
26... Rxc4 27. bxc4 Qh5 28. Qxh5 Rxh5 29. Ke2 b5 30. d6 Bd8 31. cxb5 axb5 32.
Ne3 Ke8 33. d7+ Ke7 34. Nd5+ { The pawn is untouchable. } 34... Kf8
{ 34...Kxd7  35.Nf6++-  And White wins the rook. } 35. f6
{ Black's king and bishop won't ever be able to move. } 35... e4 36. Ne7 b4 37.
Nc6 Bxf6 38. Rd6
{ Next, White takes the bishop and queens his pawn, so Eljanov resigned. A fantastic positional win by Oparin! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Reversed QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Ulf Andersson vs. Andras Adorjan, Amsterdam, 1978"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb2 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qd8 8. Ne4
{ White immediately uses the fact the f6-knight is pinned to put pressure on the c5-pawn and over the long diagonal. }
8... Nbd7 9. Rc1
{ Getting another piece in the game with a tempo is always nice. } 9... b6 10.
Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ 10...Bxf6!  Would have been a better move, even though Black still needs to go a long way to equalize. For example, after  11.Bxf6  Nxf6  12.Bb5+  It's nice to provoke a passive move like ...Bd7, so that the bishop won't be able to come to b7, controlling the long diagonal.  12...Bd7  13.Be2  O-O   13...Bc6  14.d4!  Will cause problems, because the c6-bishop is loose.  14...Nd7  15.dxc5!  Nxc5  Of course, ...bxc5 would have resulted in an ugly pawn structure, but the knight recapture creates tactical dangers on the c-file.  16.O-O  Now, the threat is b3-b4!, winning a piece.   16.b4?!  Qxd1+  Doesn't win a piece for White, because if the rook recaptures, the pieces on the c-file won't be in danger anymore.  16...O-O ??   16...Bb7  17.Bb5+±  And Black loses castling rights and is still clearly suffering.  17.b4+-  And White wins.  14.d4!  White is in a great position to open the game and get an advantage due to the weakened c6-square and the more active major pieces.  14...cxd4  15.Qxd4  Rc8  16.O-O  ⩲  With Bc4 and Ne5 on the way, White is still pressing.  Additionally, Ba6! is always a concern, as Black would lose control over the c-file. }
11. d4
{ Time to open up the game.   11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Be2  Would have been even better, keeping the bishops and preparing Ne5 and Bf3. }
11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 { Now, the c6-square is a large problem. } 12... O-O 13.
Be2
{ This move is a bit slow.   13.Bb5  Bb7  14.Bc6  Bxc6  15.Nxc6  Qxd1+  16.Kxd1  The knight on c6 is dominating the game, and after Ke2-Rfd1 White has a clear edge.  16...Rfe8  17.Ke2  The a8-rook still has a very hard time entering the game, as the a7-pawn would hang. }
13... Bb7 14. Bf3 Ne4 15. O-O Rc8 16. Qe2 Qd7 17. Rcd1
{ Black should be doing okay, but he still needs to be very precise. } 17...
Qe8 18. a4 Nc3 19. Bxc3 Bxf3 20. Qxf3 Rxc3 21. Qb7 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Rxb3 23. Qxa7
{ Of course, you would think Black should easily hold this, but with Ulf Andersson, you never know... }
23... e5 24. Rd7 Qe6 25. h3 Rb4
{ 25...Rc8!  Was necessary, preparing counterplay on the second rank. } 26.
Rfd1 Qf5 27. Rd8
{ 27.R7d6!  Would have immediately created an issue for the b6-pawn. } 27...
Rb2 28. R8d2 Rxd2 29. Rxd2 Qe4 30. Kh2 Ra8 31. Qxb6 Qxa4 32. Qf6
{ Black is still suffering, as the e5-pawn is weak. } 32... e4 33. Rd4 Qe8 34.
g4 { White makes room for the king, while also preparing ideas like h4-h5-h6. }
34... Rc8 35. Kg2 Rc6 36. Rd8 Rxf6 37. Rxe8+ Kg7 38. Rxe4
{ And eventually, Andersson won this endgame. } 38... Ra6 39. h4 Ra5 40. Kg3 h6
41. f4 Ra1 42. Re5 Rg1+ 43. Kf3 Rh1 44. h5 gxh5 45. Rxh5 Ra1 46. Rd5 Ra3 47.
Rd6 Rc3 48. f5 Rb3 49. Kf4 Ra3 50. Rd4 Rb3 51. e4 f6 52. Rd7+ Kg8 53. e5 fxe5+
54. Kxe5 Rg3
{ 54...Rb4!  Was the only move that would hold, and Black needed to calculate precisely that after  55.Kf6  Rxg4  56.Rd8+  Kh7  Black has no issues whatsoever. }
55. Ke6 Rxg4 56. Rd8+ Kh7 57. f6 Re4+ 58. Kf5 Re1 59. f7
{ And White queened his pawn. } 59... Rf1+ 60. Ke6 Re1+ 61. Kd6 Rd1+ 62. Kc7
Rc1+ 63. Kb6 *

[Event "?"]
