1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3
{ Let me explain a bit why I am recommending this move and what we are trying to accomplish. The variations starting with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/8/4PN2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c4  have become rather popular as of late, so, why not 3.c4?First of all, there is nothing wrong with 3.c4. In fact, I love this move and I am greatly interested in exploring it even more. However, I am afraid the potential zone for research is quite limited there, and a few recent sources, such as Alex Smith's e3-poison, Georgiev's The Modern English and Sielecki's/Hansen's 1.c4/1.Nf3 LTR all tackle that line. So, I am not sure how willing I am to follow the same line only to suggest a minor improvement on move 15. Instead, I am much more interested in investigating a fresh variation where I can suggest new ideas on move 5!Also, even more importantly, I believe the move  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/8/4PN2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 3@@EndFEN@@  3.b3  fits extremely well in the philosophy of this course. We play b2-b3 everywhere, so why not do that here, too?  Now, Black can try to stick to the QGD or Slav setup, or take advantage of the fact the center isn't under pressure yet by means of  3...Bf5  or  3...Bg4  . Very importantly, the move  3...c5  transposes to what we discuss after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.e3  c5  .   Another pretty thing about 3.b3, as opposed to 3.c4, is that it doesn't allow for ...dxc4, so the QGA players might find it hard to navigate the arising positions! }
3... e6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3
{ We are developing in a style similar to the Queen's Indian, but with colours reversed. What is the goal? Likely, a few types of positions can arise from here, all based on the pawn structures.1@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ... c7-c5 and take on d4, we will recapture with the e-pawn and attack on the kingside with Ne5, f2-f4 and typical moves of that kind.2@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ... c7-c5 and keep the tension, we will eventually push c2-c4 and one side will end up with a pair of hanging pawns.3@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ...c7-c5 and keep the tension, we will eventually push c2-c4 and both sides' d and c-pawns will be eliminated, which will result in the open center. N2 and N3 can also happen if Black waits long enough, sees us push c2-c4 and meets it with ...c7-c5.4@@EndBracket@@ Black will do nothing, we'll push c2-c4 and will just enjoy the center. }
6... b6 { The most popular continuation. } 7. O-O Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. c4 Ne4
{ If Black wants to prepare ...f7-f5, then it makes sense to hold off with ...c7-c5, so that the center remains more stable, as explained in the lines after 9...c7-c5 with ...Ne4 and ...f7-f5. }
10. Rc1 f5 11. Qe2 Bd6
{ Most Black players continued this way, which makes sense, as this move improves Black's control over the e5-square and his bishop's scope overall. }
12. Rfd1 Rf6 13. Nf1
{ This is a very common idea, the point of which is to bring the knight to g3 to neutralize Black's play on the kingside. Additionally, White is now prepared to go Ne5 and f2-f3. }
