{ Here is the position of our interest. It is very symmetrical, which certainly means it's extremely important to know of precise ideas/plans/move orders to maintain any kind of initiative. However, I can assure you, this position is by no means dull or boring.    Recently, my student rated about 2100 FIDE and I had a discussion about it. He was not entirely sure how to press, and drew a few games quickly. Well, the first thing I recommended him to do is to play it with Black against the best engine he can find and try to maintain equality for just ten moves. This task, of course, was successfully failed, which I perfectly expected, and that's totally fine.   The idea was to have him see that any equal position stops being equal after an inaccuracy or two, and those are inevitable against opponents who know a lot more ideas than we do. Needless to say, he won a couple of great games from this position after his experience with the engine, combined with us spending a fair amount of effort discussing it. But I digress. This little story aside, let's see how we can put Black under pressure. }
10. Rc1
{ We are asking Black, if he's interested in resolving the tension in the center, or if he'd rather keep it. }
10... Rc8 { Most people like to keep the tension. } 11. Qe2
{ This is also very possible, I would recommend you check our analysis after 10...Ne4, as the arising positions are nearly identical. }
