3... e6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3
{ We are developing in a style similar to the Queen's Indian, but with colours reversed. What is the goal? Likely, a few types of positions can arise from here, all based on the pawn structures.1@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ... c7-c5 and take on d4, we will recapture with the e-pawn and attack on the kingside with Ne5, f2-f4 and typical moves of that kind.2@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ... c7-c5 and keep the tension, we will eventually push c2-c4 and one side will end up with a pair of hanging pawns.3@@EndBracket@@ Black will play ...c7-c5 and keep the tension, we will eventually push c2-c4 and both sides' d and c-pawns will be eliminated, which will result in the open center. N2 and N3 can also happen if Black waits long enough, sees us push c2-c4 and meets it with ...c7-c5.4@@EndBracket@@ Black will do nothing, we'll push c2-c4 and will just enjoy the center. }
6... b6 { The most popular continuation. } 7. O-O Bb7 8. Nbd2 Nbd7 9. c4 c5
{ Here is the position of our interest. It is very symmetrical, which certainly means it's extremely important to know of precise ideas/plans/move orders to maintain any kind of initiative. However, I can assure you, this position is by no means dull or boring.    Recently, my student rated about 2100 FIDE and I had a discussion about it. He was not entirely sure how to press, and drew a few games quickly. Well, the first thing I recommended him to do is to play it with Black against the best engine he can find and try to maintain equality for just ten moves. This task, of course, was successfully failed, which I perfectly expected, and that's totally fine.   The idea was to have him see that any equal position stops being equal after an inaccuracy or two, and those are inevitable against opponents who know a lot more ideas than we do. Needless to say, he won a couple of great games from this position after his experience with the engine, combined with us spending a fair amount of effort discussing it. But I digress. This little story aside, let's see how we can put Black under pressure. }
10. Rc1
{ We are asking Black, if he's interested in resolving the tension in the center, or if he'd rather keep it. }
10... Rc8 { Most people like to keep the tension. } 11. cxd5
{ White has many ways of handling this, but let's check the direct path.  What if we take? }
11... exd5
{ This move is rather ambitious, because Black aims at playing with hanging pawns as opposed to liquidating the center. }
12. Qe2
{ This is a rather attractive position for White, because to achieve the perfect setup with ...Bd6 and ...Qe7 @@StartBracket@@to control the e5-square@@EndBracket@@, Black will need to waste time, as he already played ...Be7.  Now, our goals will involve trading the bishops with Ba6 to increase pressure on the queenside and the hanging pawns.   Additionally, it would often be a very worthy idea to play Rfd1 and then - attention, remember this plan! - Nf1-g3! This little knight journey will allow us to solidify our kingside, potentially throw the horsey at that lovely f5 square or force the weakening move ...g7-g6, which will make the b2-bishop rather excited. Furthermore, it's not too bad an idea to remove the knight from the d-file, so that the rook can put more pressure on the d5-pawn. Knowing this simple plan will give you a very easy time in the middlegame. }
12... Ne4 13. Rfd1 f5
{ There weren't too many high-level games that reached this position, but most of them continued with Black trying to reinforce the e4-knight this way. }
14. Ba6 { White has a strong pressure. } 14... Bxa6 15. Qxa6
{ To deal with the queenside pressure is no easy feat. For example, let's see what happens if a queen or a rook steps on c7.   By the way, while taking the a7-pawn might not be an achievement in itself as ...Ra8 will regain the a2-pawn, it's important that Black also has a huge issue with the d5-pawn @@StartBracket@@for instance, Qb7-Qxd5 might be very painful@@EndBracket@@. In the spirit of harassing the d5-pawn, we can also go Nf1-g3 and dxc5 at some point, whenever appropriate. }
15... Qc7
{ Exposes the queen and makes the e7-bishop loose, which can be punished very fast. }
16. dxc5 Ndxc5 17. Qe2
{ A very comfortable version of the IQP for White to play against, because the move ...f7-f5 weakened the long diagonal and the e6-square. On top of that, b3-b4 is about to win a piece at the moment, which will make Black waste even more time. }
