[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-QGD and Anti-QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Shakhriyar Mamedyarov vs.  Andrey Esipenko, Moscow, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 e6 3. Bb2 d5 4. e3 Be7 5. d4 O-O 6. Bd3 c5
{ Black abstains from playing ...b7-b6. } 7. Nbd2
{ For now, White keeps the tension. } 7... Nc6 8. dxc5
{ Opening up the diagonal and preparing the queenside expansion. } 8... Bxc5 9.
a3 { White is about to grab more space with b3-b4. } 9... Qe7 10. c4 a5 11. Qc2
{ Now, the h7-pawn is under pressure. } 11... Bd6 12. O-O
{ 12.Bxf6?  With the hanging rook on a1, winning the pawn would have been premature.  12...Qxf6  13.Bxh7+  Kh8  14.O-O  g6!  And Black wins the bishop. }
12... h6 13. e4
{ An interesting plan: White is opening up the center.   13.cxd5  Would have been very strong as well, the point being to either force an isolated pawn position, or after  13...Nxd5  14.Ne4!  Bc7  15.Rfd1  To create some very powerful pressure on the queenside, and now Black's queenside pieces are very passive. }
13... dxc4
{ 13...dxe4  14.Bxf6!  is even better,  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2qpp1/2nbpn1p/p7/2P1p3/PP1B1N2/1BQN1PPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@ the point being that after  14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Bxe4  would have resulted in a position where Black's queenside pieces are rather stuck, next the simple Rfe1 and Rad1 will be played.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/1p2qpp1/2nbpB1p/p7/2P1p3/PP1B1N2/2QN1PPP/R4RK1 b - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qxf6  15.Nxe4  Qe7  16.Nxd6  Qxd6  17.c5!  White grabs space on the queenside.  17...Qe7  18.Bh7+!  Kh8  19.Be4⩲  Having lured the king as far away from the center as possible, White returns the bishop to the h1-a8 diagonal. }
14. Nxc4 { Now, the threat is Nxd6 and e4-e5!, winning a piece. } 14... Bc5
{ 14...Bc7  15.e5!  Nd5  16.Bh7+  Kh8  17.Be4±  Black's pieces are incredibly passive, now Rad1 is about to be played, the d5-knight would be under pressure. Later, White can prepare a maneuver like Rd3-g3 or h3!?, preparing some kingside attack! }
15. Rad1 { Another piece joins the game. } 15... Rd8 16. e5
{ Time to grab space and secure an outpost on d6. } 16... Nd5 17. Bh7+
{ This typical idea, which we've already seen so many times, is very well worth remembering: instead of just playing Be4, why not worsen the opponent king's position first? }
17... Kh8 18. Be4
{ There is no rush, White is just improving the position. For example, Rd3-Rfd1 can be played next. It is worth mentioning that the c8-bishop is stuck and cannot come out, as that would leave the d5-knight insufficiently defended. Of course, if the bishop isn't coming out, neither is the a8-rook. }
18... Rb8 19. Qc1 { This move prepares a very cool trap. } 19... Kg8
{ 19...b5?  20.Nd6!  Is the point. Now, the c5-bishop is hanging, while after  20...Bxd6  21.exd6  Qxd6  22.Qxh6++-  White suddenly unleashes the power of his b2-bishop and checkmates the unsuspecting opponent! }
20. Bb1
{ Now, Qc2 is about to create new attacking ideas. Importantly, in order to prevent ...g7-g6, we can first go h2-h4-h5! }
20... b6 21. h4 Qf8 22. h5
{ Now, everything is ready for Qc2 with mating threats. } 22... Nce7 23. Rfe1
Kh8 24. Qc2 Qg8 { Somehow, Black is still surviving. } 25. Nd6
{ White is threatening Nxf7+, taking advantage of the fact the Black queen is overworked. }
25... Bxd6 26. exd6 Rxd6
{ 26...Nf5  27.Qd2!  Wins on the spot due to threats like Bxf5 and Qxh6+, or g2-g4! and then Qxh6. }
27. Be5 { White collects the material and easily converts his advantage. }
27... Nf5 28. Bxd6 Nxd6 29. Rxd5 exd5 30. Qc7
{ Black resigned, as soon he'll be a piece down. A very impressive use of the initiative by White! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-QGD and Anti-QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Raja Panjwani vs. Lazaro Bruzon Batista , Calgary, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. b3
{ This setup can appear even from the Symmetrical English, which is a good thing for those of you who start with 1. c4 or 1.Nf3 and 2.c4 to keep in mind. }
3... e6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. d4 cxd4 7. exd4 d5
{ Of course, soon enough the position with hanging pawns can arise. } 8. Bd3 b6
9. O-O Bb7 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. Qe2
{ Black rightfully delays ...dxc4, keeping the tension. Meanwhile, White is making typical moves that are improving the position. For example, Rfd1, Rac1, Nf1-e3 are all very typical moves. }
11... Rc8 12. Rac1 g6
{ Black safeguards the b1-h7 diagonal. Later, he might play ...Re8 and ...Bf8-g7.   12...dxc4  13.bxc4  Would give White extra opportunities related to d4-d5 or c4-c5. }
13. Rfd1 Re8 14. Nf1 Bf8
{ Just as planned: Black is bringing an extra defender to the kingside. } 15.
Ne3 Bg7 16. Ne5 dxc4 17. Bxc4
{ An interesting decision: White is happy to accept an isolated pawn. Now, Bb5! is about to create significant pressure on the pinned d7-knight as well as on the c6-square.   17.bxc4  Nxe5!  18.dxe5  Nd7  Is the point, giving White a rather suspicious pawn structure and creating an outpost on c5.  19.c5!  Is the key idea for White, unexpectedly freeing up the d6-square for the knight.  19...Nxc5?   19...bxc5  20.Bb5!  Bc6  21.a4  White has great compensation for the missing pawn and is about to follow up with Nc4-d6, obtaining some rather promising initiative.  20.Bb5±  Wins an exchange. }
17... Nb8 18. Bb5 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Re7 20. Qc4
{ Ba3! is about to win an exchange, as White's last move prevented the rook from escaping via c7. }
20... Nd5 21. Nxd5 exd5 22. Qc3 Qd6 23. Qg3
{ Both Black bishops are rather useless.  Now, White creates a threat of Nxg6!, as that b8-knight would hang, too! }
23... Rc7 24. Re1 Bf8
{ This move seems rather natural, as it defends the queen, but it happens to be a tactical blunder. }
25. Ba3 { All of a sudden, a very nice tactic appears. } 25... Qxa3 26. Nxg6
hxg6 27. Qxc7 { And soon enough, White won. } 27... Qb4 28. Re8 Ba6 29. a4 Bxb5
30. axb5 Qxb3 31. g3
{ White creates an escape square and eliminates all kinds of possible counterplay on the first rank, while the b8-knight would be lost on the next move. }
31... Qxb5 32. Qxb8 Qb4 33. Qxa7 Kg7 34. Qb8 Bd6 35. Qd8 b5 36. Kg2
{ And Black resigned, as White is so much material up and has a mating attack. As we see, the fight was very complex for a long time, but eventually, Black made a tactical blunder and got destroyed.  These are very promising positions to go for if you are looking to outplay a weaker player without trading pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-QGD and Anti-QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Hikaru Nakamura vs. Fabiano Caruana, Chess.com, 2017 "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 c5 4. e3 e6
{ Again, we arrive at the position we're familiar with. } 5. d4 Be7 6. Bd3 O-O
7. dxc5
{ White chooses to open up the game, which is one of the variation we've covered. }
7... Nc6 8. a3 { White is about to hold his extra pawn with b3-b4. } 8... a5
{ Black prevents b3-b4. } 9. O-O Bxc5 10. Nbd2 Qe7 11. e4
{ Instead of playing for c2-c4 with initiative on the queenside, White breaks through in the center, which is also very reasonable path. }
11... dxe4 12. Nxe4
{ 12.Bxf6  Is also a good path, for example  12...Qxf6  13.Nxe4  Qe7  14.Nxc5  Qxc5  15.Qd2  White has the initiative, because Black cannot develop his queenside. For example, after  15...Bd7?  16.Bxh7+!  White wins a pawn. }
12... Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Bd7
{ Black is still rather passive, the queenside doesn't look great. } 14. Qe2
Rad8 15. Rfd1 h6 16. c3
{ White prepares Bc2 followed by Qe4, building a kingside attack. } 16... Bd6
17. Bc2 Bc7 18. b4
{ White is building pressure on the queenside, looking to play b4-b5. } 18...
Bc8 19. b5 Nb8 20. a4
{ White grabbed a huge amount of space and now the Black minor pieces are very inactive. }
20... Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Rd8 22. Nd2
{ 22.Rxd8+  Qxd8  23.Qe4!  Would have been better, as it'd provoke a lot of weaknesses on the kingside.  23...g6  24.c4±  Now, the long dark diagonal is very weak as well! If White is allowed to play Qe3-c3 and build a decisive kingside attack, that'd be over in no time. }
22... Nd7 23. Nc4 Nb6 24. Ba3
{ The d6-square and the long a3-f8 diagonal is also a huge problem. } 24...
Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Bxh2+
{ Caruana opts for a seemingly attractive tactic, but it turns out to be losing the game right away. }
26. Kxh2
{ 26.Kf1!  Would have won the piece, as the Black queen is hanging and g2-g3 is about to trap the bishop.  26...Qc7  27.Nxb6  Qxb6  28.g3+-  Following Kg2, White wins the bishop easily. }
26... Qh4+ 27. Kg1 Nxc4 28. Bc5
{ Despite being a pawn down, White is still much better due to the bishop pair and Black's weak king. }
28... b6 29. Qd3 g6
{ 29...bxc5  30.Qh7+  Kf8  31.Qh8+  Ke7  32.Qxc8  Would have been Black's only chance, because despite White's protected passed pawn on b5, his king is weak, so Black has hopes to give a perpetual. }
30. Bd4 e5 31. Qxc4 Be6
{ Black gets the piece back. The rest was very messy, but eventually White prevailed. }
32. Qc7 exd4 33. Qxb6 dxc3 34. Qxa5 Qd4 35. b6 Bd5 36. Qb5 Bb7
{ 36...Qd2!  Black has to play for the perpetual immediately, intending Qc1+ Kh2 Qf4+, for example. }
37. a5 Qg4 { 37...Qd2!  Was a bit more straightforward, attacking the bishop. }
38. Qe8+ Kg7 39. Qe5+ Kh7 40. Qg3 Qd7
{ Black blunders the crucial pawn, now it's over.   40...Qc4!  Would have maintained the balance, because White cannot use the bishop, as it's stuck dealing with the passed pawn, and his king is also rather weak. }
41. Qxc3 Qd5 42. Qf3
{ White is looking to force the trade, of course, as he'll easily queen his pawns in the endgame. }
42... Qd7 43. Be4 Bxe4 44. Qxe4 Qd1+ 45. Kh2 Qh5+ 46. Kg3 Qg5+ 47. Kf3
{ 47.Kh3!  Would have escaped checks a lot more easily, for instance  47...Qxa5  48.b7  Qh5+  49.Qh4  Qe5  50.f3+-  Now there's no more checks and Qg3 followed by b7-b8Q wins on the spot. }
47... Qh5+ 48. Kg3 Qg5+ 49. Kf3 Qxa5 50. b7 Qa3+ 51. Ke2 Qb2+ 52. Kf3
{ Black was still holding, but it's tricky, and eventually, with it being a blitz game, Caruana went wrong. }
52... Qb3+ 53. Kf4 Qb2 54. Kg3 h5 55. f4 Qb3+ 56. Kh2 h4 57. Qf3 Qb4 58. Kh3
Kh6 59. Kxh4 Qb1 60. Kg3 Qe1+ 61. Kh2 Qb1 62. Qd5 Qe1 63. Qg5+
{ Black resigned, as next White queens the pawn. For us, the way the endgame was handled is irrelevant, but what's important is that White got a considerable advantage in the opening phase due to his activity in the center, while Black's queenside was always rather passive. Eventually, White managed to get a bishop pair and weaken Black's king, and eventually some mess occured, but we've learned how to handle the opening and the middlegame even better. }
