[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-QGD and Anti-QID: Model Games"]
[Black "Julio E. Granda Zuniga  vs. Manuel Larrea,  Florianopolis, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ Here, the opening went differently, but soon it tranposed to our repertoire. }
1... b6 2. Bb2 Bb7 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. d4 c5 6. Bd3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Qe2
{ White keeps developing his pieces, preparing for exchanges in the center. Of course, he is ready for a position with hanging pawns. }
8... Nc6 9. a3 { This move prevents ...Nb4. } 9... d6
{ This game would be valuable for us to learn from, because this time Black abstained from playing in a more challenging way in the center with ...d7-d5, instead going for a more complex setup that aims to retain the central pawns. }
10. c4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. Rad1
{ As we can see, White is in no rush to take drastic action. Instead, he's just improving his pieces, getting them ready for the middlegame. Next, White can improve his other rook with Rfe1, go Bb1, etc. }
12... g6 13. Bb1 Bg7
{ The bishop comes to g7 to safeguard Black's kingside another time, but this idea is tactically flawed. }
14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Ne4
{ With this forcing sequence, White manages to attack and win the d6-pawn. Now, the rest is a matter of technique. }
16... Qe7 17. Nxd6 Red8 18. Nxb7 { Time to deprive Black of the bishop pair. }
18... Qxb7 19. Be4
{ The c6-knight is pinned, which causes Black lots of inconvenience. } 19... f5
20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1
{ White adheres to a dead-simple strategy of swapping pieces. } 22... Qb6 23.
Rxd8+ Qxd8 24. e4 { Time to expose the weakened Black king. } 24... Bb2 25.
exf5 exf5 26. h4
{ White is happy to sacrifice the a3-pawn to cause havoc on the kingside. }
26... Qf6
{ 26...Bxa3  27.Qe6+!  Kf8  28.Ne5  White generates a decisive mating attack, as the a3-bishop is now completely off the game. }
27. Qe8+ Kg7 28. Ng5 h6 29. Qd7+ Kg8 30. Qh7+ Kf8 31. Qxh6+
{ White picks another pawn. Now, it's over. } 31... Ke8 32. Nf3 f4 33. h5
{ White tears the Black kingside apart even more. } 33... Bxa3 34. hxg6 a5 35.
Qh5 Kf8 36. Ng5 Qa1+ 37. Kh2 Bb2 38. Qh7
{ And Black resigned, as he's either getting mated, or is losing a piece after }
38... Bg7 39. Ne6+
{ And White trades queens with a check. A great positional game, where White very easily expoited opponent's pawn weaknesses. }
