[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bf5 setups with 4.Ba3!? g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Ba3
{ Chess of the 21st century at its best! The idea is very simple - we want to make it as inconvenient for Black as possible to go ...e7-e6. Now, Black has a couple of options. He can choose to play ...e7-e6 anyway, wait or stick to the setups with ...g7-g6 instead, claiming that the bishop on a3 is not placed optimally. We won't discuss this line too deeply as my main suggestion is another move, however, I still wanted to bring this to your attention! }
4... g6 { Does not lead to an easy equality, though. } 5. d4 Bg7 6. Bd3
{ We are just finishing the development. The main aspiration we have is that the g7-bishop is rather misplaced, so we are hoping to take advantage of the somewhat more active bishop. }
6... Bxd3 7. Qxd3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Nbd2
{ Later, we can play either c2-c4 or e3-e4. Again, this is a typical position where White can hope for a miniscule advantage due to his extra space and the more active bishop. Nothing serious, but on the other hand, this was an extremely easy line to take up and Black is still not completely equal, as the g7-bishop is a rather bad piece here. }
