[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bf5 setups with 4.Ba3!? e6 - what not to do"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Ba3
{ Chess of the 21st century at its best! The idea is very simple - we want to make it as inconvenient for Black as possible to go ...e7-e6.   Now, Black has a couple of options. He can choose to play ...e7-e6 anyway, wait or stick to the setups with ...g7-g6 instead, claiming that the bishop on a3 is not placed optimally. We won't discuss this line too deeply as my main suggestion is another move, however, I still wanted to bring this up to your attention! }
4... e6
{ This move has been played once only by a 2040-rated player, but there is nothing wrong with it. }
5. Bxf8 Kxf8 6. d4 g6 7. c4 Kg7 8. Nc3 c6 9. Bd3
{ We trade the bishops and get an objectively equal position, but Black did have to jump through a hoop or two to get his king and rook coordinated. }
9... Bxd3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bf5 setups with 4.Ba3!? e6 - trying to apply slight pressure"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Ba3
{ Chess of the 21st century at its best! The idea is very simple - we want to make it as inconvenient for Black as possible to go ...e7-e6.   Now, Black has a couple of options. He can choose to play ...e7-e6 anyway, wait or stick to the setups with ...g7-g6 instead, claiming that the bishop on a3 is not placed optimally. We won't discuss this line too deeply as my main suggestion is another move, however, I still wanted to bring this up to your attention! }
4... e6
{ This move has been played once only by a 2040-rated player, but there is nothing wrong with it. }
5. Bxf8 Kxf8 6. d4 g6 7. c4 Kg7 8. Nc3 c6 9. Be2
{ There is nothing wrong with Black's position, but I still feel suspicious about the fact he had to play ...g7-g6 alongside with ...e7-e6 and ...Bf5, as now multiple dark squares @@StartBracket@@f6, for example@@EndBracket@@ got weakened and the f5-bishop would always be in a tough spot, likely to get trapped sometime later. But, admittedly, if Black plays carefully, he should be doing okay. }
9... Ne4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. O-O Bxf3
{ Black immediately trades down this potentially problematic piece and guarantees himself a comfortable position. }
12. Bxf3 Nd7 13. Qc2
{ White's next moves will be Rab1, b2-b4, a2-a4, b4-b5, etc. I think it's a bit nicer to have the White pieces here, however, I cannot offer too much. }
