[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bf5 setups with 4.Bb2 e6 5.Nh4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Bb2 e6 5. Nh4
{ This is another rather fresh and creative idea that Nakamura used on several occasions in 2019-2021. We are immediately going after our opponent's bishop pair. }
5... Bg6
{ Is not a terrible move at all, but it's clearly unambitious, as Black immediately makes the kind of positional concession we are after. }
6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. g3
{ The other bishop certainly belongs on the long diagonal. Besides, as we opened the h-file, it makes sense to get an extra defender on the kingside and block the h2-b8 diagonal. The play here will be idea-based, so we will look at a model game, but let's proceed with a possible logical sequence for now. }
7... c5
{ Seems too ambitious, as Black weakens the h1-a8 diagonal after giving up his light-squared bishop. }
8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. c4 { Of course! Time to strike in the center. } 10...
dxc4
{ If Black were to instead castle, we could quietly develop with Qe2 and then prepare Rd1 and d2-d4, looking to break the center open and use our potent bishops. }
11. bxc4
{ Gives White fantastic control over the center. Next, we'll proceed with Qe2, Nc3, d2-d3, Rfd1, etc. }
11... O-O 12. Qe2
{ It's not obvious what Black should do from here, while our next moves are very natural, and later on, we can either break through in the center with d4-d5 at some point, or even consider attacking the oppponent's king with h2-h4, Bf3, Kg2, h4-h5, Rh1, etc. Alongside with the powerful b2-bishop, this attack can succeed rather easily, actually. }
