[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bf5 setups with 4.Bb2 e6 5.Nh4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Bb2 e6 5. Nh4
{ This is another rather fresh and creative idea that Nakamura used on several occasions in 2019-2021. We are immediately going after opponent's bishop pair. }
5... Bg6
{ Is not a terrible move at all, but it's clearly unambitious, as Black immediately makes the kind of positional concession we are after. }
6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. g3
{ The other bishop certainly belongs on the long diagonal. Besides, as we opened the h-file, it makes sense to get an extra defender on the kingside and block the h2-b8 diagonal. The play here will be idea-based, so we will look at a model game, but let's proceed with a possible logical sequence for now. }
7... c6 8. Bg2 Nbd7 9. d3 Bd6 10. Nd2
{ White is developing in a very flexible manner, not defining the situation in the center just yet. However, we can always do so: mostly, by means of c2-c4, but potentially e3-e4 or even b3-b4-b5 could be valid ideas. Additionally, it's not unreasonable to expect the plan of f2-f4, Nf3-e5, g4-g5, etc with a typical London or Dutch-style kingside attack to work great. }
10... a5
{ Black is looking to grab space on the queenside and create a one-sided tension after ... a5-a4, as after that move, we would never want to capture due to our pawn structure being ruined, while he would be able to take on b3 or push ... a4-a3 whenever he wants. So, we prevent that idea. }
11. a3 Qc7
{ Moves such as  11....e5  or @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p1n1pp1/2pbpnp1/p2p4/8/PP1PP1P1/1BPN1PBP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...O-O  seem viable alternatives here. We don't need to train several extra variations, but what I want you to remember is that attempts to grab space with ...e7-e5 always weaken the d5-pawn and make the c2-c4 and e2-e4 breaks a lot more attractive. Instead, short castling gives up the h-file and makes it more appropriate for White to also castle short if he wants to. }
12. Qe2 Be5 13. c3 { White keeps the bishop pair. } 13... g5 14. h3
{ Preventing ... g5-g4, which would restrict the kingside. } 14... Bd6 15. c4
{ Time to start active action. The position might not look very active for now, but White will surely slowly unravel, and his bishop pair will be extremely useful in the future. }
15... Be5 16. d4 Bd6 17. O-O-O
{ A very creative and strong decision. Of course, there is no attack to fear on the queenside, as ...a5-a4 will be always met with b3-b4, and if needed, Kb1 and Rc1. At the same time, White is well-prepared to open the center with e3-e4! and d4-d5!, especially if Black doesn't castle. }
17... O-O-O 18. Kb1
{ And we will play on the c-file with Rc1, Rc2-Rhc1, potentially cxd5 or c4-c5 and b3-b4, grabbing space and slowly suffocating Black, who has no active play, since attempts to open the game with ...c6-c5 or ...e6-e5 will only help our gorgeous g2-bishop spring to life. }
