{ Black is looking to grab space on the queenside and create a one-sided tension after ... a5-a4, as after that move, we would never want to capture due to our pawn structure being ruined, while he would be able to take on b3 or push ... a4-a3 whenever he wants. So, we prevent that idea. }
11. a3 Qc7 12. Qe2 Be5 13. c3 { White keeps the bishop pair. } 13... g5 14. h3
{ Preventing ... g5-g4, which would restrict the kingside. } 14... Bd6 15. c4
{ Time to start active action. The position might not look very active for now, but White will surely slowly unravel, and his bishop pair will be extremely useful in the future. }
15... Be5 16. d4 Bd6 17. O-O-O
{ A very creative and strong decision. Of course, there is no attack to fear on the queenside, as ...a5-a4 will be always met with b3-b4, and if needed, Kb1 and Rc1. At the same time, White is well-prepared to open the center with e3-e4! and d4-d5!, especially if Black doesn't castle. }
17... O-O
{ And now my suggestion would be: 1/2 @@StartBracket@@76@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H  @@StartBracket@@3226@@EndBracket@@-Gordievsky,D @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
18. g4
{ Next, we go h3-h4 and the kingside falls apart, White is completely winning. }
