[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bf5 4. Bb2 e6 5. Nh4
{ This is another rather fresh and creative idea that Nakamura used on several occasions in 2019-2021. We are immediately going after opponent's bishop pair. }
5... Bg4 6. Be2 Bxe2 7. Qxe2
{ The knight on h4 looks a bit weird now, but White has ideas related to f2-f4 and Nf3-e5, and our dark-squared bishop is incredibly powerful here. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. c4
{ Nakamura decides to attack the center rather than attack on the kingside. }
9... c5 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Rd1
{ White is looking to open up the game with d2-d4 and benefit from the more active bishop on b2, compared to Black's passive one on e7. }
11... d4
{ Robson makes an ambitious choice of going for the Benoni structure.  This pawn push is very common in these types of pawn structures and white needs to remain aware of this possibility, which aims to grab space in the centre. }
12. exd4 cxd4 13. d3
{ This resulted in a tense position, where the chances are objectively equal, but I would think it's easier to play with White, because in these Benoni positions the more pieces are traded, the easier it is to play for the side with less space and a queenside majority, which in this case is White, of course. But, again, I would rather handle this in a completely different way, as I mentioned earlier, so if you like these positions, stick with them, but if not, follow the main recommendation! 1-0 @@StartBracket@@73@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Robson,R  @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
