[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "Black just wastes a tempo"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ Is a move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book 'Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings'. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open. Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book 'Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6'. So, we can kill two birds with one stone if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bf5 { Makes no sense, why not 3...Bf5 then? } *

