[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bg4 with 4...Bxf3 - transposition into lines below"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ This is the move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open.   Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6. So, we can kill two birds with one shot if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bxf3
{ is a move that can have either of the two ideas behind it. It can either be an attempt to avoid any potential complications and tactical issues related to the bishop's position on h5 by trading and playing in a solid manner with ...e7-e6, ...c7-c6, etc, or an attempt to take the entire center with ...e7-e5! If we play d2-d4 in these solid Slav setups, Black might be rather solid... However, the pawn is still on d2, so we have some additional cool ideas! }
5. Qxf3 c6 { An attempt to build a solid position. } 6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. g4
{ 80 games reached this position, 7.g4! was chosen in 20 of them, which makes it the most popular move - and for a good reason. Since White hasn't started any activity in the center with c2-c4 or d2-d4 yet, he hasn't created any targets for Black to counterattack, and he is ready to launch a kingside offensive. }
7... e5 { This transposes to the lines covered after 5...e5. } *

