1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ This is the move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open.   Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6. So, we can kill two birds with one shot if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bxf3
{ is a move that can have either of the two ideas behind it. It can either be attempt to avoid any potential complications and tactical issues related to the bishop's position on h5 by trading and playing in a solid manner with ...e7-e6, ...c7-c6, etc, or an attempt to take the entire center with ...e7-e5! If we play d2-d4 in these solid Slav setups, Black might be rather solid....however, the pawn is still on d2, so we have some additional cool ideas! }
5. Qxf3 e5
{ This is the main move, however, I have found an idea that makes me doubt the soundness of Black's plan. }
6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. g4
{ The idea is very simple: we are about to push g4-g5, kick the knight out and win the d5-pawn! }
7... c6 8. c4
{ Black's center is under a ton of pressure, as g4-g5 is coming. This position was seen in three games, and Black players have tested such moves as 8...e4, kicking the queen out, or 8...Bd6, just developing. }
8... Bd6 9. g5 Ne4
{ This is pretty much Black's only move - what else can he do? Otherwise, the d5-pawn would fall to the attack of the c4-pawn and the queen. }
10. cxd5 { Now, the e4-knight is hanging. } 10... cxd5 11. Nc3
{ Finally we are getting to that d5-pawn! } 11... Nxg5 12. Qxd5
{ Is horrible for Black, since our pieces are much more active @@StartBracket@@look at that d5-queen!@@EndBracket@@, our development is significantly superior @@StartBracket@@all the White pieces are in the game, he is ready to castle long, go Bc4, Bb5 or even Bg2@@EndBracket@@ and, very importantly, we have a semi-open g-file that would come extremely handy soon, since Black will definitely castle short....just to run into a checkmate! Also, Black is losing the pawn pretty much now, which doesn't help, either! }
12... Be7 13. Qxb7 { We collect a free pawn. } *

