[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bg4 with 4...Bh5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ This is the move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open.   Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6. So, we can kill two birds with one shot if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bh5 5. Bb2 Nbd7
{ Is a move order suggested by both Mikhalievski and Kornev. } 6. g4
{ I like the idea of playing this chess of the 21st century, where we immediately harass the bishop, ignoring the potential weakening of our kingside, as we are more interested in concrete ideas. Importantly, Mikhalevski does not analyze this continuation at all, while Kornev mentions it, but only focuses on 7.Nh4 rather than our 7.g5. And just like that, we've tricked two more major authors :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... Bg6 7. g5
{ This move was recently tried by Artemiev in three games, which obviously means we should pay attention to it. }
7... Ne4 8. h4
{ We are looking to pursue the bishop with h4-h5. Here, Shirov tried to prevent that with ...h7-h6, which results in some very interesting complications, while Jakovenko and two other players went for ...Bh5. }
8... Bh5
{ This continuation is a lot safer than ...h7-h6, which allows for a very scary exchange sacrifice. }
9. d3 { White kicks the knight away, making room for his own knight on d2. }
9... Nd6 10. Be2
{ Now, the main strength of our position is the b2-bishop, which is making the conventional development like ...e7-e6 and ...Be7 very difficult, as the g7-pawn would be hanging at all times. }
10... h6
{ That's why in both GM-level games Black tried undermining the g5-pawn first. }
11. Nbd2 e6 12. Rg1
{ White is creating ideas on the g-file, such as gxh6 followed by capturing on g7. Of course, we don't care about losing short castling rights, as the moves g2-g4-g5 and h2-h4 must have been a clear indication we had no desire to castle short. Instead, we'll move the queen out of the way, most likely to c2 after c2-c4, and will castle long. }
12... hxg5 13. hxg5
{ Now, the funny positional threat is Rh1!, using the freshly-open h-file to pin that bishop! }
13... Bg6
{ Black prevents that. A move like 13...Nf5 could be another reasonable try, looking to overprotect the g7-pawn in order to develop the bishop, but then we just continue with c2-c4 and Qc2 anyway. Please note the knight on f5 is a bit unstable as e3-e4! could always hit it, for example, to distract it from the g7-pawn. }
14. c4
{ This move not only attacks the center, but also enables Qc2 followed by long castling. }
14... c6 15. Qc2 Qe7
{ Black moves the queen out of the way to castle long as well. } 16. Qc3
{ A very nice prophylactical move, which prevents ...e6-e5. } 16... O-O-O
{ Here, Artemiev castled, but I'd like to offer a nice improvement. } 17. Qa5
{ The White queen is very mobile and can also immediately harass the Black queenside. }
17... Kb8 18. b4
{ In this very strange position, White appears to be clearly better, as he is about to develop a strong attack on the Black king with c4-c5, a2-a4, b4-b5, Bd4, Rb1, and so on. Not an easy plan for Black to deal with at all! }
