[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ This is the move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open.   Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6. So, we can kill two birds with one shot if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bh5 5. Bb2 Nbd7
{ Is a move order suggested by both Mikhalievski and Kornev. } 6. g4
{ I like the idea of playing this chess of the 21st century, where we immediately harass the bishop, ignoring the potential weakening of our kingside, as we are more interested in concrete ideas. Importantly, Mikhalevski does not analyze this continuation at all, while Kornev mentions it, but only focuses on 7.Nh4 rather than our 7.g5. And just like that, we've tricked two more major authors :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... Bg6 7. g5
{ This move was recently tried by Artemiev in three games, which obviously means we should pay attention to it. }
7... Ne4 8. h4
{ We are looking to pursue the bishop with h4-h5. Here, Shirov tried to prevent that with ...h7-h6, which results in some very interesting complications, while Jakovenko and two other players went for ...Bh5. }
8... h6 9. h5
{ The arising exchange sacrifice idea will be really fun. Now, Black either needs to retreat, or to accept the challenge and capture on g5. }
9... Bf5 10. Nh4
{ Results in huge position problems, as the bishop barely has any retreat squares. }
10... e6 11. Nxf5 exf5 12. g6
{ Again, this idea comes in very handy, as we are looking to get a very strong pawn on g6. }
12... fxg6 13. hxg6
{ The bishop on b2 is really powerful, while the f5-pawn is rather weak, subject to attacks after Qf3 and Bh3, for instance. The f8-bishop has a hard time coming out as that would hang the g7-pawn. }
13... Ndf6 { Black needs to block the b2-bishop. } 14. Qf3
{ We are not giving the opponent a second of rest, attacking the f5-pawn right away. }
14... Qd7 { Black must defend it. } 15. Bxf6
{ We are happy to give up the strong bishop to either completely ruin his pawn structure, or to win more time. }
15... Nxf6 16. Bd3
{ Again, the f5-pawn is in trouble, as the natural defense fails. } 16... Ne4
17. Rh5
{ I know this must look like some really creative chess, but now White simply wins a pawn and gets a winning endgame. For example, after }
17... Be7 18. Qxf5 Qxf5 19. Rxf5
{ We are just a pawn up and are technically winning. It was certainly an unexpected line, wasn't it? }
