{ We immediately make sure we get the bishop pair, while following the footsteps of Nakamura, Grischuk, Edouard, and many other strong GMs. }
6... Bg6 7. Ne5 Nbd7
{ Black immediately makes us go after the bishop or release the tension in some other way. }
8. Nxg6 { Of course, White is interested in this bishop. } 8... hxg6 9. Nc3
{ This move and the idea behind it prove that the author went nuts after analyzing this position too much. On a serious note, it's a weird way to get a fresh atypical game. }
9... g5
{ Otherwise, I could be interested in pushing g4-g5 myself. With this move, Black fixes the weakish h3-pawn while also stopping any potential g4-g5 ideas in the future. }
10. Qe2 Be7 11. Bg2 c6 12. O-O-O
{ Now, White is about to do something quite fun. Let's make a random move to see what this is. }
12... a6 13. h4 gxh4 14. g5 Nh7 15. f4
{ We will surely get the pawn back, but now the Black pieces are totally paralyzed. Obviously, this is not something Black should want! }
