13. Kb1 { We are stopping it, as ...Ba3 will be met with Ba1. } 13... O-O-O 14.
f4 gxf4 15. exf4
{ I will cut this line short here to conclude that we have a rather interesting position where White's plan will involve pushing the kingside pawns with h3-h4-h5, g4-g5, etc. The bad news is that this position is a bit too weird for crystal-clear plans to exist, besides the aforementioned pawn storm. However, first of all, we get a totally unexplored game as early as after 7-8 moves, and secondly, this is quite promising from the analytical perspective, too! Where else can you get such fresh positions versus the Slav-type setups?! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bg4 with 4...Bh5 - let's not give up the h5-square"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ This is the move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open.   Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6. So, we can kill two birds with one shot if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bh5 5. Bb2 e6 6. g4
{ We immediately make sure we get the bishop pair, while following the footsteps of Nakamura, Grischuk, Edouard, and many other strong GMs. }
6... Bg6 7. Ne5 Nbd7
{ Black immediately makes us go after the bishop or release the tension in some other way. }
8. Nxg6 { Of course, White is interested in this bishop. } 8... hxg6 9. Bg2 Bd6
{ Black just keeps developing. Of course, a move like ...c7-c6 would transpose in a move or two. }
10. h4 c6 11. g5 Nh5
{ Does not seem to be the right plan, as it gives up the h5 square. The engines like this idea a lot, but it's not very clear how to play later with White. So, let's rather keep the tension! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav setups"]
[Black "3...Bg4 with 4...Bh5 #12 - space advantage and bishop pair"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 Bg4
{ This is the move suggested by GM Mikhalevski in his book Grandmaster Repertoire - Beating Minor Openings. The key difference between this and the Slav setup with ...c7-c6 and ...Bg4 is that Black chooses to not commit to ...c7-c6 yet, which leaves the options of ...c7-c5, or of ...Nd7 and quick ...e7-e5 open.   Additionally, it is proposed by GM Kornev in his book Practical Black repertoire with d5, c6. So, we can kill two birds with one shot if we find a way to pose problems here! Spoiler: we will find a way :@@EndBracket@@ }
4. h3
{ I believe it is rather vital to immediately make Black decide whether he wants to give up the bishop pair in the hopes of getting a slightly inferior but solid position, or whether he is comfortable about the idea of keeping the tension. }
4... Bh5 5. Bb2 e6 6. g4
{ We immediately make sure we get the bishop pair, while following the footsteps of Nakamura, Grischuk, Edouard, and many other strong GMs. }
6... Bg6 7. Ne5 Nbd7
{ Black immediately makes us go after the bishop or release the tension in some other way. }
8. Nxg6 { Of course, White is interested in this bishop. } 8... hxg6 9. Bg2 Bd6
{ Black just keeps developing. Of course, a move like ...c7-c6 would transpose in a move or two. }
10. d3 c6 11. Nd2 Qc7 12. Qe2
{ Again, we have a highly original position where White has set his pieces up in Hedgehog style, having grabbed the bishop pair along the way.   Here is how I would explain what's happening: Black is very solid in the center, but an attempt to play in the center with ...e6-e5 will weaken it and allow for the powerful c2-c4 break. At the same time, castling short is simply very dangerous because White can castle long or even keep the king in the center and push h3-h4-h5, g4-g5, etc. If that happens, the bishop on b2 will become extremely powerful, Black is likely to run into a fierce attack. Instead, if Black castles long, White can either also castle long and play a quiet positional game, or...keep the king in the center and push c2-c4 and then play a2-a3, b3-b4-b5 and try to attack on the queenside!   As you can see, White's options are really open, which makes me highly interested in both playing and recommending this setup. @@StartBracket@@Even though, admittedly, this is a lot more about understanding than about forcing lines, Black did not have to go exactly for this very position, but plans would have remained identical regardless@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav: Model Games"]
[Black "Maxim Matlakov vs. Grigory Gusarov, Chess.com, 2021 "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 c6 3. Bb2 Nf6 4. e3 Bg4 5. h3 Bxf3 6. Qxf3
{ This is another position we should gladly accept, because we simply get the bishop pair for no compensation. }
6... Nbd7 7. g4
{ White can easily afford to grab space and potentially prepare g4-g5. } 7...
h6 8. h4
{ White keeps grabbing space, making sure g4-g5 is an idea Black always has to be aware of. }
8... e5 9. Nc3 Bd6 10. O-O-O
{ White's king is perfectly safe on the queenside, so now it's a question of what to do with the black one. Short castling will likely get Black mated, while long castling is safe, but fairly slow and inactive. }
10... e4
{ Black opens the h2-b8 diagonal and gets the e5-square for his pieces. However, the b2-bishop is now getting a lot more reasons to be happy, too.   10...O-O ??  11.g5!  And White is immediately killing the opponent. For example  11...hxg5?   11...Ne8  12.gxh6!  g6  13.h5+-  And again White gets to the Black king.  12.hxg5  Ne8  13.Qh3  f5  14.g6  With checkmate on the next move. }
11. Qg2 Qe7
{ 11...Ne5!  12.g5  hxg5  13.hxg5  Rxh1  14.Qxh1  Nfd7  Could have still been somewhat sustainable, even though after  15.Qh8+  White either wins a pawn, or forces a very ugly response  15...Bf8  16.d3±  And White opens the center to his benefit, while Black's development is atrocious. }
12. g5 { Of course, White is ready to take all the space on Earth. } 12... Ng8
{ 12...hxg5??  13.hxg5  Rxh1  14.gxf6+-  Is an important intermediate move which wins a piece. }
13. d3 { Time to open the game even more! } 13... exd3 14. Bxd3 Ba3 15. gxh6
{ Now, the g7-pawn is in danger as well. } 15... Bxb2+ 16. Kxb2 gxh6 17. Bf5
{ This move will prove incredibly useful if Black castles long, as his knight will be pinned, which will allow for tactical problems among other things. }
17... Ngf6
{ 17...O-O-O ?  18.e4!  dxe4  19.Qh2+-  Now, Nxe4-d6 cannot be stopped. Neither can Rd6 followed by Rhd1, putting a tremendous amount of pressure on that d7-knight. }
18. e4 { Of course, White opens the game even more. } 18... dxe4 19. Nxe4 Qe5+
20. Kb1
{ Unfortunately, after playing a wonderful game, White goes tactically wrong.   20.c3!  Would have kept the opponent dead-lost, because this time  20...Nxe4  21.Bxd7+!  Kf8  22.Qf3  Would result in a completely winning position, where Black's king is rather fragile and he still needs to find a way to coordinate his pieces.  22...Nf6??  23.Rhe1+-  And Black loses a piece, as the Black queen needs to move, which will drop the f6-knight. }
20... O-O-O
{ Black doesn't use his tactical chance.   20...Nxe4!  Would have let Black bail out due to the annoying fork ...Nc3.  21.Bxd7+?   21.Bxe4  O-O-O  Is pretty safe for Black, too.  21...Kf8  And Nc3 cannot be prevented. }
21. f4 Qxf4 22. Rhf1
{ Now, the queen is in danger and there is no way to avoid losing a piece. }
22... Nxe4
{ 22...Qxh4?  23.Nxf6  Qxf6  24.Bxd7++-  and White picks up the free queen.   22...Qc7  23.Nxf6  also wins a free piece. }
23. Rxf4 Nc3+ 24. Kc1 Nxd1 25. Kxd1 Kb8 26. Rd4
{ And, of course, White easily converted his extra queen. } 26... Nb6 27. Qg3+
Ka8 28. Rxd8+ Rxd8+ 29. Kc1 Nd5 30. Qe5 f6 31. Qd4 Rf8 32. Be6 Nb6 33. Qd6 Re8
34. Bf7 Rb8 35. Qxf6
{ And Black resigned. In my opinion, an absolutely fantastic game for White, who grabbed space and restricted the opponent very skillfully. }
