[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav: Model Games"]
[Black "Alexander Grischuk vs. Laurent Fressinet, Riyadh, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Bg4 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bb2 e6 5. h3 Bh5
{ This time, Black keeps the bishop and the tension, which is more principled than capturing on f3. }
6. g4 { We immediately break the pin and grab space. } 6... Bg6 7. Ne5
{ Now, White is ready to take the g6-bishop whenever he likes. } 7... Nfd7 8.
Nxg6
{ The 'whenever he likes' moment comes immediately, as the e5-knight was being challenged. }
8... hxg6 9. Bg2 Nf6 10. c4
{ Of course, with the bishop pair, White is ready to challenge the center, he's very interested in seeing the game open up. }
10... c6 11. Qe2 Nbd7 12. Nc3 Bd6 13. Rd1
{ 13.h4!?  Is also very promising, followed by long castling. In fact, I like that idea even more, as the king is perfectly safe on the queenside. }
13... Qe7 14. O-O
{ The king is safe here as well, but long castling would have been a lot more fun, to my taste. }
14... O-O
{ This move is rather passive and unambitious, now White just has the bishop pair for nothing.   14...O-O-O !  Would have been more principled.  15.d4  g5!?  With some interesting counterchances for both sides. For instance, after  16.c5!  Bc7  17.b4!  White's play seems easier, as he's about to play b4-b5 and open the b-file. However, Black has a little tactical trick.  17...Nxg4!!  18.hxg4   18.Qxg4?!  f5!  19.Qf3  g4∞  And Black gets a huge attack.  18...Bh2+  19.Kh1  Bc7+  With a perpetual check. }
15. d4 Bb4 16. Qc2 a6 17. Ne2
{ 17.f4±  Would have been very strong, grabbing space and preventing ...e6-e5 for good. }
17... Rac8 18. Nf4 Bd6 19. Rfe1 Rfd8 20. Nd3
{ White keeps maneuvering. Potentially, he's ready to play f2-f4 and then start action on the queenside with c4-c5, b3-b4-b5, etc. }
20... e5
{ Black is tired of keeping the tension, so he immediately strikes in the center. However, that only helps the White bishops. }
21. dxe5
{ 21.g5!?  Would have been even better, the point being to either force the knight to e8, or after  21...Nh5   21...Ne4  22.h4±  And f2-f3 is always on the agenda, the e4-knight is rather unstable.  22.dxe5  Nxe5  23.Bxe5  Bxe5  24.Nxe5  Qxe5  25.h4!  Is a typical positional idea. The h5-knight is now trapped! Black won't lose it, but it's not possible to ever get it out. }
21... Nxe5 22. Nf4
{ 22.g5!?  Ne4  23.Bxe5  Bxe5  24.Nxe5  Qxe5  25.f4  Would have been a pleasant advantage for White, who can now start doubling on the d-file, putting pressure on the d5-pawn.  The e4-knight is well-placed, but it'd be difficult for it to move, since the f6-square is no longer available, while any other square will likely result in the g2-bishop getting a lot more excited about its prospects :@@EndBracket@@ }
22... dxc4 23. bxc4 Ba3 24. Bd4 Bb4 25. Rf1 Bc5 26. Qb3
{ Both parties continue slowly maneuvering. } 26... g5
{ Now, Black loses a pawn. Take a pause and find how! } 27. Bxe5 Qxe5 28. Nd3
Qe7 29. Nxc5 Qxc5 30. Qxb7 Qxc4 31. Rxd8+ Rxd8 32. Qxc6 Qxa2 33. Qc5 a5 34.
Qxg5 { And White went on to convert his advantage rather easily. } 34... a4 35.
Qa5 Rd2 36. Bf3 Nh7 37. g5
{ This idea might be somewhat suspicious, as now the White king gets weaker as well.   37.Qa8+!  Nf8  38.Rc1!  Would have been even better, preparing Rc8! with a decisive mating attack. }
37... Nf8 38. h4 a3 39. h5 g6 40. h6 Qb2
{ Unfortunately, Black managed to create a lot of counterplay thanks to his a-pawn. }
41. Qa8 Qe5 { 41...a2!  Would have given Black more than enough counterplay. }
42. h7+ Kxh7 43. Qxf8
{ Now, White won a piece, and the game was soon over. While the conversion might have not been extremely precise, we need to keep in mind this was a blitz game. However, White handled the opening and middlegame exceptionally well, which is what we need to learn and repeat in our games. }
