[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Slav: Model Games"]
[Black "Nihal Sarin vs. Mikhail Bryakin, Lichess.org, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bf5 4. e3 e6
{ Once again, we got here via a different move order. } 5. Nh4 Bg6
{ Unlike Bg4, this move is not ambitious at all. It surrenders the bishop pair right away and gives White a pleasant long-term edge to work with, while not obliging White to memorize any theoretical variations or making him put effort in to get that advantage. }
6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. g3
{ It makes a lot of sense to fianchetto the bishop for a few reasons. The first one is that there is simply no better place for it to be, as opposed to having the bishop on e2 or d3, where it is not doing anything useful. On the long diagonal, on the other hand, it has tremendous potential, since the diagonal can open up after c2-c4 or e3-e4! Secondly, the move g2-g3 shuts down the h2-b8 diagonal, which is valuable, since we're not interested in having the rook on h8 and the bishop on d6 annoy us. }
7... c5
{ ...c7-c6 is a more solid setup, not allowing the g2-bishop to show much potential any time soon. }
8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O Be7 10. c4
{ 10.d4!?  Is another interesting path, even though it seems counterintuitive, because the b2-bishop gets closed down  10...cxd4  11.exd4  O-O  12.Nd2⩲  .    Next, we can play c2-c4, or alternatively, f2-f4 followed by Nf3-e5, with a potential attack on the kingside. That attack is, of course, very typical of many Queen's Indian Defense positions from Black's perspective, or our setups in this repertoire versus the QGD, QID, and  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.e3  c5  in many cases. As Black castled, he gave up his rights on the h-file, and now we're comfortably better.   Importantly, the doubled g-pawns are a problem, because this pawn structure is inflexible, as after Ne5 there is no way to challenge the knight with ...f7-f6 due to the hanging g6-pawn. }
10... d4
{ Black goes for the Benoni-type setup reversed, but that is a dubious idea, because he lacks the crucial light-squared bishop. }
11. exd4
{ 11.Bxc6+!?  Would double the pawns, but is somewhat suspicious, because now the king gets somewhat weakened.  11...bxc6  12.Qf3  Rc8  With a complex position, which is totally okay for White, but why give up the powerful bishop? }
11... cxd4 { 11...Nxd4?  12.Bxb7+-  And White just wins a pawn. } 12. d3 O-O
13. Nd2
{ Another setup is Na3-c2 and a2-a3 followed by b3-b4. Importantly, in the normal Benoni positions, this is one of the main plans, but here we can ignore the queenside advance ideas for a few reasons.   1@@EndBracket@@ We've traded a pair of pieces, which means there's no lack of space.   2@@EndBracket@@ Black gave up his powerful light-squared bishop, which means the g2-bishop is incredibly strong and the d3-pawn is no longer a problem.   3@@EndBracket@@ We can play on the kingside, in no small part because of Black's doubled g-pawn, which means White can consider the plan f2-f4, Nf3-e5, maybe g4-g5, Qf3-h3, etc. }
13... Qd7 14. a3 a5 { Black prevents the plan b3-b4. } 15. Re1 Rad8 16. h4
{ White can perfectly afford any kingside activity he wants. The g5-square is a lovely spot for the pieces, as there is no ...f7-f6 due to the weakness of the e6-pawn. }
16... Ne8 17. Ne4 Qc7 18. Bc1
{ The bishop is on its way to f4 or g5. Alternatively, White can play Bd2 and prepare b3-b4. }
18... Nd6 19. Ng5 Nf5 20. Qg4 { Time to challenge the Black king after h4-h5! }
20... Nh6 21. Qf3
{ 21.Nxe6!  Was winning on the spot!  21...Nxg4   21...fxe6  22.Bxh6!  gxh6  23.Qxg6+  Kh8  24.Qxh6+  Kg8  25.Rxe6+-  And the Black king gets slaughtered right away.  22.Nxc7  And White is just a pawn up. }
21... Nf5 22. h5 Ne5
{ 22...Ne3!  Was the only tactical chance, the point being that now the g5-knight is hanging! }
23. Qe2
{ Now, the e5-knight is under attack, and there's no way to stop the sacrifice on e6 or the capture on g6 after Black's knight goes away. }
23... gxh5 { 23...Nc6  24.hxg6  fxg6  25.Nxe6+-  With an easy win. } 24. Qxe5
Qxe5 25. Rxe5 f6 26. Rxf5 exf5 27. Ne6
{ And Black resigned, as he loses an exchange and will be a piece down. } *

