1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 c5 3. Bb2 g6
{ This will transpose to positions discussed in the chapter on the Double Fianchetto if Black plays ...b7-b6 later, but he may also decide against that. So, let's see how we would handle the situation in that case.  Importantly, I highly recommend against playing g2-g3 at any moment, because at no other point in the repertoire do we ever go g2-g3, so let's not opt for the type of positions we're not used to getting in either case. }
4. Bxf6
{ Is an interesting attempt, even though this type of positions is rather unusual compared to the rest of our repertoire. }
4... exf6 5. c4
{ If we get to play Nc3, we'll have a very comfortable game with the outpost on d5, so Black's only chance is to immediately challenge that. }
5... d5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qd8 8. e3
{ We need to trade a few pieces and get a comfortable endgame where Black's kingside structure is not particularly impressive. Additionally, we have a potential outpost on d5, which could be very beneficial after we at some point play e3-e4. }
8... Bg7 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Rc1 O-O 12. O-O
{ Objectively, the position is balanced, but White can certainly hope to get a comfortable endgame due to the slightly better pawn structure. However, I won't get my hopes too high up, so let's rather look into a different sequence on move 4. }
