1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 c5 3. Bb2 g6
{ This will transpose to positions discussed in the chapter on the Double Fianchetto if Black plays ...b7-b6 later, but he may also decide against that. So, let's see how we would handle the situation in that case.  Importantly, I highly recommend against playing g2-g3 at any moment, because at no other point in the repertoire do we ever go g2-g3, so let's not opt for the type of positions we're not used to getting in either case. }
