{ Of course, we continue in a fashion similar to the lines we use against the KID and Double Fianchetto. }
4... Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O
{ Now, ...d7-d5 at any point will transpose to the positions we study in the chapter on the Reversed QID, while ...b7-b6 will take us to the Double Fianchetto. But, there is one more setup we need to consider. }
6... d6
{ Black is about to play ...e7-e5 and take the entire center to himself. Of course, we cannot have that happen, can we? }
7. d4 cxd4 { Now, both recaptures are rather interesting. } 8. Nxd4
{ Our goal will be to play c2-c4 and take the center. Or, if Black were to play ...e7-e5, we will attack his center! }
8... e5 9. Nb5 { The d6-pawn is in trouble. } 9... Ne8
{ Now, Black is very passive. } 10. c4
{ The d6-pawn is fixed as a target, we are about to continue with Qd2, Rd1, Nc3, potentially Ba3, and we are much better. }
