[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Reversed English: 1.Nf3 c5 and 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.b3 c5"]
[Black "3...d6 - Reversed English #1 (Trapping the queen)"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d6
{ This is an independent line that we need to take seriously: Black is looking to build a powerful center with ...e7-e5.  This move has been tried by some of the world's best players, such as Nepo, Yu Yangyi, Cheparinov, Edouard, etc. }
4. d4
{ Of course, it's crucial that we get this move in right now, as otherwise Black would go ...e7-e5, shutting down our b2-bishop. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4
{ Now, Black has a choice. He can either keep developing with ...Nf6, or try to grab the center with ...e7-e5!?, which is both ambitious and risky. }
5... e5 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. g3
{ Now, ...Nf6 would simply transpose to the  variations  (cariation:15253244/#/5/w)   discussed after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2np4/8/3N4/1P6/PBP1PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  . }
7... Be6 8. Bg2 Qd7 9. c4
{ It is difficult to imagine any other moves than ...Nf6, but let's look at 9...Bh3 as well. }
9... Bh3 10. Bxh3 Qxh3 11. Qd3
{ We are about to go Nc3 and castle long, the d6-pawn is rather weak, we can potentially challenge it with Ba3!? }
11... Qg2
{ In the only game that reached this position, Black tried this greedy move, which should have landed him in trouble. }
12. Rf1 Qxh2 13. Qf3
{ The Black queen is now nearly trapped. White has two threats: Qxc6 and Rh1, winning the queen. The game is over. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Reversed English: 1.Nf3 c5 and 1.Nf3 Nf6 2.b3 c5"]
[Black "3...d6 - Reversed English #2 (playing for space)"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d6
{ This is an independent line that we need to take seriously: Black is looking to build a powerful center with ...e7-e5.  This move has been tried by some of the world's best players, such as Nepo, Yu Yangyi, Cheparinov, Edouard, etc. }
4. d4
{ Of course, it's crucial that we get this move in right now, as otherwise Black would go ...e7-e5, shutting down our b2-bishop. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4
{ Now, Black has a choice. He can either keep developing with ...Nf6, or try to grab the center with ...e7-e5!?, which is both ambitious and risky. }
5... Nf6 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. g3
{ This is more or less the only time in the course when we go for the fianchetto. The bishop on g2 will put a considerable amount of pressure on the long diagonal, and ...d6-d5 will be always met with c2-c4!, when the center will be under even more pressure. }
7... e6 8. Bg2 d5 9. O-O Be7 10. c4
{ White cannot create any serious threats yet, but Black's center is very inflexible, and we are about to follow up with Nd2, Qc2 and potentially e2-e4. Those of you who have experience in the Grunfeld with Black will find the arising positions familiar. By the way, the c8-bishop is going to be a problem, since ...e6-e5 would be impossible to carry out, while on b7 or a6 it won't be able to do much. }
10... O-O 11. Qc2 Bb7 12. Nc3
{ It is not clear how Black should continue, while we are about to go Rfd1, Rac1, Na4 and then e2-e4. White's position is a lot esier to handle, while any Black's attempt to do something active in the center, such as ...c6-c5, will result in the center collapsing. }
