[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Reversed English: Model Games"]
[Black "Georg Meier,vs. Pavel V. Tregubov, Riyadh, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d6
{ Black is about to play ...e7-e5 and suppress our b2-bishop. So, we prevent that idea. }
4. d4 { 4.e3  e5!  Is something we don't need at all. } 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5
{ Black immediately shows his ambitions in the center. } 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. g3
{ The other bishop is being fianchettoed as well, so that we can put pressure on the c6-pawn. }
7... Nf6 8. Bg2 Qc7
{ 8...d5?  9.Bxe5±  Wins a pawn for no compensation, of course. } 9. c4
{ White takes as much as he can, making sure to make the ...d6-d5 move as difficult to accomplish as possible. }
9... Be7
{ 9...d5?  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.O-O  We are ready to put more pressure on the d5-pawn with Nc3 and challenge the Black queen with Rc1.   For example, after the natural  11.Bxd5?  Bb4+!  forces White to go Kf1, because  12.Nd2??  Nxd5!  wins a piece for Black.  11...Be6  12.Nc3!  Rd8  @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/p1q2ppp/4bn2/3pp3/8/1PN3P1/PB2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 b kq - 3 12@@EndFEN@@  12...Be7?  13.Nxd5!  Nxd5  14.Bxd5  Rd8  15.e4±  is just a free pawn for White.  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@3rkb1r/p1q2ppp/4bn2/3pp3/8/1PN3P1/PB2PPBP/R2Q1RK1 w k - 4 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rc1!  threatens the knight discovery, such as Nxd5 or Ne4.  13...Qd7  14.Qd3!  This move prepares Qb5 or Nb5-c7!, while also enabling White to follow up with Rfd1 and put even more pressure on the d5-pawn.  14...Be7  15.Na4!?  . Now, the knight is coming to c5.   Furthermore, the e5-pawn is hanging. Black's position is very difficult,  15...e4  16.Qd4  when the good news for Black is that he avoided losing a pawn, but now the d4-square became a magnificent outpost for our pieces and Nc5 is still on the way.  16...O-O  17.Nc5±  White gets an overwhelming positional advantage, as he adds the bishop pair to the list of his other perks, such as the gorgeous b2-bishop and the outpost on d4. }
10. Nc3
{ We keep developing, while making sure we increase our control of the d5-square. }
10... O-O 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. O-O { Both parties continue their development. }
12... Rad8 13. Rc2
{ The idea of this move is to potentially double up either on the d-file by means of Rd2, or on the c-file by means of Rfc1 or Qc1. Furthermore, at some point, if Black ever goes ...d6-d5, White would be able to play Qa1! and put even more pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal. }
13... Qa5 14. Qd2
{ This move not only gets the queen in the game, while also preparing Rfd1, but it also creates a tactical hazard for the a5-queen. }
14... Kh8
{ Black prevents that tactical idea by removing the king, making sure Nxe7 or Nxf6 won't come with a check.   14...Rfe8?  Let's see what that hazard is.  15.Nd5!  Qxd2  16.Nxe7+  Rxe7  17.Rxd2±  With a decisive potential advantage, since Rfd1 will target that vulnerable d6-pawn, and Ba3 is always available as well. }
15. Na4
{ White is very happy to swap queens, as in that event, the d6-pawn would be very vulnerable. }
15... Qc7
{ 15...Qxd2  16.Rxd2±  Next, not only are moves like Rfd1 and Ba3 about to challenge the d6-pawn, but also, the c4-c5! move will destroy the structure and endanger that e5-pawn. }
16. Bc3 { Now, Ba5! is a threat, intending to win an exchange. } 16... Qb8 17.
Ba5 { The bishop is quite well-placed here, actually. } 17... Rc8 18. Bh3
{ The other bishop also finds a better spot for itself. } 18... Rce8 19. Rd1 c5
{ Black activates the b7-bishop, but that comes at a cost of weakening the d5-square. }
20. Nc3 Bd8 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 22. Qe3
{ Having traded the bishops, White weakened the d6-pawn, now Nb5! is on the way. }
22... a6 23. Rcd2 Qc7 24. Bf5 { The bishop is coming to e4. } 24... Rfe8 25. f3
{ This move increases White's ability to control the e4-square even more. }
25... e4 { Black sacrifices a pawn to get some activity. } 26. Bxe4 Nxe4 27.
fxe4 Re6
{ This move is aimed at preparing ...Rde8 to put more pressure on that e4-pawn. But it fails for tactical reasons. }
28. e5 { Black is now in trouble because his d8-rook is not protected. } 28...
Qc6 { 28...Rxe5??  29.Qxe5  dxe5  30.Rxd8+  With checkmate. } 29. Qf3 Qd7 30.
e4 Qe7
{ 30...Rxe5  31.Rxd6!  Results in a completely winning position due to the weak backrank and the vulnerable b7-bishop.  31...Qxd6  32.Rxd6  Rxd6  33.Qxf7+-  White threatens the bishop and Qf8 with checkmate. }
31. Rxd6 Rdxd6 32. exd6 Qd7
{ 32...Rxd6  33.Rxd6  Qxd6  34.Qxf7+-  Wins on the spot again. } 33. Qf5 g6 34.
Qxc5 { Black loses every single pawn. The end is coming soon. } 34... Bc6 35.
b4 Kg8 36. b5 axb5 37. cxb5 Ba8 38. Qc7
{ Black resigned, as he is a billion pawns down, there is nothing he can do. A wonderful positional game, where White combined pressure on Black's weak c and d-pawns with piece play and never gave the opponent a slightest bit of counterplay! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Reversed English: Model Games"]
[Black "Francisco Vallejo Pons vs.  Romain Edouard, Bundesliga, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. b3 Nc6 3. Bb2 d6 4. d4
{ It is crucial that we prevent ...e7-e5, of course.   4.e3  e5  Is going to shut down our b2-bishop for a long time, which is obviously something we shouldn't allow for. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. g3 Be6
{ Black is simply developing his pieces, preparing ...Qd7 and ...Bh3, potentially. }
8. Bg2 Rc8 9. c4 f5
{ Black chooses a very ambitious setup, where he delays his development, but grabs a lot of space, hoping that nothing would happen dynamically, in which case he would have a lot of space for no compensation. }
10. O-O Nf6 11. c5
{ This is another crucial positional idea for us to learn. White uses the fact the e5-pawn is unprotected to dismantle Black's pawn structure. }
11... e4
{ Black is looking to shut down the g2-bishop, but that results in neglecting it's development.   11...dxc5?  12.Bxe5±  White is much better, next he'll play Nd2 and Rc1, looking to win the c5-pawn, which is incredibly weak. Furthermore, the move ...f7-f5 is significantly weakening his position, of course.   11...d5!  12.Bxe5  Bxc5⩲  Is a better path for Black, as that does not ruin the pawn structure so much. However, he is still much worse. For example, we can proceed with Bb2, Nc3, Rc1, Na4-c5, Bd4, etc, blockading Black on the weak dark squares d4 and c5. Again, the move ...f7-f5 is only hurting him, too. }
12. cxd6 Bxd6 13. Bxf6
{ It was also possible to just develop the knight, but White decides to spoil the opponent's pawn structure. It is not possible to take with the queen for tactical reasons. }
13... gxf6
{ Black is forced to make this ugly move, which of course makes his kingside pawns look very unappealing.   13...Qxf6??  14.Qxd6  Qxa1  15.Qxe6+  With an easy win for White, who picks up two pieces for a rook and threatens the c8-rook, which can hardly be defended, as ...Kd8 would get Black mated. }
14. Nc3 c5
{ Black should have rather taken care of his development by castling, instead of continuing to move the pawns. }
15. Rc1 O-O 16. Bh3
{ Time to find a new target.  That f5-pawn looks very juicy for White! It can be attacked even more with the knight from e3, for example, where it can arrive via d5. Additionally, e2-e3 and Qh5! will also get us there. At this very moment, Nxe4 is a threat, of course. }
16... Qd7 17. Nd5 f4
{ 17...Rcd8  18.Ne3  Kh8  For better or worse, Black had to keep enduring, instead of attempting unprepared activity. }
18. Nxf4 Bxh3 19. Nxh3
{ White is just a pawn up, because taking on h3 results in a terrible structure, a weak king and all other problems. }
19... Qe6
{ 19...Qxh3  20.Qxd6  The c5-pawn is about to fall, too.  20...Qf5  21.Rfd1+-  Next, either Qd5 or Rc4 followed by Rdc1 would easily win all the weak pawns. }
20. Kg2 e3 21. fxe3
{ White could have closed the position, but he takes, because Black's d6-bishop is hanging, which means he cannot recapture the e3-pawn. }
21... Rfd8 { 21...Qxe3??  22.Qxd6+-  And White is a piece up. } 22. Qc2
{ Qc4 is coming, so Black tries another desperate sacrifice. } 22... c4 23.
bxc4 Ba3 24. Rcd1 Re8 25. Nf4 Qxc4
{ 25...Qxe3  26.Rf3  And White wins the a3-bishop, or after  26...Qe7  27.e4  Nd5 cannot be stopped, the f6-pawn falls and White wins. }
26. Qxc4+ Rxc4 27. Nd5 Bb2 28. Rd2
{ Black resigned, as after the inevitable capture on f6 he'll be two pawns up. An interesting game, which shows Black can end up in a position with long-term weaknesses and no clear counterplay, which, of course, is something we are looking forward to. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Reversed English: Model Games"]
[Black "Nikolas Lubbe vs.  Barbara Juhasz, Oberliga, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 d6
{ This game started like a King's Indian, but soon enough, it will transpose to the position from our chapter on the Reversed English. }
5. d4 O-O 6. Be2 c5
{ To a large extent, this also answers the question about what happens if Black plays ...c7-c5 in the King's Indian :@@EndBracket@@ }
7. O-O Ne4
{ 7...cxd4  Would be the main move we analyze in the theoretical chapter. } 8.
Nbd2
{ White is happy to trade a pair of pieces, because that would significantly boost his development. }
8... d5
{ 8...Nxd2  9.Qxd2  Nd7  10.c4⩲  with Rfd1 and Rac1 coming next, White is comfortably better. Importantly, of course, ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7 will be always met with d4-d5!, shutting down the b7-bishop. }
9. Ne5
{ 9.c4  Is also a very good move, taking advantage of the fact Black's last move made the d5-pawn somewhat loose.  9...Nxd2  10.Qxd2  cxd4  11.Nxd4  White has a lot more activity in the center, which gives him a comfortable advantage. For example, after  11...dxc4  12.Bxc4  Nc6  13.Rfd1  White reinforces the d4-knight. Importantly, simplifications don't facilitate Black's life.  13...Nxd4  14.Bxd4  Bxd4  15.Qxd4  Qxd4  16.Rxd4  Now, White owns the d-file and can put pressure on the b7-pawn with Bd5 and Rc1-c7. It is not entirely clear how Black should unravel.  16...e6?  17.Rc1!  Black's bishop cannot come out, while Be2-f3! and Rc7! are on the way. }
9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Nc6
{ 10...cxd4  11.exd4  Does not solve Black's problems. White can easily increase his space advantage with f2-f4, or proceed with c2-c4, Rac1, Rfd1, etc. Importantly, the move ...Nc6 will create new pawn weaknesses.  11...Nc6  12.Nxc6!?  Creates a backward pawn on c6.   12.f4  is also possible, reinforcing the knight's position. }
11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. c3 { Now, the c-pawns are a problem. } 12... Qa5
{ 12...cxd4  13.cxd4  Gives White a large positional advantage, because the c5-square is weak and the c6-pawn is a problem. The simple plan of Rc1-c3-Rfc1 will put a lot of pressure on that pawn, for instance. }
13. b4
{ 13.dxc5!  Qxc5  14.c4!  would have been a good idea as well.  14...Bxb2  15.Qxb2  Now, Black never wants to take on c4, as that would result in weak queenside pawns. Instead, if she doesn't do that, we will follow up with Rac1 and Rfd1, and potentially with b3-b4 followed by c4-c5 or b4-b5, grabbing space on the queenside. }
13... cxb4 14. cxb4
{ This way, White creates a backward pawn on c6. However, it would have been even better to achieve this without the dark-squared bishops, as ours on b2 is not particularly bright. }
14... Qb6 15. Rfc1 Rb8 16. a3 Ba6
{ 16...a5  17.Bc3!  axb4  18.Bxb4±  Only worsens Black's position, because now our dark-squared bishop is finally doing something useful, and we have a passed pawn on the a-file! The simple plan of Bc5 followed by a4-a5-a6-a7 is going to be rather difficult to deal with. }
17. Rc5 Bxe2 18. Qxe2 e6 19. Qc2 Rfc8 20. Rc1
{ White successfully tripled on the c-file. The days of the c6-pawn are numbered. }
20... Bf8 21. Ra5
{ 21.Rxc6?!  Rxc6  22.Qxc6  Qxc6  23.Rxc6  a5!  Is the only reason White cannot take the pawn, as now the hanging b2-bishop allows Black to win it back. }
21... Rb7 22. Qa4 Rbc7 23. g3 Qb7 24. Bc3
{ While the c6-pawn didn't fall, the structure remains bad, so the a7-pawn and the c6-pawn are still weak in the long run. }
24... h5 25. Be1 Be7 26. Qc2 Qb6 27. Qd3 Rd8 28. f3
{ Slow maneuvering continues. White is about to prepare e3-e4. } 28... Qb7 29.
Bf2 Rcc8 30. Qc2 Rd7 31. Qa4 Rdc7 32. Kg2 Kg7 33. h3
{ There is no rush, White is slowly improving the position. } 33... f5 34. Qd1
Bd6 35. Qe2 Rf7 36. Rc2 Bc7 37. Rac5 Bb6 38. R5c3
{ Black keeps holding for the time being. How to make progress now? } 38...
Rff8 39. Qd1 a5
{ Black goes for activity, but it only weakens her position.   39...Rf7  Black should have kept waiting, but the whole point of re-routing the bishop to the kingside was to both not have a target on b2, as opposed to the situation a dozen moves earlier, when taking the c6-pawn was possible, but not particularly appealing. Now, after tying Black's pieces to the c6-pawn, White will use the well-known principle of two weaknesses by opening up the kingside!  40.Qc1  Rfc7  41.g4+-  Now, Bg3! is about to win the exchange, so Black will have to give up the c6-pawn. There is no defense! }
40. Qc1 axb4 41. axb4 Kf7 42. b5
{ White wins a pawn, as ...cxb5 would lose a rook. } 42... c5
{ 42...cxb5  43.Rxc8+- } 43. dxc5 Ba5 44. Rb3
{ And White easily queened his pawns. } 44... e5 45. b6 e4 46. c6 exf3+ 47. Kg1
Qb8 48. b7 Rc7 49. Rb5 Qa7 50. Ra2
{ Black resigned as she's losing a piece. It was certainly possible to somehow hold the endgame with perfect play, but that was by no means easy, and White's play was clearly much easier the entire time, while the opponent was only hoping to hold. }
