[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-King's Indian"]
[Black "6...c6 and 7...Nbd7, Black meets a2-a4 with a7-a5, what NOT to do"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 c6
{ Black can also choose to wait, preparing slow play like ...Qc7 and ...Nbd7 followed by ...e7-e5. }
7. O-O Nbd7 8. a4
{ I really like this rare idea used a few times by Nakamura. What's the point? For one, playing c2-c4 has the downside of depriving White of the idea Nd2-c4. Secondly, we want to go a4-a5, grabbing space on the queenside and preventing ideas like ...b7-b5 or ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7, as our a5-pawn will create a lot of unpleasant tension in the center. Now, Black can choose to stop us with ...a7-a5, or keep playing for the ...e7-e5 break. }
8... a5
{ Prevents a4-a5, but weakens the b6-square and potentially makes the a5-pawn vulnerable, as we can always hit it with ideas like Nbd2-c4, Qd2, Bc3, etc. That would be particularly painful for Black if he is to ever move the a8-rook away. }
9. Nbd2 { We continue the natural development, of course. } 9... Qc7
{ Black is taking the e5-square under more control, setting his eyes on that pawn break. }
10. Nc4
{ Was played in the only high-level game that reached this position, but I don't like the fact it allows for }
10... b5
{ When Black gets to grab space on the queenside for free, while also winning time by attacking our pieces. }
11. Ncd2 b4 { It's not clear to me why we conceded all that space. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-King's Indian"]
[Black "6...c6 and 7...Nbd7, Black meets a2-a4 with a7-a5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 c6
{ Black can also choose to wait, preparing slow play like ...Qc7 and ...Nbd7 followed by ...e7-e5. }
7. O-O Nbd7 8. a4
{ I really like this rare idea used a few times by Nakamura. What's the point? For one, playing c2-c4 has the downside of depriving White of the idea Nd2-c4. Secondly, we want to go a4-a5, grabbing space on the queenside and preventing ideas like ...b7-b5 or ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7, as our a5-pawn will create a lot on unpleasant tension is the center. Now, Black can choose to stop us with ...a7-a5, or keep playing for the ...e7-e5 break. }
8... a5
{ Prevents a4-a5, but weakens the b6-square and potentially makes the a5-pawn vulnerable, as we can always hit it with ideas like Nbd2-c4, Qd2, Bc3, etc. That would be particularly painful for Black if he is to ever move the a8-rook away. }
9. Nbd2 { We continue the natural development, of course. } 9... Qc7
{ Black is taking the e5-square under more control, setting his eyes on that pawn break. }
10. e4
{ We simply grab space in the center. Now, the goal is to play Re1 to reinforce the e4-pawn, then Bf1 to get the bishop out of the way and potentially prepare e4-e5, or make Nc4 possible, as the knight will no longer be needed to defend that e4-pawn. }
10... e5
{ Black needs to claim some space in the center as well, or else his position will simply be very passive. Here, I think it's okay to both keep the tension with such moves as Re1 as well as to trade on e5. Being faithful to my boring positional style, I would rather take on e5, which I hope the readers won't mind. If you do, explore 11.Re1, it's a very good position for White as well. }
11. dxe5
{ Now, our d2-knight couldn't be more excited, as it's setting its eyes on the fun journey to d6 via c4. }
11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5
{ And here I'd like to offer an interesting temporary sacrifice. } 13. Nc4
{ We are attacking the e5-pawn while also intending to play Qd6, or Ba3 and Bd6 or Nd6 in some combination. }
13... Nxe4 { Black should certainly accept the sacrifice. } 14. Qd3
{ Our goal is to kick the knight away to gain access to the d6-square. } 14...
Nf6 15. Bxe5 { Allows us to win the pawn right away. } 15... Qd7
{ is both ugly, as it blocks the queenside, and wrong due to } 16. Nb6 Qxd3 17.
Bxd3
{ and the Black rook ends up blocked and paralyzed on a7.  In fact, not really, as we just win it :@@EndBracket@@ }
17... Ra7 18. Bb8 { Done! } *

