17... Nd5
{ Incredible! Because the b6-knight and the e5-bishop are both unprotected, Black is able to bail out with this tactic. }
18. Bxg7 Nxb6 19. Bh6
{ I think we have a comfortable advantage due to our bishop pair in the open position. Particularly, the dark-squared bishop is very powerful, as all the dark squares and diagonals, such as the f6-square, the a1-h8 diagonal, the h4-d8 diagonal, etc, have been massively weakened.   Furthermore, remember what we said earlier about provoking ...a7-a5 so that the pawn on a5 could in the future become somewhat weak? If so, our moment of glory has come, as in any endgame with minor pieces, moves like Bd2! would create more problems than Black can solve.   Our goal should be to swap rooks and bring the king in the center. Swapping rooks is one of the best ways to utilize the bishop pair, because the bishops make it possible for our king to come to the center a lot easier, which means we will likely be a piece up in any endgame with minor pieces. }
