[White "Anti-King's Indian"]
[Black "6...c6 and 7...Nbd7, Black ignores a2-a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 c6
{ Black can also choose to wait, preparing slow play like ...Qc7 and ...Nbd7 followed by ...e7-e5. }
7. O-O Nbd7 8. a4
{ I really like this rare idea used a few times by Nakamura. What's the point? For one, playing c2-c4 has the downside of depriving White of the idea Nd2-c4. Secondly, we want to go a4-a5, grabbing space on the queenside and preventing ideas like ...b7-b5 or ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7, as our a5-pawn will create a lot on unpleasant tension is the center. Now, Black can choose to stop us with ...a7-a5, or keep playing for the ...e7-e5 break. }
8... Qc7
{ Instead, Black can already choose to ignore our queenside play. In that case, it should continue! }
9. a5 e5 10. c4
{ Now, White just grabs space in the center. The a5-pawn comes very handy, as Black's knight on d7 can hardly move, since it needs to defend the e5-pawn. That means the c8-bishop and the a8-rook cannot get out! }
10... e4
{ Would be a poor positional idea, as Black's pieces are too passive for him to hope to generate a kingside attack, which is sort of necessary in this pawn chain structure. Why is it necessary for Black to get kingside counterplay very rapidly? Because White is now going to quickly develop play on the queenside with b3-b4-b5, so Black should react on the kingside, but again, he would fail to do so. }
11. Nfd2 d5 12. Nc3
{ That d7-knight is really in the way of all Black other pieces. } 12... Re8
{ Suppose he tries to play ...Nf8, which both frees up the c8-bishop and prepares the typical idea ...h7-h5, ...Nh7-g5, bringing the pieces over to the kingside. While the move is logical, it's very slow and fails to the following typical reason. }
13. cxd5
{ White is ready to open up the c-file and get access to the b5-square. } 13...
cxd5
{ Black needs to take back with the pawn, since the knight recapture would drop the e4-pawn. }
14. Nb5 Qd8 15. Qc2
{ With Nc7, as well as Nd6 or Qc7 on the way, Black seems to be completely lost. }
