{ It is also possible to release the tension in the center, but after } 12.
Nxd4
{ White seems to be comfortably better, with b4-b5! coming, developing initiative on the queenside. }
12... Nc5 13. Bf3
{ It makes sense to take the e4-square under more control. Now, b3-b4! is a plan. }
13... Nce4
{ Suppose Black installs a knight on this good-looking square, looking to swap some pieces. }
14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4
{ White is happy to swap two pairs of pieces, as now the d6-pawn will be very weak. }
15... Rxe4 16. Qd2
{ Next, we follow with Rfd1, possibly Ne2 to trade the bishops, and will play against the d6-pawn, which would be really hard to defend. Black has a weakness, no space, and as a result, is simply worse. Maybe not much worse, but clearly worse, and has no counterplay to at least be able to have some fun or bother us. By the way, that a5-pawn is really annoying for him, isn't it? }
