[White "Anti-King's Indian"]
[Black "6...c6 and 7...Nbd7, Black ignores a2-a4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 c6
{ Black can also choose to wait, preparing slow play like ...Qc7 and ...Nbd7 followed by ...e7-e5. }
7. O-O Nbd7 8. a4
{ Black could also start with 8...Re8, but the problem is that it's never possible to prepare ...e7-e5 without ...Qc7, as with the queen on d8 and rook on e8, White can just take on e5, then trade queens and then with the pawn. }
8... Qc7
{ Instead, Black can already choose to ignore our queenside play. In that case, it should continue! }
9. a5 e5 10. c4
{ Now, White just grabs space in the center. The a5-pawn comes very handy, as Black's knight on d7 can hardly move, since it needs to defend the e5-pawn. That means the c8-bishop and the a8-rook cannot get out! }
10... Re8 11. Nc3 Nf8 12. a6
{ White is looking to weaken the opponent's queenside even more, hoping Black would take, which would make both of his a-pawns very vulnerable. }
12... b6
{ Naturally, Black chooses to avoid such a scenario, but now the a6-pawn is taking the b7-square away from the bishop, making it difficult for Black to develop. We'll take a look at the rest of the game in the chapter on model games!: 1/2 @@StartBracket@@81@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Nyzhnyk,I @@StartBracket@@2665@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
13. b4
{ Looks like a very logical and strong novelty, preparing to play b4-b5 or c4-c5, making more progress on the queenside, opening the files and making the opponent weaken squares. }
