[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7
{ The most popular decision by far: Black is not showing his hand yet, choosing to wait and possibly follow up with ...e7-e5 shortly after, or with ...c7-c5, or with something slow like ...c7-c6, ...Qc7, etc. }
7. O-O c5
{ I believe the Benoni-style choice is not as attractive for Black once his knight has been committed to d7, and that is because Black loses his main ideas in the Benoni structure: challenging the d5-pawn with ...e7-e6 is difficult because after dxe6 fxe6 the d6-pawn is often hanging, and additionally, the ...Na6-c7 plan becomes impossible, which means it's by no means easy to make the ...b7-b5 break happen. So, the Benoni positions are rather attractive here for White. However, while you're more than welcome to investigate them, I'd suggest keeping things English-style, as that's what we normally do in other variations. }
8. c4
{ If Black plays ...b7-b6, which is the most likely scenario, you will be well-served by the chapter on the Double Fianchetto, while if he doesn't, the chapter on the  Anti-English  (chpater:19)  (will be of use.) }
