[White "Anti-King's Indian"]
[Black "6....Nbd7 with ...e7-e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7
{ The most popular decision by far: Black is not showing his hand yet, choosing to wait and possibly follow up with ...e7-e5 shortly after, or with ...c7-c5, or with something slow like ...c7-c6, ...Qc7, etc. }
7. O-O e5
{ Usually, the Black players choose to immediately challenge us in the center. }
8. dxe5 Ng4 9. c4 Ngxe5
{ Mostly, Black captures this pawn, which is totally wrong from the strategic viewpoint, because as we have discussed earlier, the arising structure is very beneficial for White due to his space advantage provided by the c4-pawn and availability of the d5-square for the knight, which can hardly be challenged by ...c7-c6 as the d6-pawn then becomes weak. }
10. Nc3
{ This position is very comfortable due to the pawn structure, so it's no wonder White scores a whopping 62%! As usual, we will focus on analyzing the middlegame in the chapter on model games, but for now, let's say White wants to defend the b2-bishop with Qd2, then play Rad1 and eventually just on d5 with his knight. It's not going to be possible for Black to easily kick the knight away with ...c7-c6, as that would weaken the d6-pawn considerably. If you're interested in studying these positions on your own, I highly recommend looking at the games of Nakamura, who is a huge expert in these structures. }
10... Nxf3+ { Black trades a pair of knights. } 11. Bxf3 Ne5 12. Be2
{ Now, the knight can be kicked out with f2-f4 in the future, too. } 12... Be6
13. Qd2 f5
{ In most games, Black played this move that grabs a bit of space on the kingside. }
14. Rad1 Qd7 15. f4 Nc6 16. Bf3
{ Potentially, Black can also fall prey to the c4-c5 break, if the queen on d7 remains loose. White is much better - again, take a look at the chapter on model games! }
