12... e4 13. Nd2 { Now, the pawn on e4 would be extremely vulnerable. } 13...
f5 { Black has to defend the pawn, of course. } 14. c5
{ Time to sacrifice a pawn. If Black doesn't take, our goal is to play Nc4, Rfd1, meet ...c7-c6 with Nd6 and enjoy the fact Black cannot come out. }
14... Nxc5 15. Rad1 { White's threatening Ndxe4. } 15... Nd3
{ Black needs to block the d-file. } 16. Ndxe4
{ However, White will now take advantage of the pin. } 16... fxe4 17. Nxe4
{ Black will lose the d3-knight. } 17... Rxe4 18. Bxd3
{ White is a piece down, but he's threatening Bc4+, which will win the queen. Additionally, the rook on e4 is hanging. }
18... Re6 { The only move that prevents Bc4+. } 19. Bc4
{ White still wins an exchange and is much better with a rook and a pawn for two minor pieces. Additionally, our coordination is much better, the knight on h6 is terrible, and the c7-pawn might hang very shortly. }
19... Qe7 20. Ba3
{ We are trying to distract the queen. A move like ...Qe8 can be met in a plethora of attractive ways: for example, we can trade on e6 and win the c7-pawn. Or simply enjoy the pin and go e3-e4, f2-f4, etc. Black is not getting out! }
