1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7
{ The most popular decision by far: Black is not showing his hand yet, choosing to wait and possibly follow up with ...e7-e5 shortly after, or with ...c7-c5, or with something slow like ...c7-c6, ...Qc7, etc. }
7. O-O e5
{ Usually, the Black players choose to immediately challenge us in the center. }
8. dxe5 Ng4 9. c4 dxe5
{ This is a more principled way for Black to proceed, as he is not weakening his pawn structure. But, it is not a great idea for tactical reasons. }
10. h3 Nh6 11. Qc2
{ Now, our objective is to grab space with c4-c5!, which will also create room on c4 for the b1-knight. }
11... Re8 12. Nc3
{ White's knight is ready to go d6 in the future if Black ever goes ...c7-c6. }
12... f5 13. c5
{ We have seen this pawn sacrifice already, and now it's not a bad idea to use it again. }
13... c6
{ Refuses to take a pawn and is a better choice, but after the natural } 14.
Bc4+ Kh8 15. b4
{ We grab more space on the queenside and are about to proceed with natural moves like Rfd1, Qb3, maybe Ne2 to attack the e5-pawn, Rd6 and Rad1 to increase our pressure on the d-file, etc. The question appears: how would Black ever get his pieces out? Unfortunately, it's rather difficult to offer a good explanation to that. }
