[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-King's Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Yuriy Krykun vs.  Dolgun Can, RTU Open, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ I have played this game against a talented kid from Turkey. When the game was played, he was 11 or 12. Now, four years later, he is a 2300+ player, which shows my evaluations of his talent certainly weren't wrong. Anyway, I digress. The reason why I chose this variation is because most talented kids at this age are great at tactics, but don't have enough experience with positional chess yet. Obviously, if that's the case, you want to play in a way that would prevent your opponent from showing his true strength, and this line was a perfect fit, because if Black tries to play in a usual KID style, he ends up in a very passive @@StartBracket@@and frankly, a simply bad!@@EndBracket@@ position. }
1... Nf6 2. g3
{ Again, the opening moves are not exactly what is recommended in the theoretical chapter, but our main concern is the pawn structure as opposed to specific precise move orders. }
2... g6 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. d4 d6 6. b3
{ This variation is also aimed at discouraging ...e7-e5. By the way, it has been recommended in Sielecki's Chessable repertoire 1.d4 - Keep It Simple. I was playing this line long before Chessable was created, but it's interesting that several excellent authors, who have experience teaching club players and understand that structures is what chess is all about at this level, have suggested such an approach. }
6... e5 { Black still plays for the e5-break. } 7. dxe5 Nfd7 8. Bb2 Nc6
{ 8...dxe5!  Is a better decision, not going for this poor pawn structure. } 9.
c4 Ndxe5 10. Qd2
{ White's plan is very simple. We go Nc3-d5, Rad1 and then prepare e2-e4 and f2-f4. It is always difficult for Black to chase our d5-knight away with ...c7-c6, because that makes the d6-pawn extremely vulnerable. }
10... Be6 11. Nc3 Qe7 12. Rad1
{ As you can see, White's moves are very natural. } 12... Rab8 13. Nxe5 Nxe5
14. f4 Nc6 15. e4 { Now, the threat is f4-f5 followed by Nd5. } 15... f5
{ 15...a6??  Let's see what happens if Black skips a move.  16.f5!  Bd7  17.f6!  Bxf6  18.Nd5  And White wins a piece and the game. }
16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Nd5 Qd7 18. Rde1
{ The idea now is to double on the e-file with Re3 and Rfe1. } 18... Rbe8
{ Black tries to challenge the e-file, but that allows White to win the dark-squared bishop for a knight. I'm saying 'win' instead of 'trade', because the dark-squared bishop is an extremely important piece for Black here, the only defender of the dark squares. }
19. Rxe8 Rxe8 { 19...Qxe8?  20.Nxc7  Does not make it any better. } 20. Nf6+
Bxf6 21. Bxf6
{ If White is allowed to simply go Bb2 and Qc3, it is going to be over in no time. }
21... Be4 22. Ba1
{ 22.Bxe4!  Rxe4  23.f5!  Would have been even stronger, as Qg5 and Qh6 are a very dangerous agenda. }
22... Bxg2 23. Kxg2
{ Unfortunately, at this point I got lazy and thought I'd win without any effort, which made me reluctant to calculate precisely and almost let the opponent escape.   23.Qc3!  Would have easily won, for example  23...Bxf1   23...Re2  I think this was the move I was lazy to calculate, but after  24.Qh8+  Kf7  25.Qxh7+  Ke8  26.Qh8+  Kf7  27.f5!  White wins, as his last move took the e6-square away from Black and created a mating threat.  27...Bxf1??  28.Qg7+  Ke8  29.Qg8+  Ke7  30.f6!  That's rather cute, isn't it?  24.Qh8+  Kf7  25.Qg7+  Ke6  26.Qf6 }
23... Qe6
{ Black misses his chance.   23...Qf5!  24.Qb2  Re7  And suprisingly, White cannot make progress, because after  25.Qh8+  Kf7  26.Qxh7+  Ke8  27.Qh8+  Kd7  28.Qb2  Nb4  Black somehow gets a lot of counterplay with Nd3, Qe4, etc. It still looks weird to me, even four years later, that Black can create counterplay in such an unexpected way, but White's light squares are indeed very fragile. }
24. Qc3 Qe2+ 25. Rf2 Qe4+ 26. Rf3 Qe2+ 27. Kh3
{ Now it's over. The king escaped the checks, while mate on the long diagonal cannot be stopped. }
27... Qe6+ 28. g4 Re7 29. Qh8+ Kf7 30. f5 Qe2 31. fxg6+ Ke6 32. Qc8+
{ My opponent resigned due to forced checkmate after } 32... Rd7 33. Rf6+ Ke7
34. Qf8#
{ Again, we see a very similar point as in other model games: once White has a pawn on c4 versus the d6-pawn, the simple plan of Qd2, Rad1, Nc3-d5, e2-e4 and f2-f4 is very hard for the opponent to deal with.  Moreover, it's very easy to play with White in this structure, as every single move comes very naturally, while Black needs to think hard about how not to end up in an extremely passive position, let alone create any counterplay whatsoever. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-King's Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Hikaru Nakamura vs. Maxime Vachier Lagrave, Chess.com, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's now take a look at this example to learn why I consider the pawn structure 'c4 vs d6' extremely beneficial for White at all times, unless his pieces are placed extremely poorly. }
1. b3
{ Actually, as you can see, this game did not even start with 1.Nf3, but it'll transpose to the place we need it to transpose to rather soon. }
1... Nf6 2. Bb2 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. d4
{ Alright, now we are back on track. As I mention in the theoretical chapter, Black's main plan in most KID variations involves playing for ...d6 and ... e7-e5. This is exactly what our setup is aimed against, so let's observe how we meet that plan. }
5... d6 6. Be2 Nc6
{ Usually, the knight gets developed to d7, but all roads lead to Rome anyway. Or, in this case, to the ...e7-e5 break. }
7. O-O e5 8. dxe5 Ng4 9. c4 Ngxe5
{ 9...dxe5  Is a move that Black should usually prefer from the structural perspective. However, here it's not nearly as good as with the knight on d7, because Black lacks the opportunity to play ...c7-c6 to cover up the d5 and b5-squares.  Additionally, the d7-knight is usually re-routed somewhere via c5, or it can support ideas like Bf8-c5. On c6, instead, the knight is very misplaced. }
10. Qd2 Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Ne5 12. Be2 Re8 13. Nc3
{ This is the exact pawn structure we are looking for. White is much better here because of the following reasons:   1@@EndBracket@@ He can install the knight on d5.   2@@EndBracket@@ Black would have to either tolerate that knight for the rest of game, which does not sound appealing at all, or he'll need to go ...c7-c6. If that happens, the d6-pawn will become substantially weak, allowing White to hunt it with simple moves like Rad1, etc.   3@@EndBracket@@ Once the knight is on d5, White can often proceed with e3-e4 and f2-f4, ideally looking to trade the dark-squared bishops, install the queen on the a1-h8 diagonal and threaten some nasty checks like Nf6+.   4@@EndBracket@@ Potentially, White has c4-c5! ideas if Black is exposed on the d-file. }
13... Bd7 14. Rad1
{ This move is logical, and given it was a blitz game, very natural, but White had a stronger continuation.   14.f4!?  Would have been a very interesting path.  14...Nc6   14...Ng4  15.e4±  Also provokes a few questions, such as: what is the knight doing on g4? Next, we just follow up with Bf3, Rad1, Rfe1, Nd5, etc. It's extremely easy to play with the White pieces.  15.Bf3±  Allows White to win control over the h1-a8 diagonal again, as he managed to safely place the bishop on f3. Next moves will be Rad1, Rfe1, maybe g2-g3 to provide more room for the bishop, eventually Nd5 and e3-e4. Black has absolutely no play whatsoever. }
14... Bc6 15. Nd5 a5
{ 15...Nd7  16.Bxg7  Kxg7  17.Qc3+  Kg8  Seems to be a solid way for Black to defend. He is clearly somewhat worse, but managed to minimize his disadvantage by trading two pairs of minor pieces. Later, he might consider the following setup: ...a7-a5, ...Bxd5, ...Nc5. That's a purely defensive setup, but White might have a slightly difficult time tearing it apart. }
16. Rfe1 b6 17. f4 { Finally White starts taking action. } 17... Bxd5 18. cxd5
Nd7 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 { How to continue here as White? } 20. Bb5
{ The ...b7-b6 move caused the c6-square to become rather weak, which is something White is happy to take advantage of. }
20... Re7 21. e4 Nc5 22. Qd4+ Kg8 23. e5 { Black is about to get steamrolled. }
23... Qf8 24. Bc6 Rd8 25. Re3 Qg7 26. Rde1 dxe5
{ The decisive mistake.   26...h6  This weird move is not just an attempt to wait. Black is actually preparing ... g6-g5, looking to undermine the f4-pawn, which is so instrumental for supporting the White center. Of course, this move greatly weakens the Black king and still allows White to keep a large advantage, but it seems to be the sad necessity.  27.Qd2±  g5?   27...Kh7  Black will eventually try to prepare this ...g6-g5.  28.fxg5  hxg5  29.Rg3+- }
27. Rxe5
{ 27.fxe5!  Looks better, intending to unpin the e5-pawn by moving the queen to c4 or whatnot, followed by e5-e6! at an appopriate moment. }
27... h5 28. h3 Qf6 29. Qe3 Rxe5 30. fxe5 Qe7 31. a3 Na6 32. Bb5
{ 32.e6!  Would have won even faster, but let's keep in mind it was a blitz game. }
32... Nb8 33. Bc4 b5 { Black's last attempt to free himself out of the bind. }
34. Bxb5 Rxd5 35. Bc4 Rd8 36. Rf1 Rf8 37. Qh6
{ Black resigned, because Qxg6 cannot be prevented. e5-e6 is another threat that doesn't make his life any prettier.  I think the main conclusion to take away from this game is that the structure that arose after Black carried out the ...e7-e5 break and took with the piece is very beneficial for White for reasons discussed above. This is a pawn structure you will be getting all the time, so I cannot emphasize enough the importance of understanding it well. We'll be looking at a lot more games that feature the same pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-King's Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Jozef Franzen vs. Ventzeslav Mechkarov, Trnava,1984"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6 3. d4 g6 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 Nc6 7. O-O e5
{ Black again tries to quickly prepare ...e7-e5. Back in the day when this game was played, theory might not have been developed and known nearly as well, but this break has always been KID's central theme. And, of course, the main beauty of our variation is that Black's main plan is wrong against what we do. 😊 }
8. dxe5 Ng4
{ 8...dxe5?  As usual, Black canot recapture immediately.  9.Qxd8  Rxd8  10.Nxe5  Nxe5  11.Bxe5±  Just a free pawn for us. }
9. c4 Ngxe5 10. Nc3
{ Again, we have this very beneficial pawn structure, where the knight is enjoying the outpost on d5. Next, we are about to play Qd2, Rad1, potentially trade on e5 and prepare e3-e4 and f2-f4-f5, starting the typical kingside play. }
10... Nxf3+ 11. Bxf3 Ne5 12. Be2
{ Black succeeded in kicking the bishop away from the h1-a8 diagonal, which I guess is good news for Black, but now the knight is about to be kicked out with f2-f4, which is a useful move anyway, as it grabs space, and on top of that, White would also win a tempo. }
12... h5 { Black looks to obtain a better control of the g4-square. } 13. Qd2
Be6 14. f4 { Time to start making progress in the center. } 14... Ng4 15. Bf3
{ White positions the bishop on the long diagonal again, while also winning a tempo by attacking the b7-pawn. }
15... Rb8 16. Rae1
{ White shows he's primarily interested in kingside play, or else the rook would have gone on d1. }
16... Qh4 17. h3
{ Of course, this simple move is great, as it stops the threat of mate in one and wins a tempo. The Black queen's position doesn't make much sense. }
17... Nf6 18. Nb5
{ This unusual move turns out very strong, as it attacks both the pawns on c7 and a7. }
18... c6 19. Nxd6
{ Finally White's positional advantage got converted into material one. The rest is relatively simple, as White is still much more active and the knight will be easily supported with c4-c5 or with e3-e4-e5. }
19... Rfd8 20. Rd1 Ne8 21. c5 { The knight is staying strong! } 21... b6 22.
Bxg7 Nxg7 23. Qc3 bxc5 24. Qxc5
{ Now, on top of other problems, Black's queenside pawn structure is also very weak. }
24... Rd7 25. Qe5 Rf8 26. Rd4
{ White is preparing to double on the d-file, while also creating a tactical threat. }
26... Bd5
{ 26...a6??  Let's see White's threat in case Black skips a move.  27.f5+-  White wins a piece as he attacks not only the e6-bishop, but also the h4-queen with his rook! That was another big point behind his last move. }
27. Bxd5 cxd5 28. Rxd5 { Another pawn falls... } 28... Re7 29. Qc3 Ne8 30. Nc4
Nf6 31. Re5 Rxe5 32. Nxe5
{ White is happy to trade even more. Being two pawns up and seeing that queen on h4, which is just awfully out of play, I don't think White has much doubts about the evaluation. }
32... Ne4 33. Nxg6 { Another cute tactic that forces simplifications. } 33...
Nxc3 { 33...fxg6  34.Qc4++-  Picks the e4-knight. } 34. Nxh4 Rd8 35. Rf2 Rd1+
36. Kh2 Ra1 37. Rc2 Nxa2 38. Rc5 { White is also picking up the h5-pawn. }
38... Nb4 39. Nf5 { 39.Rxh5  Is also very good, of course. } 39... Rb1 40. Nd4
h4 41. Rg5+ Kf8 42. Rb5 Nd3 43. Nf5
{ Instead, White also threatens mate with Rb8. } 43... Kg8 44. Nxh4 Nc1 45. b4
Nd3 46. Ra5 Nxb4 47. Rxa7 Nd5 48. Nf5
{ And Black finally resigned, as he is three pawns down and has no counterplay or hope. A great positional game from White, in my opinion, as he was always in control, slowly but surely improved his position and made sure Black never ever got any counterplay. That's exactly how you want to outplay the opponent! }
