[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-King's Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Alexander Riazantsev vs. Volodar Murzin, Sochi, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Be2 Nbd7 7. O-O Re8
{ Black waits, preparing to carry out the move ...e7-e5 in more favorable conditions. }
8. c4
{ White takes space in the center. If Black doesn't ever play ...e7-e5, White will keep grabbing space after Nc3, b3-b4, a2-a4, etc, playing on the queenside. }
8... e5 9. dxe5
{ Of course, White takes, as always, hoping to get the beneficial structure we had seen in the previous games. }
9... Ng4 10. Nbd2 dxe5
{ However, this time goes for the symmetrical pawn structure. As I had explained in the theoretical part, this structure is beneficial for Black, as he won't be significantly behind in space and activity if he manages to stabilize the position. The question is 'if', since that g4-knight is terribly misplaced now. }
11. h3
{ 11.b4⩲  Seems to be an improvement, preparing c4-c5, Bc4, Qb3, etc, looking to grab space on the queenside and to develop pressure on the a2-g8 diagonal. White seems to be somewhat better. }
11... Nh6
{ Black misses his chance to equalize immediately, and now things start escalating very fast.   11...e4!  Was a very strong opportunity, which would have actually equalized.  12.Bxg7  exf3  13.Bxf3  Nxf2!  Is the key tactic, spoiling White's structure.  14.Rxf2  Kxg7  15.Qc2  The structure is worse, but White is more active, which should mean the position is balanced. But, of course, that's not what we want after the opening, is it? }
12. Qc2 Qe7 13. Rfd1
{ 13.Rfc1⩲  Is an idea I would prefer, the point being to prepare c4-c5! and quickly start playing on the queenside. }
13... f5
{ Black is looking to grab space on the kingside, but that weakens his position too much. }
14. c5
{ This typical pawn sacrifice, which we have seen several times in the theoretical chapter, is very strong here as well. }
14... Nxc5
{ 14...Qxc5?  15.Qxc5  Nxc5  16.Rac1  Would allow White to get the c7-pawn back, or the one on e5 in the event of ...Ne6.  16...Ne6   16...Nd7  17.Rxc7+-  Is entirely winning, as he is dominating the seventh rank and is about to annoy Black even more with Bb5, or with Bc4-Ng5, for instance. Black simply cannot move!  17...Nf7  18.Bc4!  Now, Ng5! is about to win.  18...h6  Black needs to prevent Ng5.  19.Bxf7+  Kxf7  20.Nc4+-  Now, the knight is coming to d6. Besides, Rxd7 is a threat, White is entirely winning.  17.Bxe5  Bxe5  18.Nxe5±  White is much better due to his superior activity, he is going to develop more initiative on the queenside wtih b3-b4. Nc4 or Nb3-c5, Bc4, etc. The knight in the center can be reinforced with f2-f4!?, as now the e5-square became an outpost. }
15. Rac1
{ White keeps developing his last pieces, while also creating threats. } 15...
b6 16. b4 { Of course, the pieces keep being pushed all the way back. } 16...
Na6 17. Qa4 { Now, the a6-knight is in danger. } 17... Nxb4
{ 17...Nb8?  18.Rxc7!  Distracts the queen from protecting the e8-rook, White is completely winning.  18...Qxc7  19.Qxe8+  Bf8  20.Bc4++-  With an easy win, for instance  20...Nf7  21.Nxe5+- }
18. Rxc7 { Same idea: the queen is being distracted. } 18... Qxc7
{ 18...Qf8  19.Rxg7+!  Immediately destroys Black.  19...Qxg7   19...Kxg7  20.Nxe5+-  Black will also get killed on the long dark diagonal.  20.Qxe8++- }
19. Qxe8+ Bf8 20. Bc4+ Nf7 21. Nxe5
{ Black resigned as there is no way to prevent all the attacks on the f7-knight, so he is losing a piece. Keep in mind the a8-rook and the c8-bishop have never even managed to move! }
