[Black "3...Bg4 with ...e5 - the right path N3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6
{ Black makes a claim he is about to play ...e7-e5, which is something we should not allow for, of course. }
3. d4 Bg4 4. e3
{ While ...Bxf3 was by no means a threat, there is no need to discuss some random pawn structure that doesn't arise anywhere else in our repertoire, so we play e2-e3. }
4... Nbd7 5. h3
{ I find it desirable to immediately clarify the situation with the bishop, making Black either concede the bishop pair, or retreat to h5, where the bishop would be somewhat endangered due to the ever-existing possibiltiies of g2-g4 at an appropriate moment. }
5... Bh5 6. Bb2
{ White just keeps developing in a natural way. Of course, our next moves are also rather easy and obvious: for example, we can follow up with Nbd2, Be2 and O-O. Alternatively, c2-c4 and Nc3 is a good setup as well, but keeping the knight on d2 allows the bishop on b2 to be active and to control the e5-square. Now, Black must be facing a bit of an existential crisis: playing ...e7-e5 is suspicious due to dynamic reasons we are about to see in a second, and ... g7-g6 is not possible either, as the h5-bishop will get trapped @@StartBracket@@here we see the benefits of including h2-h3!@@EndBracket@@. So, his only way of developing involves ... e7-e6, which, obviously, is a setup that has nothing to do with the Old Indian. }
6... e5
{ This was played in most of the few games that reached this position, but this move has a relatively straightforward issue attached to it. }
7. dxe5 dxe5 8. Nbd2
{ Now, however, the e5-pawn is certainly a problem! As the variations below show, White sholud not hurry taking it, but Black always needs to keep that very possibility in mind. Interestingly, this natural move is a novelty. }
8... Qe7
{ Is the move the engine likes, intending long castling. However, after } 9. g4
Bg6 10. Qe2
{ White is looking to castle long himself as well and later utilize his more active pieces and space advantage on the kingside. The restricted bishop on g6 is a very common and annoying issue, because there are always ideas related to trapping it by means on h4-h5, as well as capturing it with Nh4-g6, getting the bishop pair. Importantly, our last move is based on a key tactical nuance. }
10... Bxc2 11. Rc1 Bg6
{ Here, Rxc7 leads to easy and obvious advantage, as White prevents long castling and will easily finish his development with Bg2 and O-O, while Black's queen on e7 makes the rest of his development very problematic. However, we have an even better idea at our disposal! }
12. Qb5 O-O-O 13. Qa5
{ With this cute maneuver, we threaten checkmate on c7 and the a7-pawn. After }
13... c6 14. Qxa7
{ Black needs to be very careful to make sure he is not going to get checkmated with the combination of Rxc6 and Ba6+, for example. Additionally, Nc4-a5 is on the way, or Bc3-a5, etc. }
