{ Is the move the engine likes, intending long castling. However, after } 9. g4
Bg6 10. Qe2
{ White is looking to castle long himself as well and later utilize his more active pieces and space advantage on the kingside. The restricted bishop on g6 is a very common and annoying issue, because there are always ideas related to trapping it by means on h4-h5, as well as capturing it with Nh4-g6, getting the bishop pair. Importantly, our last move is based on a key tactical nuance. }
10... O-O-O 11. O-O-O
{ Now, it's not obvious at all how Black should be getting his kingside pieces out. On the other hand, we can continue with Bg2, g4-g5 and h3-h4, possibly with Nc4. Importantly, ...e5-e4 is almost always guaranteed to be a terrible idea, as that move will be met with Nh4 followed by Nxg6, then the e4-pawn would be extremely vulnerable, and the b2-bishop would be really enjoying itself on the long diagonal. }
11... Qe6
{ For example, this move looks natural, trying to get the bishop out. } 12. Nc4
{ Now, the e5-pawn is in danger. } 12... Be7
{ The engine believes the position after ...Bd6 is so bad that he needs to give up a pawn. However, White can even ignore the pawn in order to focus on development and connect his rooks. }
13. Nfxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Rxd1+
{ And here we really wish we could take on d1 with the rook. } *

