[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Old Indian"]
[Black "3...c5?! N1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6
{ Black makes a claim he is about to play ...e7-e5, which is something we should not allow for, of course. }
3. d4 c5 { This move is not great, but it's worth checking how to handle it. }
4. dxc5
{ While e2-e3 is not a bad reply at all, the direct capture is even better. }
4... Qa5+
{ Here, White can block the check in more than one way, but I particularly like one cheeky sequence. }
5. Qd2 Qxc5 6. Ba3
{ Now, the queen doesn't have too many great squares. In the only game that reached this position, he retreated to the natural c7-square. }
6... Qc7 7. c4
{ We grab space and prepare Nc3, from where it can always jump to d5 or b5. Importantly, the bishop on a3 will be very useful if Black ever goes ...e7-e6, because the d6-pawn would become really vulnerable. Instead, he can continue ...g7-g6, but that just gives us a very pleasant position with space advantage due to the c4-pawn. Additionally, the queen is misplaced on the c-file. }
7... g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Nd4 O-O 10. e3
{ Next, Be2 and O-O will be played, followed by Rc1, Rfd1 and potentially Nd5 at some point. Black is just somewhat worse, and while we don't have a decisive advantage or anything like that, our extra space and better control of the center just gives us a very pleasant game. }
