[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Old Indian"]
[Black "3...c5?! N2 - Black loses castling rights"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6
{ Black makes a claim he is about to play ...e7-e5, which is something we should not allow for, of course. }
3. d4 c5 { This move is not great, but it's worth checking how to handle it. }
4. dxc5
{ While e2-e3 is not a bad reply at all, the direct capture is even better. }
4... dxc5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nc3
{ Next, we just go Bf4 and castle long with a huge lead in development. Importantly, in many cases, the idea of giving up castling rights is not bad at all @@StartBracket@@think Philidor Defense, for example@@EndBracket@@, but in those situations, he has a pawn on c6 and hides the king on c7. The c6-pawn prevents checks on b5 and d5, for example. Here, however, he pawn is already on c5, so those squares are available to White.  Let's take a brief look at how the position can play out. }
6... e6 7. Bf4 Be7 { Black just hopes to get his pieces out. } 8. O-O-O+ Ke8 9.
Ne5 { Next, we can follow up with Nb5, or Nc4-d6, for example. } 9... Bd7 10.
g3
{ This is another great developing move, which prepares Bg2 with strong pressure on the long diagonal. }
10... Nc6 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Bg2 Rc8 13. Rd2
{ Next, we just double on the d-file. Importantly, Black cannot castle, so it's not clear at all how he should keep developing.  Meanwhile, we have the bishop pair, the d-file and a big lead in development for no compensation. }
