[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Old Indian"]
[Black "3...Nbd7, slow play N2 - the key break c4-c5!"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6
{ Black makes a claim he is about to play ...e7-e5, which is something we should not allow for, of course. }
3. d4 Nbd7
{ This is a typical way to play the Old Indian. Black's goal is to prepare ...e7-e5, challenging White in the center, and looking to develop the bishop to e7 rather than g7. Of course, on e7 it is a bit more passive, but this way of development also takes less time. }
4. Bb2
{ The good news about our setup is that the bishop on b2 makes the idea of playing ...e7-e5 rather difficult to execute. If Black is to insist on that, he'll need to make the moves ...c7-c6 and ...Qc7, which is by no means the end of the world, but it's certainly not the most active way of playing out there. }
4... c6
{ Since ...e7-e5 cannot be played right away, Black is looking to play ...Qc7 and support the e5-square once more. }
5. Nbd2
{ This move is more flexible than e2-e3, because it keeps the option of e2-e4 open. }
5... Qc7 6. e4
{ I think there is no reason to abstain from taking as much center as possible. }
6... e5 7. Be2
{ White just keeps developing his pieces, preparing to castle and keep increasing his space advantage. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. c4
{ It makes sense to grab space.  In fact, having a knight on d2 has benefits compared to it normal position on c3, because it allows the b2-bishop to stay active.  Additionally, we can continue with Re1 and then bring it to the kingside with Nf1-g3! Now, we will consider two opportunities: Black can either choose to open the center with ...exd4, or keep the tension for as long as possible by playing typical passive moves like ...b7-b6, ...Bb7, ...Rfe8, etc. }
9... b6
{ Keeping the tension appears to be a better decision, since ...exd4 leads to a very passive position, as we see in the corresponding variation. Let's suppose Black just waits. }
10. Qc2
{ We connect the rooks, now the plan is to get them in the center with Rad1 and Rfe1. Later, the knight can come over to f1 and g3, which will enable White to generate pressure on the kingside. }
10... Bb7 11. Rfe1 Rfe8
{ Black also makes some semi-useful moves, the point being to potentially put some pressure on the e4-pawn after ...Bf8. Besides, the e7-bishop can potentially get re-routed to g7, which is a common idea in the Old Indian and many variations of Spanish, for example. }
12. Rad1 Bf8 13. Bd3
{ We overprotect the e4-pawn. Next, the knight is ready to go to g3, or maybe to e3. }
13... Rad8 14. Nf1 { Time to re-route the horsey. } 14... g6
{ Black keeps improving the bishop. } 15. Ng3 Bg7 16. Qc1
{ This move overprotects the White queen, which enables him to potentially push d4-d5. Alternatively, we can continue with b3-b4, a2-a4, etc, grabbing space on the kingside. Taking on d4 is always positionally wrong, as it simply concedes the center and enables White to have a better access to the d6-weakness. Otherwise, we will keep slowly improving the position, and Black cannot do anything whatsoever. }
16... a6 { Instead, let's suppose Black keeps waiting. } 17. b4
{ Now, c4-c5! is potentially also on the agenda. Let's pretend Black keeps waiting - what else can he do? }
17... Ba8 18. c5 { Now, the position is getting critical. } 18... bxc5 19. bxc5
dxc5 20. dxe5 Ng4 21. e6 { And White gets a winning position. } 21... Rxe6 22.
Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Bxa6
{ And we have a decisive potential advantage due to the much better pawn structure, the passed a-pawn and the weak c-pawns. The a8-bishop is absolutely dead, too. Black could certainly play much better, not allowing the position to fall apart so quickly, but he certainly had no active opportunities whatsoever, which is obviously a very unpleasant situation to be in, from practical perspective. }
