[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Old Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Astaneh Lopez, Alex vs. Baburin, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6 3. d4 { It's important to prevent ... e7-e5. } 3... Bg4 4.
e3
{ This precise move order disallows ...Bxf3, which could otherwise spoil the pawn structure. }
4... Nbd7 5. h3
{ Challenging the bishop as early as possible makes a lot of sense, so that we either grab the bishop pair or force it to the awkward h5-square, where we can always harass it with g2-g4. }
5... Bxf3 6. Qxf3 c6
{ Having given up the bishop pair, Black tries to build a solid position in the center, as opposed to opening it up. }
7. Bb2 g6 8. Nd2 Bg7 9. g4
{ A very creative move, which immediately shows White's ambitions on the kingside. Now, it's the time for us to castle long and prepare h3-h4-h5 and g4-g5. }
9... Qa5 10. a3
{ It's important to play this move, so that we can castle without hanging the a2-pawn. }
10... e5 11. O-O-O O-O
{ Here, White needed to start opening the game as soon as possible to utilize the potential of his bishop pair. }
12. g5
{ I am not a big fan of this move, since it allows the Black knight to occupy a powerful blockading position on h5.   12.dxe5!  dxe5  13.h4±  Next, h4-h5 is on the way, followed by Qh3 with a very powerful attack on the h-file. }
12... Nh5 13. h4 exd4 14. Nc4
{ 14.exd4  Would have potentially been somewhat stronger, so that the knight can instead go to e4. }
14... Qc7 15. Bxd4 d5
{ Now, Black is safe on the kingside, and might be already seizing the initiative, because he has more space in the center. }
16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Nb2 f5
{ This move is not terrible, but Black could start action on the queenside somewhat quicker.   17...Nc5!  Would have brought the knight to e4, and potentially prepared ...Qa5, attacking the weakened White king. }
18. Be2
{ White's goal is to move the queen and threaten Bxh5, which is a serious problem, because the h5-knight is trapped. }
18... f4 19. e4
{ Black has ruined the blockade he himself had created, now White is much better, as he's opening the position and the third rank is now available for the queen. For example, the check on c3 could be unpleasant to deal with at times. }
19... Ne5
{ 19...dxe4?  20.Qc3+!  Kg8??  21.Bc4++-  Look how active the White pieces became, all of a sudden! Now, the game is over. }
20. Qc3 f3 21. Rxd5 { With this cute tactical idea, White wins a pawn. } 21...
Rae8 22. Bd1
{ White managed to keep the position under control while retaining an extra pawn. Of course, he is winning. }
22... Qe7 23. Rd3 { 23.Rd2  Would have been a lot safer. } 23... Kg8 24. Re3
Qxa3
{ 24...Nf4!  Would have again come close to turning the tables, as ...Ng2 is about to trap the rook. }
25. Kb1 Qe7 26. Nd3
{ White returned the pawn, but now removes the e5-knight, which is holding the f3-pawn. Once the knight is gone, the f3-pawn would fall and we would be much better. }
26... Nf4
{ The parties agreed to a draw, but it seems premature. For example, after }
27. Nxe5 Qxe5 28. Qxe5 Rxe5 29. Bxf3
{ White is a pawn up, and even though Black had managed to establish a fairly reliable blockade, it's only a blockade good enough for a potential fortress, rather than for creating any threats or active counterchances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Old Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Hess, Robert L vs. Auger, Michael W"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 d6 2. Bb2 c6
{ Again, the game started with a weird move order, but soon enough tranposed to our repertoire. }
3. Nf3 Qc7 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nbd2 Nbd7 6. e4 e5
{ Instead of grabbing space with c2-c4, White chooses a somewhat different setup. }
7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4
{ This move is aimed at preventing ...b7-b5, which could enable Black to grab space on the queenside and generate at least some activity. }
9... b6 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Nf1
{ Unfortunately, this move decreases White's control over the e4-square and allows for counterplay.   11.Bf1  In my view, it would have made sense to prepare c2-c4, grabbing even more space on the queenside. Later, that could be even followed with b3-b4, a4-a5, etc. }
11... Rfe8
{ 11...d5!  Would have given Black a lot of counterplay. For example:  12.dxe5  Nxe4!  13.Bd3  Ndc5!  Would see Black activate his pieces. However, we can also pursue our play on the kingside with f2-f4.  14.Nd4  Qxe5   14...Rfe8  15.Nf5±  With initiative, as Qg4 is on the way, followed by f2-f4.  15.b4!  Ne6  16.Nxc6!  Leads to some messy complications  16...Qxb2  17.Nxe7+  Kh8  Here, White's knight on e7 looks rather weird, but perhaps he can maintain the dynamic balance.  18.Bxe4  dxe4  19.Qd7  Rab8  20.Nf5  With Nd6 coming, White should be just fine. But, frankly, we've looked at some messy complications, which are interesting from the perspective of having fun, but absolutely useless from opening preparation standpoint, because we don't ever need to allow for that break. However, it's good to be aware of the potential dangers we can face unless we are paying attention! }
12. Ng3 { Now, White is again in control. } 12... Bf8 13. Qd3
{ Again, White allows for the ...d6-d5! break.   13.dxe5  dxe5?   13...Nxe5!  14.Bxe5  dxe5  15.Ng5!  And again the f7-pawn is a huge problem.  15...Re7  16.Nf5!  Rd7  17.Qf3±  With ideas like Rad1, trading the d7-rook and depriving Black of defenders of the f7-pawn, White's position is dominant. Furthermore, Nh6+ is something Black always needs to be careful about.  14.Ng5!  Would win on the spot, as there is no way to defend the f7-pawn.  14...Re7  15.Nf5+-  And the rook is trapped. }
13... h6
{ 13...d5!  This thematic break would have again given Black a very comfortable game.  14.Ba6  Bxa6  15.Qxa6  exd4  With severe pressure on the e4-pawn. Importantly, Black has a nice positional finesse here.  16.exd5  c5∓  And the d5-pawn is very weak, and will likely fall. Moral of the story: don't allow for the ...d6-d5 pawn break in such positions! }
14. Rad1 Rad8 15. Ba6
{ White is looking to trade the bishops to potentially negate the dangers of ...d6-d5. If I were White, I would have rather exchanged the d-pawns, preventing that idea altogether. }
15... Ba8 16. Nf5
{ 16.dxe5!  dxe5  17.Qe2⩲  Would have been a very comfortable position, where we can follow up with Nh4-f5, for example, Bc4, etc. }
16... exd4 17. Qxd4
{ 17.N3xd4!  Would have been a lot stronger, preparing Qg3! with attacking ideas on the kingside. That would have made the f5-knight, the g3-queen and the b2-bishop feel as though they were on cloud nine! }
17... Ne5
{ 17...c5!  Would have won the e4-pawn, as that a8-bishop springs to life with tempo. }
18. Qc3
{ 18.Qe3!  Would have been even stronger, preparing to bring the queen to g3 or h3, attacking the Black king, which is barely defended, as the Black queen and other pieces are hardly able to protect it. }
18... c5 19. Nxe5 dxe5 20. f3
{ Now, White is positionally dominating.  Why so? Well, because the a8-bishop is terrible, so is one on f8. Instead, the White light-squared bishop can come to c4, the f5-knight is amazing, the d5-square is weak. All these factors enable us to say White is nearly winning. }
20... Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Rd8 22. Rd3
{ 22.Rxd8!  Qxd8  23.Qxe5!  Would have been winning, but maybe White was unsure of what happens after a check on d1.  23...Qd1+  24.Bf1+-  White is entirely winning, as Nh6+! is a threat. }
22... Rxd3 23. Bxd3 Nd7 24. Bc4 g6 25. Ne3
{ The knight is getting re-routed to d5. } 25... Qd6 26. Qe1 Nb8 27. Bb5 Bg7
28. Nc4
{ Positioning the knight on d5 would have been more natural, but it's not misplaced on c4, either. }
28... Qc7 29. Qd2
{ Unfortunately, this well-played strategic game now goes wrong, as White suddenly gets his bishop trapped. }
29... a6 30. Be8 Qe7 { 30...Kf8  31.Nd6  Ke7-+  Black just wins a piece. } 31.
Nd6 { Now, the bishop is perfectly safe. } 31... Bf8 32. Bxf7+ Kh7 33. Nc8
{ 33.Nc4!!  Qxf7  34.Qd8+-  And White would have gotten the missing minor piece back, because not only the b8-knight and a8-bishop are hanging, but also the f8-bishop will be endangered if Black were to go ...Qb7 or something along those lines.  34...Bxe4 }
33... Qxf7 34. Nxb6
{ White missed an opportunity to get the piece back, got only two pawns for it and eventually the game was drawn. While the rest of it was fun, probably it's not the most instructive thing in the world, so let's cut in here and just learn a few crucial positional ideas from the early middlegame, such as preventing ...d6-d5, bringing the knight on f5 and queen on g3 to attack the king, and so on. }
