[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Old Indian: Model Games"]
[Black "Horacek, Donald vs. Evans, Stanley W"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 d6 3. d4 Bg4 4. e3 Nbd7 5. h3 Bh5
{ This time, Black chooses to keep the bishop for the time being, which is a more ambitious decision than the spineless ...Bxf3. }
6. Bb2 e5
{ Black looks to immediately carry out his main pawn break, claiming it is safe to do so because of the pinned f3-knight. }
7. g4
{ While breaking the pin is not a terrible idea, we prefer a different theoretical solution. But still, let's see how the game developed!   7.dxe5  dxe5  8.Nbd2  is the variation we analyze in the theoretical part. }
7... Bg6 8. Bg2
{ The bishop certainly belongs on the long diagonal. Now, White is ready to grab the bishop pair with Nh4. }
8... exd4 9. Nxd4 c6
{ Black restricts the g2-bishop, preparing to play ... d6-d5. } 10. Nd2 d5
{ Black builds the center, but we are about to challenge it. } 11. Qe2
{ 11.g5!?  Ne4  12.h4±  Would have been a very logical, ambitious and strong path. Now, h4-h5! is a threat, trapping the bishop. }
11... Be7
{ 11...Bb4!  Would have at least been somewhat active, developing fast and potentially looking to pin the knight with ...Ne4. }
12. Nf5
{ Unfortunately, White misses an opportunity to develop a decisive initiative on the kingside.   12.g5!  Ne4  13.h4!  Is again strong, preparing h4-h5. Black could try to stop that threat, but it wouldn't result in a particularly appealing position.  13...h5  14.Nxe4  Bxe4  15.Bxe4  dxe4  16.O-O-O  +-  Now, White is ready to play Nf5, maybe g5-g6 or Rg1, we are completely winning. Of course, Black cannot castle, either, as that would drop the h5-pawn. }
12... Bxf5 13. gxf5 Qc7
{ Black prepares to castle long, which is very logical, since short castling will greatly expose his king to the attack on the g-file. }
14. O-O-O
{ 14.c4!?  Challenging the opponent in the center would have been very reasonable and promising. The biggest appeal of that move is that it would have discouraged long castling.  14...O-O-O ??  15.cxd5!  cxd5??  16.Rc1  And White wins a piece, as now the queen is hanging, so Black is forced to block the file.  16...Nc5  17.b4+-  With an easy win. }
14... O-O-O 15. Kb1
{ 15.c4!  Would have again made a lot of sense, opening the g2-bishop.  15...dxc4?!  16.Nxc4↑  With Be5 coming next, the d6-square appears rather weak, so does the Black king overall. }
15... Kb8 16. f4 { This move weakens the e3-pawn. } 16... Rhe8 17. Rhe1 Bd6 18.
Qf2 Ka8
{ Now, Black is in full control, and unfortunately, White does not have much play himself. That's why it was crucial to play c2-c4 a lot faster! }
19. c4 dxc4
{ 19...Nc5⩱  Would have taken full advantage of the weakened d3-square. } 20.
Nxc4
{ Now, the d6-bishop is hanging and e3-e4-e5 is on the most urgent agenda. }
20... Bf8 21. e4 Nh5 22. e5
{ Black had certainly misplayed it and now is getting pushed back and restricted. }
22... g6 23. f6
{ 23.Bd4!  Would have been even stronger, attacking the a7-pawn. The main point is that  23...a6??  24.e6!  Wins on the spot.  24...Ndf6  25.Be5+-  Next, Nb6 is a checkmate or a decisive discovery that wins the queen. }
23... Nc5 24. Nd6
{ 24.Bd4!  Would have been even more direct, attacking the c5-knight, which has nowhere to go as the a7-pawn would hang. Importantly,  24...b6?  25.f5+-  Would prepare e5-e6! and then e6-e7!, just simply queening those pawns! }
24... Bxd6 25. exd6 Qa5 26. Re7 Rf8 27. Re5
{ And Black resigned, as he is losing a piece, because it's not possible to defend the knight with ...b7-b6. This was a complex game, for sure. Our main takeaway as that g4-g5! can be a very strong idea early on, pushing the Black pieces back. If that is not possible for whatever reason when the position is slightly different, then we need to open the game in a different way, such as with c2-c4!, but otherwise, the bishop pair won't be particularly useful. }
27... b6 28. Bxc6+ { Was the problem. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld "]
[Black "Grunfeld becomes lame Slav #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares.   White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ...c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... c6 { Most people play this way, but this is far from ambitious. } 7. Be2
{ We don't need to do anything brilliant to have a comfortable game in these Shlekhter Slav type of positions, as we just have more space and the g7-bishop is very passive. However, a few ideas are worth knowing. }
7... Bf5
{ Is also a possible way to develop the bishop, but it makes less sense to me, because it can end up in danger on f5 due to such ideas as Nh4, or h2-h3 and g2-g4, and so on. Why not just trade it for the White knight on f3? }
8. O-O Nbd7 9. h3
{ This very interesting move restricts Black even more, preventing him from accessing the g4-square with his pieces, while potentially threatening g2-g4. Again, I believe these positions should be studied on the level of ideas rather than forcing sequences, so let's look at a  model game  (varition:15294119)  (.) }
