[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld "]
[Black "6...e6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares.   White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ...c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... e6
{ Generally, the moves ...g7-g6 and ...e7-e6 do not combine well, and that is because they weaken the dark squares, such as f6. If Black wants to generate counterplay, he needs to prepare ...c7-c5 in the future, at which point the question arises: why didn't he play ...c7-c5 right away instead? }
7. Nbd2 b6 8. Rc1
{ White keeps developing, taking the c-file under control, which helps suppress ideas like ...c7-c5. }
8... Bb7 9. cxd5
{ We eliminate the tension in the center, as recapturing back with the pawn makes the b7-bishop somewhat unhappy, while taking back with the piece is awkward, too. }
9... exd5
{ In the games that reached this position, everyone took with the pawn. } 10.
Be2 Nbd7 11. O-O { White finishes the development. } 11... c5
{ Sooner or later, the c7-pawn would become a problem, so Black immediately claims space in the center with ...c7-c5. }
12. Rc2
{ Next, we'll play Qa1, preparing to create pressure on the somewhat vulnerable a1-h8 diagonal, which will be followed with Rfc1, threatening the c5-pawn more. An interesting balanced fight is ahead, where I would pick White, as he will be the one deciding when and if the pressure in the center should be released. }
