{ Here is the novelty: we are simply pushing the Black pieces away, grabbing space and winning time. }
14... Na4
{ Might seem tempting to attack that b2-bishop, but this move is wrong as it signiicantly misplaces the knight. }
15. Be5 { We save the precious bishop while also winning time. } 15... Rcc8 16.
Rfc1
{ White is much better, as the a4-knight is completely out of play and our minor pieces are a lot more active: we own the a1-h8 diagonal, the c-file, etc. Importantly, now c4-c5! might be a strong positional idea, creating a dangerous passed pawn, which will be supported by the rooks. }
