[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld "]
[Black "6....c5 with 7...dxc4 #1- a narrow path to an awkward endgame"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares.   White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ...c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... c5 7. dxc5 dxc4
{ This move was played once only@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, so I wouldn't worry too much about the theoretical equality, but this is Black's best chance. }
8. Qxd8
{ This natural move is a novelty.  Of course, there is no need to lose castling rights. }
8... Rxd8 9. Bxc4
{ Okay, so for the time being, we are a pawn up, and Black certainly needs to hurry to get it back, or else White will develop and keep it with b3-b4. }
9... Ne4
{ Is coming close to equalizing the game from the engine perspective, but I fail to trust this idea due to the following strong idea. }
10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. Ne5
{ Not only do we attack the f7-pawn, but also we are about to play Nd3!, defending the c5-pawn. }
11... Nc6 { Is the engine move, but I fail to trust it for two reasons. } 12.
Nxf7
{ And more importantly, Black needs to temporarily sacrifice a pawn, which looks really odd. }
12... Rf8
{ Once the knight retreats, the f2-pawn will be in danger. So, we ignore the threat and create ours, looking to dislodge the e4-horse. }
13. Bd5 Nxc5 14. Bxc6
{ Our goal is to worsen his pawn structure and simply retreat to e5 with our knight, playing for long-term positional advantages. }
14... Nd3+ 15. Ke2 Nxf2 { Now, Black bails out, for example } 16. Rf1 bxc6 17.
Rxf2 Rxf7 18. Rxf7+ Kxf7 19. Nd2
{ This position should be a draw, even though we still have the superior pawn structure. This sequence is just an example of how deeply we can dig, however, it's by no means something you need to remember.  It is much rather an indication that to make up for his structural downsides, Black needs to find some incredibly precise dynamic moves, which is highly unlikely, of course, if not outright impossible. }
