[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld "]
[Black "6....c5 with 7...dxc4 #6 - Black plays perfectly and draws"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares.   White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ...c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... c5 7. dxc5 dxc4
{ This move was played once only@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, so I wouldn't worry too much about the theoretical equality, but this is Black's best chance. }
8. Qxd8
{ This natural move is a novelty.  Of course, there is no need to lose castling rights. }
8... Rxd8 9. Bxc4
{ Okay, so for the time being, we are a pawn down, and Black certainly needs to hurry to get it back, or else White will develop and keep it with b3-b4. }
9... Nbd7
{ This move might look obvious, so you might be wondering, why would I award it with an exclamation mark? Well, because it results in an ugly pawn structure but still equalizes, so Black needs to acknowledge the dynamic benefits of his position. }
10. b4 { Is an ambitious attempt to keep the extra pawn, but after } 10... a5
11. a3 Ne4
{ Black manages to get counterplay with this key move. What is the idea behind it? This is rather cute, actually. So, Black cannot ever create any issues by trading on b4 and taking on a1, because the White bishop is protecting the rook! However, with his last move, Black unleashes the bishop on g7, the point being to trade bishops and to start threatening that a1-rook!  A very subtle idea, if you ask me. }
12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Ra2
{ Is a principled attempt to keep the pawn, but Black has enough counterplay here. }
13... axb4 14. axb4 Rxa2 15. Bxa2 Nb8
{ I wholeheartedly admit I don't believe for a single second you will ever see this sequence, especially Black's last move, which is aimed at threatening either ...Na6 with a fork, or ...Nc6. However, we also need to admit White has no advantage if Black finds this idea, and the queenside will soon evaporate. }
16. Nfd2 Nxd2 17. Nxd2 Na6 { Black gets the pawn back. } 18. Bc4 Nxb4 19. Ke2
{ This should be a simple draw, which is a good way to test Black's knowledge and precision in defense, but of course, this is not a real theoretical challenge, so let's take a step back and look for something better. }
