[White "Anti-Grunfeld "]
[Black "6....c5 with 7...dxc4 #8 - superior structure"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares.   White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ...c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... c5 7. dxc5 dxc4
{ This move was played once only@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@, so I wouldn't worry too much about the theoretical equality, but this is Black's best chance. }
8. Qxd8
{ This natural move is a novelty.  Of course, there is no need to lose castling rights. }
8... Rxd8 9. Bxc4
{ Okay, so for the time being, we are a pawn down, and Black certainly needs to hurry to get it back, or else White will develop and keep it with b3-b4. }
9... Nbd7
{ This move might look obvious, so you might be wondering, why would I aware it with an exclamation mark? Well, because it results in an ugly pawn structure but still equalizes, so Black needs to acknowledge the dynamic benefits of his position. }
10. c6 { We immediately spoil his pawn structure. } 10... bxc6 11. O-O
{ Now, we have the better pawn structure, but Black has ways of winning time by attacking our pieces @@StartBracket@@for example, ... Nb6 is about to win a tempo on the bishop@@EndBracket@@. Additionally, he can try to liquidate some of the queenside pawns with ...a5-a4, which is a strategically dangerous plan because bxa4 will result in a pawn structure where White has an outside passer on the a-file, however, this idea might still succeed at times. }
11... a5 12. Nc3 e6
{ Let's suppose Black just waits in order to see how we obtain a dominant strategic position. }
13. Na4 Nd5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rfd1
{ Now, e3-e4 is on the way, kicking that knight on d5 away and restricting Black. Alternatively, Ng5-e4 is a strong plan, preparing to install one of the knights on c5. Furthermore, the simple Rac1, Kf1-e1, etc are going to be played next, centralizing the king and starting to create pressure on the weak c6-pawn. Black's c6-pawn is a problem, the c5-square is an outpost for our pieces, the b7-bishop is bad. All in all, we are much better and the position is really easy to play! }
