8. Qxd8
{ This natural move is a novelty.  Of course, there is no need to lose castling rights. }
8... Rxd8 9. Bxc4
{ Okay, so for the time being, we are a pawn down, and Black certainly needs to hurry to get it back, or else White will develop and keep it with b3-b4. }
9... Nbd7
{ This move might look obvious, so you might be wondering, why would I aware it with an exclamation mark? Well, because it results in an ugly pawn structure but still equalizes, so Black needs to acknowledge the dynamic benefits of his position. }
10. c6 { We immediately spoil his pawn structure. } 10... bxc6 11. O-O
{ Now, we have the better pawn structure, but Black has ways of winning time by attacking our pieces @@StartBracket@@for example, ... Nb6 is about to win a tempo on the bishop@@EndBracket@@. Additionally, he can try to liquidate some of the queenside pawns with ...a5-a4, which is a strategically dangerous plan because bxa4 will result in a pawn structure where White has an outside passer on the a-file, however, this idea might still succeed at times. }
11... a5 12. Nc3 Nb6
{ Black needs to immediately create some counterplay, or else Na4! would be very strong, taking away the b6-square and preparing to install the horsey on c5. }
13. Rfd1
{ We are ignoring the positional threat of Nxc4, as the Black rook is now under attack. }
13... Rxd1+ 14. Rxd1
{ We are threatening Rd8+, which will tie all the Black pieces on the back rank.  Of course, that idea has to be addressed. }
14... Nxc4 15. Rd8+ Bf8 16. bxc4
{ Is a positional disaster for Black, because the Black pieces are stuck on the back rank. For example, Ba3 is a threat, intending to capture the pawn on e7. Now, the only defense for Black is }
16... Bb7 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 { However, now his queenside pawns are weak. } 18. Nd4
{ The White knight is headed to b3 in order to challenge that a5-pawn. The opponent needs to be extremely precise, or else he will lose the a5-pawn and likely the game. }
18... e5 { Black is looking to play ...Bb4, protecting the a5-pawn. } 19. Nb3
{ Black is already losing a pawn, because an attempt to protect it aggravates his life even more. }
19... Bb4 20. Na4
{ Now, the pawn on e5 is hanging, and a2-a3! is also a threat, tucking the bishop away to win the pawn on a5. I am afraid it's not possible for Black to address both threats, so he loses. A good example of how things can go wrong! }
