{ We are ignoring the positional threat of Nxc4, as the Black rook is now under attack. }
13... Rxd1+ 14. Rxd1
{ We are threatening Rd8+, which will tie all the Black pieces on the back rank.  Of course, that idea has to be addressed. }
14... Bg4
{ Black deals with the threat of Rd8 while also developing one of the last inactive pieces. }
15. Be2 { We remove the bishop, stopping the idea of ...Nxc4. } 15... a4
{ Black needs to immediately swap the queenside pawns. } 16. Nxa4 Nxa4 17. bxa4
{ The a4-pawn is certainly weak, but it cannot be captured right away. } 17...
Ne4
{ With very precise play, Black will be able to neutralize our initiative and save half a point. He trades the bishops to make sure his king won't be in danger after the future Rd8, as he makes room for it on g7, and prepares to jump on c3 with the knight after the trade. }
18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rd4
{ These moves are not entirely forced, but I still want to make sure we look at ways to create problems for the opponent even after he makes so many precise decisions in a row. For the time being, we are attacking both of his minor pieces, forcing an ugly move like ...f7-f5, or an awkward retreat like ...Nf6. }
19... Nf6 20. Bd1
{ An interesting idea - the bishop is now gonna be used to defend the a4-pawn and to come over to b3, overprotecting the queenside. }
20... c5 21. Rc4 Ra5 22. Bb3
{ White keeps the extra pawn, but Black has created a rather reliable position we'll have a somewhat hard time breaking through in.   However, while we are not objectively better, I consider this outcome a big success: first, there is no objective advantage in the Grunfeld overall, just like in any major opening, and secondly, we got Black in a position where he made the right decision as early on move 7@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ only once @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ so far. }
