[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld "]
[Black "6....c5 with 7...Qa5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5
{ In the Grunfeld style, Black also grabs a fair share of the center, fighting for the c4 and e4-squares.   White can choose to either develop slowly, or to challenge the center right away with c2-c4. That move is not bad, but if Black knows what he is doing, he will be able to get a relatively safe position pretty fast. However, I still recommend that we play the principled move 6.c4, because as practice shows, Black players are not aware of the right path! }
6. c4
{ Now, Black will either counterattack in the center with ...c7-c5, or play ...c7-c6, reinforcing it. Some people also tried ...b7-b6 and ...e7-e6, which are not terrible continuations, so we'll look at those as well. }
6... c5 7. dxc5 Qa5+
{ This move was played more or less at all times, even by such strong players as Mamedyarov, but it's suspicious, as now we'll win a ton of time while attacking the Black queen. }
8. Nbd2
{ Here, Black can make a few choices, such as recapturing the c5-pawn, which is the most obvious continuation, or playing ...Rd8 to pin the knight, or even taking on c4 right away. }
8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Qxc5
{ Is likely going to transpose to positions very similar to the ones after 8...Qxc5, but let's see a few more moves. }
10. Rc1 Qd6
{ The Women's World Champion chose to retreat to this seemingly safe square. The central pawns have been eliminated, but the White pieces are a lot more active, especially the bishops, so we should have the dynamic advantage. }
11. O-O Nc6 12. Qe2
{ Next we are about to play Rfd1, which will x-ray the Black queen on d6, eiter making the opponent waste even more time moving it around, or exposing him to ideas like Ne4!?, for instance. }
12... a6
{ Black made this move to prevent Bb5 followed by a capture on c6, for example. Seems to make sense, as it's a bit difficult to say what else she could do. Now, it's time for an improvement. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@91@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Ju,W @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 }
13. e4
{ This move seems rather natural, doesn't it? White takes more space and prepares e4-e5!, threatening to win a piece. }
13... e5
{ Black stops the threat of e4-e5, but this move shuts down the g7-bishop and significantly improves one on c4. }
14. Rfd1
{ Now, a few interesting plans could be Nb1-c3-d5!?, taking advantage of the freshly-created outpost on d5, or Ng5!?, putting pressure on the f7-pawn. }
14... Qe7 15. h3
{ We restrict Black even more, preventing ...Bg4 and ...Ng4. Later, we can for example proceed with Bd5, Nc4 and Ba3, activating all of our minor pieces and using the weak squares on d6, d5, etc. What can our opponent even do?! }
