[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld: Model Games"]
[Black "Dmitry Gordievsky vs. Gabriela Antova, Lichess.org, 2020 "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. b3 Nf6 3. Bb2 c5 4. e3 g6
{ Interestingly enough, this position has been analyzed in our repertoire via this move order in the chapter on the Reversed Queen's Indian! Here, however, we analyze the moves 5.c4 and 5.Bb5. }
5. d4 { 5.c4  is our main move. } 5... Bg7 6. dxc5 Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 Qxc5 8. c4 Nc6
9. a3 O-O 10. b4
{ Now, the game transposed to our chapter on the Anti-Grunfeld. Isn't it amazing how fluid and transpositional this repertoire is? Speaking of the move in the game, White is grabbing space on the queenside while also winning time. }
10... Qd6 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Ne4
{ Now, not only is the Black queen threatened, but also the d5-knight is in a somewhat awkward situation. }
13... Qd8 14. Qd2
{ We are about to follow up with Rd1 or Bc4, winning even more time by attacking that knight. A very important tactical idea is that Rd1 cannot be answered with a move like ...Nb6, because that would lose a queen. }
14... Bg4
{ 14...h6?  Let me illustrate the tactical danger I had just described.  15.Rd1!  Nb6??  16.Qb2++-  And White wins the queen, as the d1-rook was x-raying it! }
15. Be2 { Meanwhile, White just keep developing. } 15... Rc8 16. O-O f6
{ This move weakens the e6-square for no reason.   16...Nf6  Seems like a more natural move, but it doesn't solve his problems.    17.Qb2!  The queen on this square is going to be extremely well-placed. Importantly, the Black queen has a rather hard time finding good squares.  17...Qc7  18.Rac1  Now, b4-b5 is a threat, as the c6-knight is pinned.  18...Qb8  Black prevents the tactical threat of b4-b5, but not the queen is positioned very poorly and passively.  19.Rc5!?  We keep increasing the pressure on the c-file, preparing Rfc1, Qc3, and potentially b4-b5.  19...Rfd8  20.h3!  It makes sense to either grab the bishop, or force it to retreat, which will create a very nice tactical opportunity.  20...Be6?  Black cannot comfortably retreat, as after  21.g4!  g4-g5! is about to win the pinned f6-knight!    21...h6  22.g5!  hxg5  23.Nexg5  Now, of course, Nxe6 is a threat.  23...Bd7  24.b5!  Now, the c6-knight barely has any squares to go to.  24...Na5  25.Rxc8  Rxc8  26.Qb4!  Now, the a5-knight is in danger, and so is the e7-pawn.  We are winning a pawn, as both threats at the same time cannot be parried.  26...Qc7  27.Qxe7±  We just won a pawn for no compensation whatsoever and are nearly winning.  Not a bad outcome! Importantly, the Black king is still weak, so he needs to swap queens.  27...Bf5   27...Rf8??  28.Ne6++-  Is a very pretty tactical idea, which wins a queen, because the f7-pawn is pinned, and so is the d7-bishop.  28.Qxc7  Rxc7  29.Nd4±  We are just a pawn up in the endgame, the rest will depend on how passionate you are about the endgames :@@EndBracket@@ }
17. Rfd1
{ 17.Nd4+-  Would have been even stronger. The point is that the bishop cannot take on e2 due to the fork on e6.  17...Bxe2??   17...Bd7  18.Nc5!  Again, the fork on e6 is threatened.  18...Nxd4  19.Qxd4  We are threatening the d5-knight and the b7-pawn, which Black cannot defend with Bc6 due to the aforementioned fork.  19...Bc6??   19...b6??  20.Nxd7  Qxd7  21.e4+-  And again White wins a piece.  20.Ne6++-  18.Ne6++-  Wins on the spot. }
17... Nb6 18. Qb2 Qe8 19. Nc5
{ White still managed to keep a terrific amount of pressure. Now, the b7-pawn is very weak. }
19... e5
{ Black rightfully chooses to give it up.   19...Nd8  Would have defended the pawn for the time being, but after  20.a4+-  Bb5! and a4-a5 are on the way, Black's position is awfully passive and material conquests must be on the way. }
20. Nxb7 Rc7 21. Nd6
{ Not only is White a pawn up, but also, his pieces are a lot more active. The rest was rather easy. }
21... Qe7 22. h3 Be6 23. Rac1 Rd8 24. Ne4
{ The knight is coming over to c5. Next, the objective is to advance the queenside pawns. }
24... Bd5 25. Nc5 Qf7 26. b5 { Time to go! } 26... Na5
{ This blunders a tactic. } 27. Nxe5 fxe5 28. Ne6+
{ And White won a very cute game. } 28... Bxe6
{ 28...Qxe6?  29.Rxc7+  Next, e3-e4 follows and White wins a piece, as the d5-bishop is pinned. }
29. Qxe5+ Kh6 30. Rxc7
{ The tactical complications resulted in a position where White has a rook and three pawns for the awful minor pieces, such as the totally inactive a5-knight. }
30... Rxd1+ 31. Bxd1 Nac4 32. Rxf7 Nxe5 33. Rxa7
{ Black resigned, as the queenside pawns will easily promote. A great example of how superior piece activity in these symmetrical positions can create a lot of dangers. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld: Model Games"]
[Black "Maxim Rodshtein vs. Yannick Gozzoli, Brest, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 5. b3
{ This time, the game arrived at our Anti-Slav/Grunfeld setup via a normal Slav move order. }
5... Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Nbd2 Bg4 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. O-O
{ White just keeps developing, delaying any kind of action for the time being. }
9... Re8
{ 9...a6  If Black were to make a somewhat neutral move, we would immediately challenge the bishop.  10.h3!  Bh5??   10...Bf5  11.g4!  Be4  12.Ne5±  And Black is in deep trouble as f2-f3! is about to trap the bishop on e4!   10...Bxf3  11.Nxf3  Gives us a bishop pair and a pleasant long-term advantage. Admittedly, these positions are very solid for Black, but we are the ones with all the active ideas. Let's take a look at a logical sequence.  11...e6  12.a4!?  The idea is to grab space and prepare b4-b5, for instance, followed by Qb3, Rfc1, and so on, with easy and risk-free play on the queenside.  12...Re8  13.Bd3!?  Another useful idea could be to take the e4-square under more control. The plan is to go Qc2 and prevent ...Ne4 followed by ...f7-f5 forever.  13...Ne4  14.Qc2  f5  15.b4⩲  We are happy to ignore Black's knight for now, as we can follow up with Nd2 and then challenge it with f2-f3, later re-routing the knight on the queenside.  11.g4±  Just wins a piece and the game. }
10. Rc1
{ White places the rook on the c-file in advance, preparing to use it after exchanging on d5. }
10... a5
{ This move is weaker than ...e7-e6, as now Black cannot recapture with the e-pawn.   10...e6!  Would have been a lot better, the point being to be able to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn. Then, White would have played h2-h3, following the plan from the annotations above. }
11. cxd5 { A very timely trade, opening the file. } 11... cxd5 12. h3
{ Now, we grab the bishop pair. } 12... Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Qb6 14. Qc2
{ White takes the c-file under control, preparing to go Qc7, trade queens and obtain a very favorable endgame with the bishop pair, where our light-squared bishop would be amazing, while Black's g7-bishop is extremely inactive. }
14... e6 15. a4
{ The goal of this move is to take the b5-square under control. } 15... Bf8 16.
Bb5 { Of course, now it's time to use the square. } 16... Reb8 17. g4
{ White creates a tactical threat of g4-g5, kicking the f6-knight out and winning one on d7. Besides, he is just grabbing space on the kingside, which is perfectly safe as all the Black pieces are on the other side of the board. }
17... h6 18. h4 { Again, the threat is g4-g5, winning a knight. } 18... Qd8 19.
Qc7 { Our bishop pair is calling for the endgame! } 19... Nb6 20. Ne5
{ The threat is to take on c7. } 20... Qxc7 21. Rxc7
{ Again, the f7-pawn is a problem. } 21... Bd6 22. Rfc1
{ A fantastic positional exchange sacrifice. } 22... Nc4
{ Desperation.   22...Bxc7  23.Rxc7  Would have been terrible for Black, because the f7-pawn cannot be defended.  23...Rf8  24.Ba3!  And White would get the exchange back, while keeping a winning endgame, as the b7-pawn is also about to fall. }
23. Rxf7 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Kxf7 25. bxc4
{ White is still entirely winning, as the bishops are dominating the board. }
25... Ne8 26. cxd5 exd5 27. Bd7
{ Now, e5-e6! is on the way, creating a strong passed pawn. } 27... Ng7 28. f4
{ 28.Rd1!  Would have been even stronger, winning the d5-pawn. } 28... Ke7 29.
Bb5 Rc8 30. Rd1
{ Of course, White refuses to trade the rooks, attacking the d5-pawn instead. }
30... Rc2 31. Ba3+ Ke6 32. e4
{ A very nice tactical idea, which takes advantage of the tactically problematic e6-king. }
32... dxe4 33. Rd7
{ Now, Rxg7 is a threat, so is Rd6-g6 once the knight retreats. } 33... Rac8
{ 33...Ne8  34.Re7+!  And White wins a knight on e8 with a winning position. }
34. Re7+
{ Before capturing the knight, White just repeats moves to win a bit of time. }
34... Kd5 35. Rd7+ Ke6 36. Rxg7 R8c3 37. Re7+ Kd5 38. Rd7+ Ke6 39. Re7+ Kd5 40.
Rd7+ Ke6 41. Rd6+
{ Having repeated one more time, White gets on the right track. } 41... Kf7 42.
e6+ Ke7 43. Rc6+
{ And Black resigned, as he's losing an exchange, or the White pawn queens. }
43... Rxa3
{ 43...Kf6  44.Rxc3  Rxc3  45.e7  And the pawn queens on the next turn. A great positional accomplishment, in my opinion! As we can see, White was slightly better at first, and eventually developed a strong initiative on the queenside after opening the c-file. Instead, it would have been a lot better for Black to play ...e7-e6 faster, so that he could meet cxd5 with exd5, but even that would have resulted in a slightly inferior passive position, which, of course, is not an outcome we should be looking to shy away from. }
44. Rxc2 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Grunfeld: Model Games"]
[Black "Hikaru Nakamura vs. Razvan Preotu,  Chess.com, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 g6 3. Bb2 Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. d4 d5 6. c4 c5
{ Black chooses the most principled path, looking to liquidate the central tension. This is an approach we've already seen in Gordievsky's game, but it wouldn't hurt to see another example of Black having problems here. }
7. dxc5 Qa5+ 8. Nbd2 Qxc5 9. Rc1
{ Instead of capturing on d5 or starting with a2-a3, White begins with this move, which is very reasonable as well. }
9... Nc6 10. a3 { Time to grab space with b3-b4. } 10... Qd6 11. b4 dxc4 12.
Bxc4
{ The plan is to follow up with short castling, Qb3 and Rfd1, putting pressure on the f7-pawn and on the vulnerable Black queen. }
12... Ng4
{ Black trades a pair of pieces, but it wastes time and allows White to develop very comfortably. }
13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. O-O Rd8
{ This move is erroneous, as it weakens the f7-pawn. } 15. Qb3
{ Of course, this natural move is even more tempting when it comes with a tempo. }
15... Nge5
{ 15...e6?  Would fail to solve Black's problems, because now the dark-squares, in particular f6, are very weak.  16.Ne4!  Qe7  17.Qc3+!  Kg8??   17...f6  Does not lost on the spot, but the position is awful, as f6 is still weak, the g4-knight is misplaced and the queenside cannot get developed.  18.h3!  And White wins, as the knight cannot retreat due to the fork on f6.  18...Nh6  19.Nf6+  Kh8  20.Nd5++-  With a free extra queen. }
16. Rfd1
{ 16.b5!?  Would have been even more tempting, because Black cannot take on c4.  16...Nxc4?   16...Nxf3+  17.Nxf3  Now, the knight still barely has squares to retreat to.  17...Nb8?  is very passive.   17...Ne5  18.Nxe5  Qxe5  19.Bxf7±  White just wins a pawn. Importantly, the bishop is safe, because  19...e6  20.f4!  Will allow us to rescue the bishop either by means of Rc7, or maybe even with a gorgeous sacrifice.  20...Qf6  21.Bxg6!  hxg6  22.Rc7+  Rd7  23.Rfc1±  With two pawns for a piece and a threat of capturing on c8, as well as a completely dominant position, White is completely winning.  18.Rfd1  Qb6  19.Rxd8  Qxd8  20.Bxf7+-  With an absolutely decisive lead in development and an extra pawn.  17.Nxc4  Qc7  18.bxc6+-  With an extra piece. }
16... Nxc4 { This move only accelerates White's play. } 17. Nxc4 Qf6 18. b5
{ Time to push Black's pieces even further backward! } 18... Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 Nb8
{ Look at those beauties on the queenside :@@EndBracket@@ } 20. Nd6
{ Nakamura chooses the flashiest way to convert his decisive lead in development. The c1-rook is now attacking the bishop. }
20... Bd7 21. Nxb7
{ 21.Ne4!  Is even stronger, continuing to create dynamic threats.  21...Qb2  22.Rb1  Qa2  23.Qd4+!  We are looking to provoke weakening moves likes ... f7-f6 and keep attacking. Again, Black is so passive! }
21... a6 22. Nc5 Bxb5 23. a4 Bc6 24. Nd4
{ White returned the extra pawn and somewhat lost his lead in development, but is still a lot better. }
24... e5 25. Ndb3
{ 25.Nce6+!  Would have been a lot stronger.  25...fxe6  26.Nxc6  Nxc6  27.Rxc6±  With a huge advantage, as the king is very weak, so are the pawns on a6 and e6. }
25... Qe7 26. Na5 Be8 27. Qd5 { The White pieces keep dominating. } 27... Ra7
28. Nc4 Rc7 29. Nxe5 { White is just collecting the free pawn. } 29... Bxa4 30.
Qd4
{ Now, not only is the bishop hanging, but so are discoveries with the knight on e5, such as Nd7+ or Ng4+. }
30... f6 31. Ne6+ { And Black resigned as he is losing all of his material. }
31... Qxe6 32. Rxc7+
{ With decisive material gains and a decisive attack, too. Look, Black literally never got his queenside pieces out! }
