[Black "Playing for a slight space advantage"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 b6
{ Of course, this move, which is my very own recommendation for Black in the course on the Accelerated Queen's Indian, is to a large extent a critical test to this repertoire: what if Black simply keeps the symmetry? }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. e3 g6
{ Since positions after ...e6 are covered via QGD, as mentioned in the text, the only thing we need to analyze in this chapter is the Double Fianchetto, which is a rather ambitious opening for Black. This is typically the path Black would choose if he wants to make sure he avoids simplifications. Or, in other words, a 'must-win' line versus weaker opponents. }
5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White just quietly develops his pieces, not defining the situation in the center yet. At this point, Black can play in the Grunfeld-ish style with ...d7-d5, or flexibly with ...e7-e6, ... c7-c5. Of course, the plan ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 will transpose to King's Indian. }
7... e6
{ Is a more complex position, as Black keeps the tension in the center, keeping his options open. For example, he can wait with ...Qe7, ...Rd8, etc, and then go ...d7-d5, or ...c7-c5. I think attempts to memorize precise theory and sequences is not very helpful here. Instead, we should look at the model games. }
8. O-O d6
{ Is possible, but rather inactive. In the following game, White achieved a slight comfortable edge without much effort. }
9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Rad1 Qe7 11. d4 c5 12. Rfe1
{ White has more space and can keep improving the position with e3-e4, d4-d5, etc. We'll take a look at this example in the chapter on model games, too. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@ -Gumularz,S @@StartBracket@@2526@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
