{ Is a more complex position, as Black keeps the tension in the center, keeping his options open. For example, he can wait with ...Qe7, ...Rd8, etc, and then go ...d7-d5, or ...c7-c5. I think attempts to memorize precise theory and sequences is not very helpful here. Instead, we should look at the model games. }
8. O-O c5 9. d4
{ As Black isn't doing much in the center, White begins taking action. } 9...
Qe7 10. Rc1 d5
{ Is premature. It would be really useful for us to learn, why exactly, this pattern is very instructive. }
11. dxc5
{ Now, Black would be best served by taking on c5 with the knight, which is obviously impossible. }
11... bxc5 12. Na4
{ And I would feel very uncomfortable if I were Black, because the c5-pawn is extremely vulnerable. }
12... Nbd7 13. cxd5 { Time to destroy the center. } 13... exd5
{ Of course, taking on d5 with the piece means accepting a strategic defeat, as the pawn structure in that case would be atrocious. }
14. Bxf6
{ Now, the knight cannot recapture as the c5-pawn would be lost, while after }
14... Bxf6 15. Bb5
{ Wins a pawn for White, because the knight on d7 cannot move due to the c5-pawn hanging, while if it doesn't, Bxd7 and Nxc5 wins. }
