1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 b6
{ Of course, this move, which is my very own recommendation for Black in the course on the Accelerated Queen's Indian, is to a large extent a critical test to this repertoire: what if Black simply keeps the symmetry? }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. e3 g6
{ Since positions after ...e6 are covered via QGD, as mentioned in the text, the only thing we need to analyze in this chapter is the Double Fianchetto, which is a rather ambitious opening for Black. This is typically the path Black would choose if he wants to make sure he avoids simplifications. Or, in other words, a 'must-win' line versus weaker opponents. }
5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White just quietly develops his pieces, not defining the situation in the center yet. At this point, Black can play in the Grunfeld-ish style with ...d7-d5, of flexiblty with ...e7-e6, ... c7-c5. Of course, the plan ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 will transpose to King's Indian. }
7... c5 8. O-O d5
{ Is what a lot of players did, but the list of White's proponents of the line is even more impressive: Nepo, Karjakin, Martirosyan and many others! }
9. Nxd5
{ This is a very safe path, which will result in an equal endgame where Black would need to be somewhat careful. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. d4
{ Key position. Our plan is to obtain a slight pressure after simplifications. }
12... Na6
{ Is a typical way to protect the c-pawn in many cases, but here it doesn't work too well, as White now wins a lot of time. }
13. Bc4 Qd6 14. Qe2 { All the moves come with tempi on the Black pieces. }
14... Nb4 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. e4
{ Time to restrict that b7-bishop. The threat is a2-a3 and b3-b4, winning a lot of time and grabbing space. }
16... e5 { Black also fights for space in the center. } 17. h4
{ Now, given all the Black pieces are stuck on the queenside, it's not unreasonable for us to try our chances on the opposite flank. }
17... Rfd8 18. Ng5 { Again suddenly creates a huge problem with the f7-pawn. }
18... Rd7 19. Bxf7 { And White wins due to Ne6+ coming. } *

