5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White just quietly develops his pieces, not defining the situation in the center yet. At this point, Black can play in the Grunfeld-ish style with ...d7-d5, of flexiblty with ...e7-e6, ... c7-c5. Of course, the plan ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 will transpose to King's Indian. }
7... c5 8. O-O d5
{ Is what a lot of players did, but the list of White's proponents of the line is even more impressive: Nepo, Karjakin, Martirosyan and many others! }
9. Nxd5
{ This is a very safe path, which will result in an equal endgame where Black would need to be somewhat careful. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. d4
{ Key position. Our plan is to obtain a slight pressure after simplifications. }
12... cxd4 13. Qxd4+ Qxd4 14. Nxd4
{ Interestringly, from this objectively equal position White scored 75%. In my opinion, while it should be an easy draw for an engine, Black should play very carefully and we can certainly pose problems here. For example, the first question is, where should the Black knight go? }
14... Nc6
{ Does not solve all the problems, either. Why? Doesn't the position look entirely equal? Well, the move ...b7-b6 weakened the a6 square, and since both parties are interesed in fighting for the open c-file, the move Ba6! is now available to White, which means Black would always fail while challenging the c-file. }
15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Rfc1 Bd5 17. Rc7
{ The opponent still has no time to neuralize our slight initiative, as he needs to deal with our threats. }
17... e6 18. Ba6 { This classy move wins the c-file for good. } 18... Rfd8 19.
Rac1
{ Now, we will prepare f2-f3 and e3-e4, which will endanger the d5-bishop. It's not that easy to neutralize White's slight initiative. }
19... e5 20. g4
{ The goal now is to prepare g4-g5, which will suffocate Black's kingside. Later, we will maybe trade bishops with Bb7 and try to double on the seventh rank. Black should be undoubtedly holding, but things can quickly escalate. Let's see how that happens if he wastes a move or two. }
20... h6 21. Bb7 Bxb7 22. Rxb7 { Now, there's no good way to prevent Rc1-c7. }
22... Rdc8
{ This prevents the doubling of rooks on the 7th rank, but at the cost of a pawn. }
23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Rxa7 { And White is a pawn up and is completely winning. } *

