[Black "Mainline imbalance #2 - the gorgeous center"]
[Result "*"]

{ %evp 0,35,39,11,24,-8,12,12,12,5,20,15,23,-1,-1,2,6,-5,7,4,4,2,37,37,37,21, 60,36,20,23,9,14,15,17,27,37,29,37 }
1. Nf3 Nf6 2. b3 b6
{ Of course, this move, which is my very own recommendation for Black in the course on the Accelerated Queen's Indian, is to a large extent a critical test to this repertoire: what if Black simply keeps the symmetry? }
3. Bb2 Bb7 4. e3 g6
{ Since positions after ...e6 are covered via QGD, as mentioned in the text, the only thing we need to analyze in this chapter is the Double Fianchetto, which is a rather ambitious opening for Black. This is typically the path Black would choose if he wants to make sure he avoids simplifications. Or, in other words, a 'must-win' line versus weaker opponents. }
5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2
{ White just quietly develops his pieces, not defining the situation in the center yet. At this point, Black can play in the Grunfeld-ish style with ...d7-d5, of flexiblty with ...e7-e6, ... c7-c5. Of course, the plan ...d7-d6 and ...e7-e5 will transpose to King's Indian. }
7... c5 8. O-O d5
{ Is what a lot of players did, but the list of White's proponents of the line is even more impressive: Nepo, Karjakin, Martirosyan and many others! }
9. Nxd5
{ This is a very safe path, which will result in an equal endgame where Black would need to be somewhat careful. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Nxe3
{ Is also possible, but White will get an extra pawn in the center } 11. fxe3
Kxg7 12. d4
{ Now, the positional threat is d4-d5! followed by e3-e4!, grabbing space and restricting the b7-bishop. }
12... e6 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Rad1
{ Having centralized the pieces, we are ready to continue with d4-d5! and e3-e4! A warning: do that with caution, because while d4-d5 will give us a very strong passed pawn, ...exd5 will expose the backward e3-pawn, which can certainly be a problem in the long run if we mishandle things. We are already in brand-new territory with no games, but we can certainly estimate a couple logical moves for both sides. }
14... Qe7 15. d5
{ Once we prepare e3-e4!, White will have a large advantage, and will be always able to meet ...exd5 with exd5!. }
15... exd5 16. cxd5 a6
{ As we see after ...Rfe8, the tactical threat of Bb5 could be very annoying, so Black covers that square. }
17. Rfe1 Rfe8 18. e4
{ Once again, the pawn is untouchable due to Bb5!, but otherwise, White will be able to maintain his strong center and a very pleasant position.  Conclusion: Objectively speaking, the double fianchetto is a very decent solution for Black, and in the sequence with quick ...d7-d5 he is preparing rapid simplifications. If he handles the position well, he comes very close to a draw in those lines, and I understand the arising dry positions might not be something every single one of you would enjoy. However, I have a few things to say to cheer you up: 1@@EndBracket@@ Usually, people play Double Fianchetto to get a complex position, not to try to trade everything and hold a draw. 2@@EndBracket@@You can always choose to play d2-d4 instead of trading on d5, according to one of our model games. 3@@EndBracket@@This drawing line is one of the most problematic spots in this repertoire. So, that's not something you'll encounter much. Or, rather, something you'll see only once in ages. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Double Fianchetto: Model Games"]
[Black "Alireza Firouzja vs. Szymon Gumularz,  Chess.com, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e3 b6 2. c4 Bb7 3. Nc3 e6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. b3 g6 6. Bb2 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O
d6 9. Qc2 Nbd7 10. Rad1 Qe7 11. d4
{ And here we are, back to our repertoire. In return for some fighting chances and flexible center, Black had to concede the entire center, which, of course, gives White a comfortable advantage. }
11... c5 12. Rfe1 a6 13. a4
{ A nice prophylactical move: White makes sure ...b6-b5 will never be an agenda. }
13... Rac8 14. d5
{ Closing the center with d4-d5 is almost always beneficial when the opponent has fianchettoed the light-squared bishop, because now this piece is very inactive. }
14... e5 15. a5
{ Time to ruin Black's pawn structure. White takes advantage of the fact ...b6-b5 is not possible. }
15... bxa5
{ 15...b5  16.cxb5  axb5  17.Bxb5  Is something Black could do, but that would just cost him a pawn for little to no compensation. }
16. Ra1 { Now, White is scooping up the pray on the a-file. } 16... h6 17. Rxa5
Nh7 18. Nd2 f5 19. Bf1
{ 19.e4!  Seemed more accurate, preventing ...e5-e4 from Black, which activates his bishop and enables ...Ne5 in the future. }
19... h5 20. Raa1 h4
{ During the few last moves, e3-e4! would have always been rather strong for the aforementioned reasons. }
21. f4
{ Firouzja tries to take away the e5-square from the Black pieces, but e3-e4 would have achieved just that as well without letting the g7-bishop get active. }
21... e4 22. Ne2 Bxb2 23. Qxb2 Qg7
{ Black should have kept the queens on, because his weaknesses are long-term: the a6-pawn is a target, and after the queens are gone, White can take all the time in the world to harass that pawn. }
24. Qxg7+ Kxg7 25. Reb1 Ra8 26. b4
{ Time to get some action on the queenside!  The idea is that despite giving up the c5-outpost after ...cxb4, White benefits because he would gain the outpost on d4! }
26... Rfb8 27. Nb3
{ 27.bxc5!  Nxc5  28.Rb6!  Would have caused a lot of problems with the weak d6-pawn, and after  28...Rd8  29.Nb3!  White wins, because  29...Nxb3??  30.Rxb7++-  White gives a check and then also picks the b3-knight! }
27... cxb4 28. Ra5 Rc8 29. Ned4 Kf6 30. Ra4 Rab8 31. Rxb4
{ White still picked the pawn and enjoys a comfortable advantage due to weaknesses of the a6 and d6-pawns and his outpost on c6. }
31... Ba8 32. Rxb8 Rxb8 33. Ra1 Rb6 34. Kf2 Ke7 35. Ke1 Nhf6 36. Be2 Ne8 37.
Kd2 Nc7 38. Kc3 { Of course, the White king needed to come in action. } 38...
Rb8 39. Ra5 Rg8 40. Bf1 Rc8 41. Kd2 Rg8 42. Nc2 g5
{ Black should have kept waiting, as this unprepared pawn break creates a weak square on f4 and a weak pawn on f5. }
43. Ncd4 Kf6 44. Ne6 { 44.fxg5+  Would have been simple and good, too. } 44...
Nxe6 45. dxe6 Kxe6
{ 45...Nc5!  Would have kept the a5-rook away from attacking the f5-pawn and given Black some drawing chances. }
46. Nd4+ Ke7 47. Nxf5+ Kf6 48. Nxd6
{ Now, it's over, as White just collects all the pawns. } 48... gxf4 49. exf4
e3+ 50. Kxe3 Bxg2 51. Be2
{ 51.Rg5!  Would have won even quicker, because this move attacks both the g8-rook and the g2-bishop, while after  51...Rxg5  52.fxg5+  Is a check, which means White's got enough time to pick the bishop.  52...Ke6  53.Bxg2  Kxd6  54.Kd4+-  With an easy win due to two passed pawns. }
51... Nb8 52. Rh5 h3 53. Rh6+ Ke7 54. Nf5+ Kd7 55. Rh7+ Kc6 56. Nd4+
{ 56.Ne7+!  Time trouble....one of the sharpest tactical players of our time misses the simple fork. }
56... Kc5 57. Rc7+ Kb4 58. f5 Re8+ 59. Kd2 a5 60. f6 Rf8 61. f7 Na6 62. Re7 Nc5
63. Bh5 a4 64. Re8 Nd7 65. Ne6 a3 66. Nxf8 a2 67. Nxd7
{ And after some unnecessary complications, White won, because he is a bunch of material up and will queen the pawn with a check. The middlegame and endgame in this game was fun, but the most important part for us are the first 20-25 moves, where we saw how we can use our extra space, advance the d4-pawn and shut the b7-bishop down to follow with more action on the kingside. A great model game to pick the early middlegame ideas from, if you ask me. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Double Fianchetto: Model Games"]
[Black "Haik M. Martirosyan  vs. Rinat Jumabayev, Chess.com, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 Nf6 2. e3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 b6 5. c4 Bb7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O
c5 9. d4 Qe7
{ Okay, so instead of trying to simplify the game by preparing ...d7-d5, Black keeps the tension. Now what?  Let's have one of Armenia's top young talents answer that question. }
10. Rc1
{ White just keeping preparing his pieces for the upcoming middlegame. Next, Qd2 and Rfd1 seems to be a very easy followup. }
10... Rd8 11. Ba3
{ Time to put some pressure on the c5-pawn. In fact, this move has a somewhat deeper intent: Black might have still chosen to play ...d7-d5, trying to eliminate the center, so with his last move, White aims to provoke ...d7-d6, which will obviously discourage ...d7-d5. }
11... d6 12. Qd2 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Rfd1
{ Black manages to swap a pair of pieces, but White is still a tiny bit better due to his extra space. }
14... Na6 15. Bb2
{ White determined that ...d7-d5 is no longer a concern because after cxd5 the White e2-bishop will suddenly be able to attack the a6-knight! }
15... d5 { And Black falls just for that trap. } 16. cxd5
{ Of course, now White wins a pawn, as the a6-knight is hanging. } 16... Nb4
17. dxc5 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Nxd5 19. c6
{ And with his extra pawn, White went on to win rather easily. } 19... Rac8 20.
Ne5 f6 21. Nd7 { The f6-pawn is an issue, too. } 21... e5 22. f3
{ White wins a piece, now it's over. } 22... Nxe3
{ 22...Bf5?  23.Rxd5  wins the piece, of course. } 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 24. Rxd8+
Qxd8 25. fxe4 Qg5 26. Bf3 { White simply stops mate in one. } 26... Rc7 27. Qd2
Qf4 28. Qd8+
{ And Black resigned as he's also losing the c7-rook with check. You may wonder, what does this game teach us, given the main reason for Black's disaster was a blunder? I think this is an important observation to make: while White's advantage might not be large, and in fact the engine might be even claiming equality, it's crucial that Black has no counterplay whatsoever and his unprepared attempts to break through in the center can result in the position falling apart really fast, which is a good thing for the White players to know! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Double Fianchetto: Model Games"]
[Black "Istvan Csom vs. Gyula Horvath, Zalakaros, 1996"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. b3 g6 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Nc3
d5
{ This is the most principled line Black can choose against our setup. The point is simple: he wants to eliminate the entire center and draw the game. Admittedly, unless you are a titled player, no one would ever want to draw, as most people at a club level play for a win with both colours. But in either case, we want to see a successful example of White's play. }
9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ 10...Nxe3  Is also possible and is analyzed in detail in the theoretical chapter. }
11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. d4
{ White is looking to trade queens and get a slight edge in the endgame. }
12... cxd4 13. Qxd4+ Qxd4 14. Nxd4 Nd7
{ 14...Nc6  15.Nxc6!  Doesn't equalize for Black, and despite us reviewing that in the theoretical part of the course, I'd like to emphasize one key idea again.  15...Bxc6  16.Rfc1  Now, it's desirable for Black to fight for the c-file, but that isn't possible!  16...Rfc8?  17.Ba6!  Rc7  18.Rc3+-  And White wins the piece due to the pin, as Rac1 and Bb5 will attack that c6-bishop too many times. }
15. Rfc1
{ It's useful to fight for the c-file exactly with this rook. Why so? Well, because we now have an endgame position, so we need to actively use our king. Now, our king can join the game via f1-e1-d2. }
15... Rfc8
{ 15...Rac8?  Is a natural mistake. The problem with this move is discussed in the theoretical chapter , the point being that  16.Bg4!  creates a problem, as the knight is pinned. Crucially,  16...e6??  17.Bxe6!  fxe6  18.Nxe6+  Kg8  19.Nxf8+-  results in a winning position with a rook and two pawns for two minor pieces. }
16. b4
{ White grabs space and prevents the Black pieces from having access to the c5-square. }
16... a6 17. a3 Kf6 18. f3
{ This move is aimed at preparing e3-e4, which will grab space and restrict the Black b7-bishop. }
18... e6 19. Kf2 Ke7 20. e4 e5
{ This move also fights for the space. It seems nice that Black positions his pawns on the dark squares, which is supposed to be good, because he has a light-squared bishop. However, this move also weakens the a2-g8 diagonal and the d5-square, so it's not such a one-sided move. }
21. Nb3 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Rc8
{ Black swaps the rooks, looking to simplify the game even more. } 23. Ke3 Rxc1
24. Nxc1 Nb8 25. Nb3 Bc6 26. Nd2
{ The knight is slowly finding its way towards the greener pastures, such as c4, from where it attacks the pawns on b6 and e5. }
26... f6 27. Nc4 Nd7 28. Nb2
{ The a6-pawn is now attacked. The game remains balanced, but it's not a draw yet! }
28... Nb8 { 28...b5  29.Nd3!  Will allow the knight to come to the c5-square. }
29. h4
{ White takes advantage of an opportunity to grab space on the kingside. }
29... Bb5
{ Black strives to trade more pieces, but now his pawn structure becomes very rigid and inflexible.   29...h5?  Stops White from grabbing space, but after  30.g4!  White is now either going to get an outside passed pawn, or create a weakness on h5.  30...hxg4   30...b5  31.gxh5!  gxh5  32.f4  Will put Black on the edge of a disaster, as now the h5-pawn is a huge issue.  32...Be8  33.Nd3  Now, the e5-pawn is weak.  33...Kd6  34.f5±  Next, White brings the knight to h5 with Nf2-h1-g3, for example, wins the e5-pawn and the game.  31.fxg4  And h4-h5! comes next. }
30. Bxb5 axb5 31. Nd1 Na6 32. Nc3
{ Of course, White is happy to improve the knight and make the Black one sit on c7 tied to the defense of the pawn. }
32... Nc7 33. f4 { Now, time to challenge the center. } 33... exf4+ 34. Kxf4
Kd6 35. g4 { White grabs all the space he can. } 35... Ne6+ 36. Ke3 Nc7 37. Ne2
Ne6 38. Ng1 h5
{ Black should have waited, but this move only creates a weakness on h5. } 39.
gxh5 gxh5 40. Nf3 Ke7 41. e5 f5 42. Ng1 Nf8 43. Kf4 Ke6
{ 43...Ng6+  44.Kg5  Nxe5  45.Kxf5  was still somehow holdable for Black, even though the position afte  45...Nc4  46.Nf3  Nxa3  47.Nd4  Kd6  48.Kg5  looks very scary, as the h-pawn will run really fast. }
44. Nf3 Ng6+ 45. Kg5 Nxe5 46. Nd4+ Kd5 47. Nxf5
{ Now, White is picking up the h-pawn, while Black is too slow when it comes to generate queenside counterplay. }
47... Kc4 48. Nd6+ Kb3 49. Nxb5 Ka4 50. Na7 b5 51. Nxb5 Kxb5 52. Kxh5
{ And White easily promoted his pawns. } 52... Ka4 53. Kg5 Kxa3 54. b5 Kb4 55.
b6 Kc5 56. b7 Nd7 57. h5 Kc6 58. h6 Kxb7 59. h7 Ne5 60. Kf6
{ And Black resigned. While the endgame was certainly holdable, if you want to become a better player, you need to learn to play these positions out till the end as opposed to shaking hands and agreeing to a draw on move 20. Admittedly, this was the most challenging line against our repertoire! }
