[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Double Fianchetto: Model Games"]
[Black "Yuriy Kuzubov vs. Shamsiddin Vokhidov, Chess.com, 2020 "]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3
{ The opening moves were, again, different, but soon enough it transposed to the position we are looking for. }
4... g6 5. b3 Bg7 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Rc1 b6
{ Here, White could just keep developing with Be2, but instead he immediately went for a position with hanging pawns. }
8. d4 cxd4 9. exd4 d5 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O
{ The only con here is that the knight belongs on d2 rather than c3, because from there it helps support the c4-pawn, which would come handy after ...dxc4, ...Rc8 and ...Na5. }
11... Rc8 12. Re1 dxc4
{ 12...e6  Seems to be a safer way to play, keeping the tension, because Black can capture at absolutely any moment, while the early ...dxc4 allows for additional opportunities for White, such as d4-d5. }
13. bxc4 Na5 14. Ne5
{ 14.Ba3!  would have been the best move, unexpectedly targeting the e7-pawn!  14...Nxc4?   14...Re8  15.c5!?  with an interesting position, where White gives up the d5-square, but gains space and opportunities like Bb5, Ne5 and potentially c5-c6.  15.Bxc4  Rxc4  16.Bxe7+-  and White wins an exchange. }
14... Nd7 { Now, the White center is under pressure. } 15. Nd5 Bxd5
{ 15...e6!  16.Ne3  Nxe5  17.dxe5  Qc7  would have kept Black's position under control, while also harming White's structure.  18.Ng4⩱  Even though, White still does have some play on the kingside. }
16. cxd5
{ Now, the White knight is about to land on c6, causing severe damage. } 16...
Rxc1 17. Bxc1 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Bxe5
{ Black wins a pawn, but his knight on a5 is very passive, and White's d5-pawn is restricting Black severely. }
19. Bf3 Qd6 20. Qe2 Rc8
{ Black takes advantage of the weakness of White's first rank.   20...Bf6  Would have also kept Black's position under control. }
21. Qa6 { 21.Qxe5??  Qxe5  22.Rxe5  Rxc1+  And Black wins. } 21... Rc7 22. g3
Qf6 23. Kg2 Nc4 24. Bh6
{ White keeps creating some small threats, keeping Black's pieces at bay. The extra pawn doesn't make much difference for the time being. }
24... g5 { Black thought he was about to win the piece, but after } 25. Bxg5
Qxg5 26. Re4
{ White took advantage of the fact the c4-knight is in danger, and so is the Black queen on the g-file. }
26... Qc1 27. Be2 { The extra piece will be done no matter what! } 27... Nd6
28. Rxe5 Qd2 29. Bf3 Qd4 30. Qe2
{ White consolidated the position and is about to start creating threats on the kingside. }
30... Kf8 31. Rh5 Kg7 32. Rh4 Qc3 33. Be4 { Time to challenge the Black king! }
33... f5 34. Bxf5
{ 34.Bb1!  Would have been better, keeping a pair of minor pieces and preparing Qh5 or Rh5. }
34... Nxf5 35. Qg4+ Kf6 36. Rh5
{ White is a piece down, but he has some very strong pressure, and here Black needed to defend with only moves. }
36... Qc2
{ 36...Qd3!  Would have maintained equality, since not only does Black defend the knight, but he also attacks the d5-pawn. }
37. Qf4
{ 37.Qg5+!  Ke5  38.Qf4+!  Kf6  39.g4!  Would have been winning, but in time trouble, White did not notice that idea. }
37... Rc4 38. Qg5+ Kf7
{ Black needed to dare to go ...Ke5!, but now he is getting mated. } 39. Rxh7+
Ke8 40. Qg8+ Kd7 41. Qe6+ Kc7 42. d6+ { The Black king finds its fate. } 42...
Nxd6 43. Qxe7+ Kc6 44. Qd7+ Kc5 45. Rh5+ Kb4 46. Qxd6+ Ka4 47. Qd7+ Kb4 48.
Rb5+ Kc3 49. Rb3+ { And Black resigned as he's losing the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Dutch"]
[Black "2...g6 - the early kingside aggression #1"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the chapter on the Anti-Dutch! I've spent a long time thinking about what to recommend against this opening, and that is primarily not because it's hard to fight for the advantage, but because we don't want to engage in highly theoretical opening discussions, and even more importantly, we do not want to be move-ordered into some variation that does not fit with the rest of this repertoire. Therefore, I hope you forgive me for not sticking to the pure b2-b3 plans which are typical of the rest of the course! However, I am really excited to show you the sideline that I find very promising, yet really easy to learn and relatively little-known. }
1. Nf3 f5 2. d4
{ Okay, we seem to be going for the main setups with d4! But, we won't enter the mainline theory, don't worry. Now, most people who play the Dutch would stay flexible with ... Nf6, but it's certainly also worth checking out such moves as 2...g6, 2...e6 and 2...d5. }
2... g6
{ This is a cheeky attempt to get to the Leningrad Dutch type of positions without allowing for our beloved Bg5 move. }
3. h4
{ Unfortunately, not developing the knight to f6 early on, combined with playing ...g7-g6, has been lately known for being very dangerous due to this typical h-pawn thrust. }
3... Nf6 4. h5
{ Many of you have likely seen this exchange sacrifice idea before in many various scenarios, it is very strong here as well. We are looking to take on g6, of course, or possibly go h5-h6!, forcing Black to take some action. }
4... Nxh5 5. Rxh5 gxh5 6. e4 Bg7 7. Nh4
{ Black can also try to go 7...e6, but in that case we still take on h5, play Nc3 and castle long, intending to enjoy the long-term weakness of the Black king. No need to come up with anything brilliant, let's play simple chess! }
7... O-O 8. Nxf5
{ White doesn't need to urgently win anything back or hurry in any way. Instead, we are just looking to dominate the kingside, maybe exchange the g7-bishop, win the h5-pawn, bring the bishop in with Bg5 or Bh6, the other pieces with Bd3, Nc3, O-O-O, Rh1 and slowly but surely slaughter Black. }
8... Rxf5 9. exf5
{ Is a possible way for Black to play, but now he's not even any material up, the h5-pawn is about to be lost and his king safety is terrible. By the way, it's rather hard to get the queenside pieces out, too. }
9... Qe8 { The only move to avoid losing h5. } 10. Bc4+ Kh8 11. Nc3
{ We will just get the rest of the pieces in the game by means of Be3, Qf3, O-O-O, Rh1, etc, leaving Black with an ugly passive position with a weak kingside. Take your time! }
*

