1. Nf3 f5 2. d4
{ Okay, we seem to be going for the main setups with d4! But, we won't enter the mainline theory, don't worry. Now, most people who play the Dutch would stay flexible with ... Nf6, but it's certainly also worth checking out such moves as 2...g6, 2...e6 and 2...d5. }
2... Nf6
{ The most flexible and common move which doesn't define yet what variation of the Dutch Black is going for. }
3. Bg5
{ This line is not as good as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Bg5  variation @@StartBracket@@which, by the way, alongside with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  is what I consider to be some of the best ways of tackling the Dutch@@EndBracket@@, but it's still a very promising choice. This sideline has been successfully used by the likes of Aronian, Andreikin, Dubov, Harikrishna, Vitiugov and many other very strong players, which will hopefully ensure you a bit more of its soundness. We are potentially looking to spoil the Black structure by capturing on  f6  . Or maybe we'll just play e2-e3 next, having gotten our dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain! }
3... Ne4
{ This Trompovsky-style move is certainly also worth considering, but it will result in Black having a very hard time developing the rest of his pieces, as we are about to see. }
4. h4
{ Importantly, it's very difficult for Black to develop his kingside without compomising it heavily. That's why most people go ... c7-c5 here, looking for the Trompowvsky-style counterplay. }
4... c5 5. e3
{ Of course, such moves as ...d7-d6 or ...g7-g6 will transpose to positions similar to the ones discussed above. }
5... Qb6 { A very principled move, aimed at winning the b2-pawn. } 6. Nbd2 Qxb2
7. Rb1
{ Black should definitely abstain from taking on a2 as well, as that would only enable White to win even more time with Bc4. }
7... Qa3 8. Rb3 Qa5 9. Bc4
{ I would dare to say Black is entirely lost here. Why is that? Well, unlike in the usual Trompowsky, his structure and king safety have been severely compromised by the move ...f7-f5. That's why he'll find it very difficult to get out, whereas White can proceed with O-O, Qa1!? and develop a ton of pressure on the a1-h8 diagonal as well as on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
9... e6 10. d5 Be7 11. O-O
{ Black cannot castle as the e7-bishop would hang, while after } 11... Nxg5 12.
Nxg5 O-O 13. e4
{ White is entirely winning, because the Black queenside simply cannot come out, while we are about to go either e4-e5 followed by d5-d6!, completely paralyzing Black, or Qh5 and Rg3, checkmating his helpless king. }
