{ The most popular move by far, which you will be likely seeing in 65-70% of the games. }
4. Nbd2
{ White is about to take advantage of the pinned f6-knight by pushing e2-e4! }
4... d5
{ Results in Stonewall positions where White got the dark-squared bishop out to g5, as opposed to having it stuck on a1, which is certainly a major improvement.  The knight on d2 is not placed passively, because after Nf3-e5 it can go to f3, supporting the other horse! }
5. e3 Be7 6. c4 c6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Ne4 9. Bxe7
{ Exchanging the dark-squared bishops highlights the weakness of the opponent's dark squares. }
9... Qxe7 10. Rc1 Nd7 11. Qc2
{ We will slowly prepare our queenside play, while Black cannot do much for the following reasons:1@@EndBracket@@ Moving the d7-knight allows for Ne5! followed by f2-f3!, kicking the e4-knight away.2@@EndBracket@@ Playing ...b7-b6 weakens the c-file, enabling White to immediately take on d5, force ...cxd5, which as we know is an undesirable way for Black to recapture, and invade on the c-file.3@@EndBracket@@ Playing ...g7-g5 is premature, we react by either invading on e5 with the knight or going Be2!, Ne1! and f2-f3, kicking the e4-knight away and re-routing the f3-knight to d3. }
