{ Welcome to the chapter on the Anti-Dutch! I've spent a long time thinking about what to recommend against this opening, and that is primarily not because it's hard to fight for the advantage, but because we don't want to engage in highly theoretical opening discussions, and even more importantly, we do not want to be move-ordered into some variation that does not fit with the rest of this repertoire. Therefore, I hope you forgive me for not sticking to the pure b2-b3 plans which are typical of the rest of the course! However, I am really excited to show you the sideline that I find very promising, yet really easy to learn and relatively little-known. }
1. Nf3 f5 2. d4
{ Okay, we seem to be going for the main setups with d4! But, we won't enter the mainline theory, don't worry. Now, most people who play the Dutch would stay flexible with ... Nf6, but it's certainly also worth checking out such moves as 2...g6, 2...e6 and 2...d5. }
2... Nf6
{ The most flexible and common move which doesn't define yet what variation of the Dutch Black is going for. }
3. Bg5
{ This line is not as good as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Bg5  variation @@StartBracket@@which, by the way, alongside with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  is what I consider to be some of the best ways of tackling the Dutch@@EndBracket@@, but it's still a very promising choice. This sideline has been successfully used by the likes of Aronian, Andreikin, Dubov, Harikrishna, Vitiugov and many other very strong players, which will hopefully ensure you a bit more of its soundness. We are potentially looking to spoil the Black structure by capturing on  f6  . Or maybe we'll just play e2-e3 next, having gotten our dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain! }
3... e6
{ The most popular move by far, which you will be likely seeing in 65-70% of the games. }
4. Nbd2
{ White is about to take advantage of the pinned f6-knight by pushing e2-e4! }
4... Be7
{ Black unpins the knight, while also developing and getting ready to castle. }
5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4
{ Transposes to the famous variation @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  e6  4.e4  fxe4  5.Nxe4  Be7  6.Bxf6  Bxf6  7.Nf3  . For one, I would highly recommend seeing the game Lasker-Thomas if you hadn't yet, that should give a couple ideas on how dangerous Black's position is. We won't go too deep in theory here, but we certainly will look at a couple model variations to see what dangers Black is facing. }
7... O-O 8. Bd3
{ Black has a few main issues here. For one, the fact his f6-knight and f-pawn are missing mean the kingside is weakened, and just like in the very famous game Lasker-Thomas, he could easily find himself checkmated after Ne5, Qh5, etc. However, it's also worth saying lack of the f-pawn makes it difficult for him to develop his queenside without weakening the pawn structure considerably, since moving the d-pawn would make the e6-pawn extremely weak. }
8... Nc6 { The most common move. } 9. c3 d5 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Qe2
{ We are taking the e5-square under control, preventing the opponent from carrying out the liberating ... e6-e5 break. }
11... Bd7 12. O-O Rae8 13. Bb5
{ One of the key ideas in this position. We are looking to get rid of the c6-knight, which is a useful piece that is supporting the e5-break, and leave Black with that terrible passive light-squared bishop versus our drop-dead gorgeous knight on e5. Always keep in mind the following basic positional rule: while trading pieces, look not just at what you trade, but also at what remains on the board! }
13... Nb8
{ Is a much smarter choice, looking to get rid of the weak bishop, but White doesn't need to oblige. }
14. Rae1
{ We don't mind trading if that enables us to massively activate our pieces. }
14... Bxb5 15. Qxb5 b6 16. Re3
{ Now Black's b8-knight is stuck and we're about to follow up with Rfe1, maybe Qa4 to attack a7, etc. Black has no active moves at all. }
*

