1. Nf3 f5 2. d4
{ Okay, we seem to be going for the main setups with d4! But, we won't enter the mainline theory, don't worry. Now, most people who play the Dutch would stay flexible with ... Nf6, but it's certainly also worth checking out such moves as 2...g6, 2...e6 and 2...d5. }
2... Nf6
{ The most flexible and common move which doesn't define yet what variation of the Dutch Black is going for. }
3. Bg5
{ This line is not as good as the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Bg5  variation @@StartBracket@@which, by the way, alongside with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  f5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bg5  is what I consider to be some of the best ways of tackling the Dutch@@EndBracket@@, but it's still a very promising choice. This sideline has been successfully used by the likes of Aronian, Andreikin, Dubov, Harikrishna, Vitiugov and many other very strong players, which will hopefully ensure you a bit more of its soundness. We are potentially looking to spoil the Black structure by capturing on  f6  . Or maybe we'll just play e2-e3 next, having gotten our dark-squared bishop outside the pawn chain! }
3... e6
{ The most popular move by far, which you will be likely seeing in 65-70% of the games. }
4. Nbd2
{ White is about to take advantage of the pinned f6-knight by pushing e2-e4! }
4... Be7
{ Black unpins the knight, while also developing and getting ready to castle. }
5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. e4 O-O 7. Bd3 d5
{ Black is immediately challenging the White center. } 8. exf5 exf5 9. O-O
{ Now, the main goal would be fighting for the weak e5-square. } 9... Nc6
{ Black takes it under control, while also attacking the d4-pawn. } 10. c3 Qd6
{ Black keeps developing while taking e5 under even more control. } 11. Qc2
{ We connect rooks while also winning a tempo by attacking that f5-pawn and making Black weaken his position a bit more. }
11... g6 12. Rfe1
{ White now grabs the only open file, preparing to invade on e5. } 12... Bd7
{ Black also gets some of last pieces out. } 13. Bb5
{ Intending to potentially exchange on c6 and then play Ne5!, looking to dominate the bishops with the knights. Alternatively, we could use the d3-square for other purposes, as we are about to see. }
13... Rae8 14. a4
{ We grab a bit more space on the queenside, while also protecting our b5-bishop just in case. }
14... a6 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nb3
{ Another very cool idea. Now the knight is going to c5 and to d3! Potentially, it could make a lot of sense to continue with Nc5 and a4-a5!, squeezing the Black queenside and fixing the weakness on b7, which Black would need to guard for a long time. }
16... Rxe1+ 17. Nxe1
{ Is also very good for us, as now we'll anyway proceed with the same plan of re-routing the knights to e5. Now that the f-pawn is no longer blocked, Nd3 and f2-f4! certainly becomes a very attractive plan. }
