[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Dutch: Model Games"]
[Black "Viktor Kortschnoj vs. Richard Meulde, Brussels, 1987rs "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 e6 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4
{ Black has a few main issues here. For one, the fact his f6-knight and f-pawn are missing mean the kingside is weakened, and just like in the very famous game Lasker-Thomas, he could easily find himself checkmated after Ne5, Qh5, etc. However, it's also worth saying lack of the f-pawn makes it difficult for him to develop his queenside without weakening the pawn structure considerably, since moving the d-pawn would make the e6-pawn extremely weak. }
7... d5 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Now, the e5-square is very weak, and the c8-bishop isn't great, either, to put it mildly. }
9. c3 Nd7 10. Qd2
{ White is getting the queen out, potentially preparing the move Qe3 that would help control the e5-square better, or maybe even preparing Qg5!?, trading queens and going for a better endgame. Importantly, Black would like to carry out the ...e6-e5 break, which would get him rid of the backward e6-pawn and free up his terrible c8-bishop. However, he cannot do that yet. }
10... O-O { 10...e5?  11.dxe5  Nxe5??  12.Qe3+-  And White wins a piece. } 11.
Qe3 Qh6
{ Black trades queens, which is a terrible positional mistake. White's advantage was long-lasting, and still is, so the trade hurts Black considerably. }
12. Qxh6 gxh6 13. Be2
{ 13.Bd3  Would have been an even better square for the bishop, perhaps, as the b1-h7 diagonal offers it a lot of opportunities. }
13... a6
{ 13...c5  14.Bb5!?  a6  15.Bxd7  Bxd7  16.Ne5±  Is exactly the type of position White wants, as his minor piece is much better. }
14. O-O c5
{ Black went ...a7-a6 to make sure White won't ever have an opportunity to go Bb5 and take on d7, achieving a position with a perfect minor piece, the knight on e5, versus Black's awful light-squared bishop. }
15. Rfe1 b6 16. Bd3 Rf6
{ Black could also play ...Nf6, defending the pawn that way, but that'd involve giving up the e5-square, which is also not great. }
17. Re3 Ra7 18. g3 Rc7 19. Rae1
{ White is happy to double on the only semi-open file and put more pressure on that e6-pawn, of course. }
19... Rf7 20. Nh4 Nf8 21. f4
{ White takes even more space, while also restricting the e6-pawn even more. }
21... Rf6 22. Nf3 Bd7 23. Ne5 h5
{ 23...Bc8?  Defends the a6-pawn, but loses something else.  24.Ng4+-  And the h6-pawn is lost. In fact, so is the exchange, because ...Rf7 runs into Nxh6 with a fork. }
24. Bxa6
{ Now, White is also a pawn up. The rest was easy for the legendary grandmaster. }
24... c4 25. Nxd7 Rxd7 26. Bc8 { A very original way to attack the e6-pawn! }
26... Rd6 27. f5 exf5 28. Re5
{ White temporarily sacrifices a pawn and now picks the f-pawn. } 28... Rf7 29.
Bxf5 Ng6 30. Be6 Nxe5 31. Rxe5 Rxe6 32. Rxe6
{ And Black resigned, as he's losing all of his pawns. Either Rxb6, or Re5! would pick another pawn or two, and, of course, Black has no counterplay. A great example of how we kill Black in this variation! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Dutch: Model Games"]
[Black "Dmitry Gurevich vs. Antonio Gual Pascual, London, 1994"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 e6 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. Bxf6 Bxf6 6. e4 O-O 7. Bd3 d5
{ The most principled reaction to our repertoire. } 8. exf5 exf5 9. O-O
{ Now, the main goal would be fighting for the weak e5-square. } 9... Nc6 10.
c3
{ White protects the d4-pawn, while also preventing ideas like ...Nb4, leaving the Black knight and bishop out of business. }
10... Qd6 { Black keeps developing while taking e5 under even more control. }
11. Qc2
{ We connect rooks while also winning a tempo by attacking that f5-pawn and making Black weaken his position a bit more. }
11... Bd7
{ Black also gets some of the last pieces out. In the repertoire, we discuss 11...g6 followed by 12...Bd7, which in this case transposed. }
12. Rfe1 g6 13. b4
{ In the course, the move Bb5 is suggested, aimed at taking on c6 and installing the knight on the weak e5-square. In this case, however, White chose to go for the space grabbing, which also makes a lot of sense. }
13... Rae8 14. b5 Na5 15. Nb3 Nc4
{ Black keeps the knights, but now the White one comes to c5, causing havoc.   15...Nxb3  16.axb3⩲  Would result in a position where White has opportunities both on the a-file, due to the weakness of the a7-pawn, as well as in the center, as c3-c4 is coming whenever White wants. }
16. a4 c6 17. Nc5 cxb5
{ 17...Bc8  18.Bxc4!  dxc4  19.Qa2!  Would cause a lot of issues, since the only way to defend the pawn is  19...Qd5!  but then  20.bxc6±  Forces Black to take with the pawn, which gives White a fantastic pawn structure and opportunities to keep challenging the weak c4-pawn later with Nd2! Importantly, the Black bishops are terrible. }
18. Rxe8 Bxe8 19. Nxb7 Qb6 20. Nc5 Be7
{ 20...bxa4  21.Nxa4⩲  Would be a terrible position for Black, because White has an outpost on c5. Additionally, the a7-pawn is very weak, and we'll keep attacking it with moves like Qa2. Furthermore, the bishops are still very inactive. }
21. Qa2
{ 21.Qe2!  Bxc5  22.axb5!  Would have been a very nice temporary piece sac. The point here is that if  22...Bd6?  23.Ra6!  Qc7  24.Bxc4!  dxc4  25.Qe6+!  And White gets his piece back with a winning position. But, of course, this is a very weird and unusual tactic, which is really hard to find. }
21... Bxc5 22. dxc5 Qxc5 23. axb5 Rf7
{ 23...Bxb5  24.Bxc4  Bxc4  25.Qxa7  Would have resulted in a drawn endgame, even though after  25...Qxa7  26.Rxa7  Black still needs to work for a draw, as the seventh rank has been severely weakened, and White can try playing the dark squares with f2-f4, maybe Nd4 or Ne5, maybe Kf2-e3-d4-e5, etc. }
24. Bxc4 dxc4 25. Re1 Bxb5 26. Re5
{ White is a pawn down, but Black's king is rather weak, so he still needs to be accurate. }
26... Qd6 27. Qe2 a6 28. Nd4 f4 29. h4
{ While the position is still balanced, White is doing his best to develop the initiative. Now, h4-h5! is about to dismantle the Black king even more. }
29... f3 { This desperate pawn sacrifice doesn't result in anything good. } 30.
Nxf3 Qd3 31. Qe1 Bc6 { This just wastes time. } 32. Nd4 Ba4 33. Kh2 h6 34. Rd5
{ Now, Rd8 followed by Ne6 or Qe5 is unstoppable, and the Black queen on d3 is completely cut off and unable to help, so he had to resign instead of getting mated. A nice positional game that highlighted the potential of White's pieces on the weak dark squares, if you ask me! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Anti-Dutch: Model Games"]
[Black "Dmitry Andreikin vs. Pavel Potapov, Sochi, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 f5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bg5 e6 4. Nbd2 d5
{ With this move, Black prevents e2-e4, however the arising position is not great for him: essentially, it's a bad Queen's Gambit, where ...f7-f5 is just a weakening move. I am not of the highest opinion of the Dutch overall, but Stonewall makes valid points against the Fianchetto variation, for example, where the g2-bishop is bad and restricted. Here, instead, we get all the perks of the Queen's Gambit Declined and no disadvantages, while Black gets a weakened e5-square. }
5. e3
{ The knight on d2 is not placed passively, because after Nf3-e5 it can go to f3, supporting the other one. }
5... Be7 6. c4 c6 7. Bd3
{ White challenged the center and keeps making normal developing moves. Later, we can grab space with b2-b4 and start active actions on the queenside. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 9. cxd5
{ Attention! This is a VERY important positional idea in the Stonewall positions. It is crucial to take this pawn exactly now. Why so? Because Black wants to play ...exd5 to get a semi-open e-file and enhance the activity of his c8-bishop. However, now he cannot do that as taking with the e-pawn would lose him the f5-pawn, which means we get to open the c-file and get a free ride on the queenside! }
9... cxd5 { 9...exd5  10.Bxf5+-  Wins a pawn. } 10. Rc1 Nb6 11. Nb3
{ White is looking to use the c5-square. } 11... Na4 12. Qe2 Bd7 13. Bf4
{ We can now play for the following advantages:1@@EndBracket@@ The square on e5 is weak.2@@EndBracket@@ We can fight for the c-file by using both our rooks and our powerful f4-bishop.3@@EndBracket@@ The a4-knight is completely out of play.4@@EndBracket@@ The d7-bishop is rather inactive and has no prospects. }
13... Rc8 14. Ne5 a6 15. Rxc8 Bxc8 16. Rc1 Bd6 17. h3 Qe7 18. Qc2
{ Of course, having the only open file on the board, White happily grabs it with all the major pieces he can. }
18... Nb6
{ 18...Bd7  19.Nxd7  Qxd7  20.Bxd6  Qxd6  21.Na5+-  Would be very strong for White, because the b7-pawn is hanging, and so is the a4-knight, so White wins a pawn. }
19. Nc5
{ White is dominating the board. Next, we can either challenge the vulnerable b6-knight with Qb3 and see if Black has a decent response, or grab even more space with b2-b4, a2-a4, etc. }
19... Bxe5 20. Bxe5 { Now, the bishop pair adds to our advantages. } 20... Nbd7
21. Bf4 Nxc5 22. Qxc5 Qxc5 23. Rxc5
{ The endgame is hopeless for Black due to our ownership of the c-file, bishop pair and his terrible c8-bishop. Now, the goal is to grab even more space on the queenside and activate the king, if possible. }
23... Nd7 24. Rc3 Nb6 25. Kf1 { Time for the king to come into action. } 25...
Na4 26. Rc2 Nb6 27. b3
{ White restricts the opponent's knight and prevents it from ever coming to c4. Using pawns to restrict the opponent's minor pieces is one of the main ways of converting the bishop pair. }
27... Na8 { Look at that 'beautiful' knight. } 28. a4 b6 29. b4
{ Of course, White takes all the space he can! } 29... Bb7 30. b5
{ This move completely restricts the b7-bishop and fixes the weakness on b6. }
30... a5 31. g4
{ Given the Black minor pieces are stuck on the queenside and won't ever get out, White can now create problems on the kingside as well. }
31... g6 32. Kg2 Kf7 33. Kg3 { Time to use those weak dark squares. } 33... Rh8
{ 33...Rc8  34.Be5!  And White is completely winning after the rook trade, too, as he's effectively two pieces up, because the Black knight is stuck, while the Black bishop is useless.  34...Rxc2  35.Bxc2  Ke7  36.Kf4!  Kf7  37.Kg5!  The king comes to h6!  37...Kg8  38.Kf6+-  And that's the end. }
34. Be5 Rg8 35. h4 { White does all he wants on the kingside. } 35... Bc8 36.
f3 Bb7 37. Kf4 h6 38. h5 g5+ 39. Kg3
{ Now that White managed to provoke the weakening pawn move, there is no way to hold that f5-pawn. Black is forced to open the f-file or give up pawns. }
39... Bc8 40. Rc6 Bd7 41. Rd6 Ke7 42. gxf5
{ Black resigned, as taking back loses the h-pawn. Look at those pieces, they've never made themselves useful!  This is, undoubtedly, one of my favorite model games in this course. }
